144
00:11:45,620 --> 00:11:46,902
[SPEAKER_24]: So that's what he's saying.

145
00:11:47,042 --> 00:11:49,785
[SPEAKER_39]: And you think that tonight could be a game-changer then in the election, do you?

146
00:11:49,846 --> 00:12:07,228
[SPEAKER_24]: I think any opportunity that Rishi Sunak has to engage with the public, he does really well, because he is ultimately not just a nice guy, but he's somebody that is deeply driven by core values, and you can see that in the policies he's putting forward in a very detailed manifesto, and he will take the opportunity tonight to set that out.

147
00:12:07,208 --> 00:12:08,149
[SPEAKER_39]: looking forward to that.

148
00:12:08,169 --> 00:12:31,140
[SPEAKER_39]: Thank you very much indeed Gareth Davis there speaking to us as we build up to the main event because there's just over three weeks to go until the election and of course there is, just take a quick time check, just around 18 minutes to go until our main event here kicks off, the Leaders event here on Sky News where you will get the chance to directly compare

149
00:12:31,120 --> 00:12:33,164
[SPEAKER_39]: both Rishi Sunak and Sir Keir Starmer.

150
00:12:33,184 --> 00:12:42,080
[SPEAKER_39]: And that matters because although it might look like, according to the polls, that Keir Starmer's cruising to a comfortable win, there are always some tough tests on the road to Downing Street.

151
00:12:42,140 --> 00:12:44,385
[SPEAKER_39]: And one of them, of course, comes tonight.

152
00:12:44,465 --> 00:12:47,470
[SPEAKER_39]: We can talk now to the Shadow Health Secretary, Wes Streeting.

153
00:12:47,490 --> 00:12:49,554
[SPEAKER_39]: Good to have you here in Grimsby.

154
00:12:50,215 --> 00:12:52,740
[SPEAKER_39]: So, I mean, I guess it's Keir Starmer's to lose tonight, is it?

155
00:12:53,142 --> 00:12:59,310
[SPEAKER_21]: Well, the great thing about tonight's format is that as well as questions from Beth, we also get questions from the audience.

156
00:12:59,891 --> 00:13:02,314
[SPEAKER_21]: These are the sorts of interactions Keir really enjoys.

157
00:13:02,374 --> 00:13:05,018
[SPEAKER_21]: And it's a chance for us to do two things, I think.

158
00:13:05,598 --> 00:13:10,725
[SPEAKER_21]: One is to get across Labour's message of change and how we'll bring it about in terms of the policies.

159
00:13:11,346 --> 00:13:18,295
[SPEAKER_21]: And secondly, to make sure that people get the message that the only way this country gets the change we need is if people vote for it.

160
00:13:18,475 --> 00:13:20,398
[SPEAKER_21]: And I think it's been extraordinary

161
00:13:20,378 --> 00:13:23,301
[SPEAKER_21]: this morning to hear a senior cabinet minister.

162
00:13:23,669 --> 00:13:30,315
[SPEAKER_21]: effectively throwing the election, saying, oh, the Conservatives, oh, we've got to just try and stop this landslide Labour majority.

163
00:13:30,455 --> 00:13:44,689
[SPEAKER_21]: I mean, this is a deliberate calculation to try and persuade millions of people who are undecided, but in fact the whole country who haven't yet voted, that change is inevitable and therefore you don't have to go and vote for it.

164
00:13:44,849 --> 00:13:46,691
[SPEAKER_21]: And, you know, our message is simple.

165
00:13:46,871 --> 00:13:48,012
[SPEAKER_21]: The country needs change.

166
00:13:48,052 --> 00:13:51,415
[SPEAKER_21]: We will only get that change if people vote for change by voting Labour.

