[SPEAKER_43]: Many people, I think, in this room will agree with that.

532
00:40:15,088 --> 00:40:21,076
[SPEAKER_43]: That's why many people also suspect when you're in power, you will raise more tax.

533
00:40:21,096 --> 00:40:22,858
[SPEAKER_43]: And I want you to be honest here, please.

534
00:40:23,299 --> 00:40:28,566
[SPEAKER_43]: You've said you'll raise specific taxes on profits on oil and gas companies, closing loopholes on...

535
00:40:28,546 --> 00:40:32,472
[SPEAKER_43]: tax avoidance, tax reform on private equity, VAT on private schools.

536
00:40:32,933 --> 00:40:35,557
[SPEAKER_43]: But the Tories say you will go further.

537
00:40:35,958 --> 00:40:36,980
[SPEAKER_43]: They're right, aren't they?

538
00:40:37,280 --> 00:40:37,701
[SPEAKER_43]: You will.

539
00:40:38,021 --> 00:40:42,929
[SPEAKER_31]: Well, the first thing I'd say is the Tories are in no position to lecture anyone about tax rises.

540
00:40:43,290 --> 00:40:46,555
[SPEAKER_31]: We've got the highest tax burden.

541
00:40:48,222 --> 00:40:50,685
[SPEAKER_31]: For 70 years.

542
00:40:50,705 --> 00:40:54,850
[SPEAKER_31]: And I think that working people shouldn't pay more tax and we will not raise their tax.

543
00:40:54,870 --> 00:40:57,433
[SPEAKER_31]: OK. What we need to do is get the economy going.

544
00:40:57,613 --> 00:41:04,060
[SPEAKER_31]: There's a reason that taxes have gone up so much in recent years, and that's because the economy is flatlining.

545
00:41:04,380 --> 00:41:05,962
[SPEAKER_31]: We have to address that problem.

546
00:41:05,982 --> 00:41:17,976
[SPEAKER_31]: And tomorrow, our manifesto is a plan for growth, a detailed plan of the first steps we will do in government to get our economy working so that living standards go up and we have the money we need for our public services.

547
00:41:17,956 --> 00:41:21,883
[SPEAKER_43]: So no tax rises of any kind in the next Parliament under Labour?

548
00:41:22,383 --> 00:41:30,477
[SPEAKER_31]: No tax rises for working people, and nothing in our manifesto requires tax rises over and above those that we have specifically set out.

549
00:41:30,777 --> 00:41:32,540
[SPEAKER_31]: So no tax rises in the next Parliament?

550
00:41:32,841 --> 00:41:35,225
[SPEAKER_31]: No tax rises needed in the plans in our manifesto.

551
00:41:35,265 --> 00:41:36,006
[SPEAKER_31]: In the plans?

552
00:41:36,307 --> 00:41:38,671
[SPEAKER_31]: No tax rises for working people.

553
00:41:38,751 --> 00:41:40,133
[SPEAKER_31]: That's income tax.

554
00:41:40,113 --> 00:41:41,657
[SPEAKER_31]: National Insurance, a VAT.

555
00:41:41,677 --> 00:41:43,723
[SPEAKER_43]: OK, so you're not ruling out.

556
00:41:44,064 --> 00:41:50,563
[SPEAKER_43]: I just decode that for you guys, because when a politician says no plans, it does mean I might.

557
00:41:51,004 --> 00:41:52,589
[SPEAKER_43]: Well, Beth, I'm not...

558
00:41:52,609 --> 00:41:53,872
[SPEAKER_43]: I've done this a bit.

559
00:41:53,892 --> 00:41:54,173
[SPEAKER_43]: It does.

560
00:41:57,410 --> 00:42:03,948
[SPEAKER_31]: Look, I'm not going to sit here tonight and write the next five years' worth of budgets, and you wouldn't take me seriously if I did.

561
00:42:04,430 --> 00:42:06,054
[SPEAKER_31]: What I will say is that we will not raise...

562
00:42:06,074 --> 00:42:08,260
[SPEAKER_43]: But you've ruled out income tax and you've ruled out NI.

563
00:42:08,461 --> 00:42:08,982
[SPEAKER_43]: Yes, because...

564
00:42:09,002 --> 00:42:11,148
[SPEAKER_43]: So you are ruling out some tax rises, but not all.

565
00:42:11,169 --> 00:42:12,432
[SPEAKER_31]: Because I think working people are paying too much...

566
00:42:12,412 --> 00:42:16,341
[SPEAKER_31]: OK. And I think paying far too much tax in recent years.

567
00:42:16,361 --> 00:42:20,971
[SPEAKER_43]: OK, what I'm hearing is you're... And I think that has made the cost-of-living crisis ten times worse than it would otherwise be.

568
00:42:20,991 --> 00:42:27,506
[SPEAKER_43]: OK, what I'm hearing is that you are not ruling out some tax rises, and you've talked about working...

569
00:42:28,228 --> 00:42:31,956
[SPEAKER_43]: But I have said that none of our... We're going to unveil our manifesto tomorrow.

570
00:42:31,936 --> 00:42:33,198
[SPEAKER_31]: No tax surprises.

571
00:42:33,298 --> 00:42:33,959
[SPEAKER_31]: I got it.

572
00:42:34,119 --> 00:42:37,364
[SPEAKER_31]: NI, VAT... No need to raise tax on the plans we're setting out.

573
00:42:37,384 --> 00:42:37,584
[SPEAKER_31]: I got it.

574
00:42:37,884 --> 00:42:41,389
[SPEAKER_43]: But the point is, is there are other taxes that affect working people, aren't there?

575
00:42:41,409 --> 00:42:42,551
[SPEAKER_43]: What about council tax?

576
00:42:42,611 --> 00:42:45,695
[SPEAKER_43]: I'm sure many people are worried about that, yeah?

577
00:42:45,716 --> 00:42:49,421
[SPEAKER_43]: The Labour Party in Wales launched a review of council tax banding.

578
00:42:49,781 --> 00:42:52,425
[SPEAKER_43]: Are you going to rule out a review in England too?

579
00:42:52,405 --> 00:42:55,572
[SPEAKER_31]: Well, council taxes is too high for many people.

580
00:42:55,632 --> 00:42:56,755
[SPEAKER_31]: It's been going up.

581
00:42:56,795 --> 00:42:58,158
[SPEAKER_31]: It went up again this year.

582
00:42:58,198 --> 00:43:01,165
[SPEAKER_31]: But that's because the government lost control of the economy.

583
00:43:01,225 --> 00:43:03,811
[SPEAKER_43]: So you're not going to do a review of the council tax bans?

584
00:43:04,071 --> 00:43:08,943
[SPEAKER_43]: I'm really trying to... You know they were last revalued when I was a teenager, and I'm really old now.

585
00:43:09,283 --> 00:43:09,604
[SPEAKER_31]: Yeah.

586
00:43:11,288 --> 00:43:14,513
[SPEAKER_31]: Beth, you're pushing me over and over again on tax.

587
00:43:15,194 --> 00:43:17,859
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm not wanting to raise tax.

588
00:43:17,879 --> 00:43:19,642
[SPEAKER_31]: I think people are taxed too much already.

589
00:43:19,802 --> 00:43:22,947
[SPEAKER_31]: What I want to do, my central mission, is to grow the economy.

590
00:43:22,967 --> 00:43:30,580
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm not going to apologise for that, because I genuinely think that if you don't grow the economy, then you're taxing an ever-diminishing return.

591
00:43:30,560 --> 00:43:33,386
[SPEAKER_43]: I mean, people here will be worried about fuel duty, right?

592
00:43:33,847 --> 00:43:34,028
[SPEAKER_43]: Yeah.

593
00:43:34,128 --> 00:43:36,673
[SPEAKER_43]: The Conservatives have frozen it since 2011.

594
00:43:37,014 --> 00:43:40,161
[SPEAKER_43]: If you unfroze it, you could get 5 to 6 billion quid.

595
00:43:40,462 --> 00:43:41,985
[SPEAKER_43]: That's a tax on working people.

596
00:43:42,386 --> 00:43:44,270
[SPEAKER_43]: Yes, and that's why every single...

597
00:43:44,310 --> 00:43:45,733
[SPEAKER_31]: So you are going to freeze it?

598
00:43:45,713 --> 00:43:49,058
[SPEAKER_31]: Every single budget, we have supported the freeze on fuel duty.

599
00:43:49,078 --> 00:43:52,202
[SPEAKER_31]: And you will continue to do that as Prime Minister if you would win?

600
00:43:52,643 --> 00:43:56,208
[SPEAKER_31]: We have to concentrate on growing the economy.

601
00:43:56,328 --> 00:44:01,936
[SPEAKER_31]: On fuel duty, that has to be decided budget by budget, but my track record is... Do you think he's going to do it or not?

602
00:44:01,957 --> 00:44:02,577
[SPEAKER_31]: I don't know.

603
00:44:03,278 --> 00:44:08,506
[SPEAKER_31]: We've supported the cap on fuel duty every single time it's come up.

604
00:44:08,526 --> 00:44:09,207
[SPEAKER_31]: OK.

605
00:44:10,182 --> 00:44:11,665
[SPEAKER_31]: I want to do things differently.

606
00:44:11,785 --> 00:44:16,834
[SPEAKER_31]: If we just do things in the same way as we've done for the last 14 years, we'll end up in the same mess.

607
00:44:16,854 --> 00:44:18,396
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm not prepared to do that.

608
00:44:18,416 --> 00:44:28,955
[SPEAKER_31]: This election is an election about change, about doing things differently, about growing the economy, and making sure we create the wealth so this country can run our public service.

609
00:44:29,175 --> 00:44:29,235
[SPEAKER_31]: OK.

610
00:44:29,315 --> 00:44:32,641
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm going to have one more go, and then we can end it.

611
00:44:32,661 --> 00:44:33,102
[SPEAKER_31]: No, no, no.

612
00:44:33,082 --> 00:44:34,644
[SPEAKER_31]: I do want to finish this.

613
00:44:34,664 --> 00:44:36,206
[SPEAKER_31]: I ran a public service for five years.

614
00:44:36,647 --> 00:44:39,130
[SPEAKER_31]: I ran a public service in the austerity years.

615
00:44:39,551 --> 00:44:41,333
[SPEAKER_31]: I know what it means to be a public servant.

616
00:44:41,654 --> 00:44:43,837
[SPEAKER_31]: I absolutely care about our public services.

617
00:44:43,857 --> 00:44:49,645
[SPEAKER_31]: My wife works in the NHS, my mum worked in the NHS, and I know what it means to the NHS.

618
00:44:50,186 --> 00:44:53,230
[SPEAKER_31]: So I absolutely want our public services to function.

619
00:44:53,270 --> 00:44:55,974
[SPEAKER_43]: I believe in them, I've worked in them for five years.

620
00:44:56,114 --> 00:44:59,899
[SPEAKER_43]: I've heard the specifics on certain taxes, but to be clear,

621
00:44:59,879 --> 00:45:08,494
[SPEAKER_43]: council tax revaluation, which could put up council tax bills, fuel tax, you know, you're not being explicit on it and that is your prerogative.

622
00:45:08,534 --> 00:45:10,097
[SPEAKER_43]: But what about capital gains tax?

623
00:45:10,117 --> 00:45:14,264
[SPEAKER_43]: That's the tax you pay when you sell a valuable asset like shares or a second home.

624
00:45:14,665 --> 00:45:20,656
[SPEAKER_43]: If you made capital gains tax the same level as income tax, you could raise £14 billion a year.

625
00:45:21,036 --> 00:45:23,220
[SPEAKER_43]: That must be attractive to you if you want to repair

626
00:45:23,200 --> 00:45:25,163
[SPEAKER_31]: That is not in our manifesto.

627
00:45:25,183 --> 00:45:26,806
[SPEAKER_31]: That is not a choice that we are making.

628
00:45:26,846 --> 00:45:28,128
[SPEAKER_31]: It will not be unveiled tomorrow.

629
00:45:28,148 --> 00:45:32,975
[SPEAKER_31]: There's no surprises in our manifesto, because our manifesto is a manifesto for growth.

630
00:45:33,296 --> 00:45:39,045
[SPEAKER_31]: It's about how we tackle our planning laws, how we get the skills for our young people, how we set up great British energy.

631
00:45:39,085 --> 00:45:46,036
[SPEAKER_31]: This is going to be a publicly owned energy company so that taxpayers' money that goes into investing in energy comes back to the taxpayer.

632
00:45:46,056 --> 00:45:46,837
[SPEAKER_31]: OK, so, Kit, the reason I...

633
00:45:46,857 --> 00:45:48,600
[SPEAKER_43]: These are the ideas that we have that I want to make.

634
00:45:48,580 --> 00:45:51,123
[SPEAKER_43]: to put on the table to grow our economy for the future.

635
00:45:51,203 --> 00:45:59,054
[SPEAKER_43]: Just the reason I'm asking you this is I don't know if you remember that interview we did in September 2021 when I asked you about wealth taxes.

636
00:45:59,114 --> 00:46:04,421
[SPEAKER_43]: You said people who earn their money from properties, dividends, stock shares, they should be looked at.

637
00:46:04,481 --> 00:46:10,329
[SPEAKER_43]: We need to look at a range of options, and that includes the way people earn their money.

638
00:46:10,369 --> 00:46:12,111
[SPEAKER_43]: So you were looking at wealth taxes.

639
00:46:12,391 --> 00:46:13,873
[SPEAKER_43]: You are looking at wealth taxes.

640
00:46:13,893 --> 00:46:15,195
[SPEAKER_31]: It's OK to say it.

641
00:46:15,175 --> 00:46:16,898
[SPEAKER_31]: We're not looking at wealth taxes.

642
00:46:17,058 --> 00:46:19,482
[SPEAKER_31]: Nothing in our manifesto will require tax flows.

643
00:46:19,502 --> 00:46:20,284
[SPEAKER_31]: You'll see it for yourself.

644
00:46:20,304 --> 00:46:21,826
[SPEAKER_31]: But you won't rule it out.

645
00:46:22,027 --> 00:46:23,309
[SPEAKER_31]: Look, let's test this tomorrow.

646
00:46:23,369 --> 00:46:27,877
[SPEAKER_31]: I invite all of you, please, if you get the chance tomorrow afternoon, have a look at the manifesto.

647
00:46:27,917 --> 00:46:29,399
[SPEAKER_31]: We're launching it tomorrow morning.

648
00:46:29,560 --> 00:46:32,104
[SPEAKER_31]: And you will see for yourselves that every single thing

649
00:46:32,084 --> 00:46:35,447
[SPEAKER_31]: is fully costed, fully funded, and they do not involve tax.

650
00:46:35,467 --> 00:46:36,928
[SPEAKER_31]: So we're going round and round in circles.

651
00:46:36,948 --> 00:46:39,230
[SPEAKER_31]: That's the document that we're going to launch tomorrow.

652
00:46:39,310 --> 00:46:41,893
[SPEAKER_43]: If it's not ruled out in the manifesto, it's on the table.

653
00:46:41,933 --> 00:46:43,394
[SPEAKER_43]: So let's just carry on.

654
00:46:43,935 --> 00:46:45,956
[SPEAKER_43]: What about you personally?

655
00:46:46,016 --> 00:46:50,420
[SPEAKER_43]: You earned £128,000 in tax last year.

656
00:46:50,761 --> 00:46:53,303
[SPEAKER_43]: You paid £44,000 in income tax.

657
00:46:53,643 --> 00:46:55,865
[SPEAKER_43]: That puts you in the top 2% to 3% of earners.

658
00:46:56,266 --> 00:46:59,148
[SPEAKER_43]: Would you personally be happy to pay more tax?

659
00:46:59,168 --> 00:47:00,049
[SPEAKER_43]: Yes, of course.

660
00:47:00,029 --> 00:47:00,670
[SPEAKER_31]: OK.

661
00:47:00,730 --> 00:47:02,773
[SPEAKER_31]: I've always paid my tax in full.

662
00:47:03,955 --> 00:47:11,265
[SPEAKER_31]: But, you know, and I accept I earn a lot of money in the job I am now in, but when I grew up, my dad was a toolmaker.

663
00:47:11,285 --> 00:47:12,928
[SPEAKER_31]: He worked in a factory.

664
00:47:12,948 --> 00:47:13,429
[SPEAKER_31]: It's true.

665
00:47:13,709 --> 00:47:18,496
[SPEAKER_31]: My mum was a nurse and, actually, we couldn't make ends meet, which actually isn't a laughing matter.

666
00:47:18,516 --> 00:47:19,538
[SPEAKER_31]: We couldn't make ends meet.

667
00:47:19,858 --> 00:47:21,000
[SPEAKER_31]: We couldn't pay our bills.

668
00:47:21,360 --> 00:47:23,303
[SPEAKER_31]: I know what it feels like.

669
00:47:23,283 --> 00:47:26,308
[SPEAKER_31]: to feel anxious about the next bill which you can't pay.

670
00:47:26,528 --> 00:47:32,619
[SPEAKER_31]: And what I have recognised is a lot of people today are in precisely the same position as I was in.

671
00:47:34,161 --> 00:47:40,912
[SPEAKER_31]: Politics is about your policies, of course it is, but it's also about who do you have in your mind's eye when you make your decisions.

672
00:47:41,213 --> 00:47:43,777
[SPEAKER_31]: Who are you thinking about when you make your decisions?

673
00:47:44,098 --> 00:47:46,442
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm thinking about the people who are struggling with their bills.

674
00:47:46,742 --> 00:47:48,565
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm thinking about working people who deserve

675
00:47:48,545 --> 00:47:49,707
[SPEAKER_31]: I want to come on...

676
00:47:49,727 --> 00:47:58,319
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm thinking about working people who want their living standards to go up, and our plan for the country, which we will set out tomorrow, is a confident, hopeful manifesto for change.

677
00:47:58,339 --> 00:48:00,922
[SPEAKER_43]: I don't want to interrupt, but I'm nearly finished.

678
00:48:00,942 --> 00:48:05,248
[SPEAKER_43]: Because I want to come on to something that matters to working people, and that's child benefits.

679
00:48:05,749 --> 00:48:08,072
[SPEAKER_43]: At the moment, just to remind you all, if...

680
00:48:08,052 --> 00:48:14,462
[SPEAKER_43]: you probably know, there's a two-child benefit cap for families, some of whom have more children than that.

681
00:48:14,782 --> 00:48:17,767
[SPEAKER_43]: This is hitting some of the poorest and most vulnerable in Britain.

682
00:48:18,107 --> 00:48:25,939
[SPEAKER_43]: The Resolution Foundation think tank says families cannot claim about £3,200 per extra child a year.

683
00:48:26,279 --> 00:48:33,310
[SPEAKER_43]: Dozens of organisations, from the Trade Union Congress to the Church of England to the former Prime Minister, Gordon Brown, have called for it to go.

684
00:48:33,650 --> 00:48:34,352
[SPEAKER_43]: Will you scrap it?

685
00:48:34,392 --> 00:48:36,034
[SPEAKER_43]: Is that in your manifesto tomorrow?

686
00:48:36,014 --> 00:48:37,337
[SPEAKER_31]: No, it isn't.

687
00:48:37,357 --> 00:48:51,466
[SPEAKER_31]: And it's been a really difficult decision for all the reasons you outlined, because the last Labour government had a laser focus on dealing with child poverty and did a huge amount of good work, including Sure Start and the programmes that were set up.

688
00:48:51,486 --> 00:48:52,268
[SPEAKER_43]: It cost £1.3 billion.

689
00:48:52,248 --> 00:49:01,781
[SPEAKER_43]: All of those wealth taxes I was talking about, all the 5% on top earners, you could do that, and you could do that policy £1.3 billion a year.

690
00:49:02,202 --> 00:49:04,866
[SPEAKER_31]: Huge damage has been done to our economy under this government.

691
00:49:05,286 --> 00:49:06,048
[SPEAKER_31]: Huge damage.

692
00:49:06,829 --> 00:49:14,880
[SPEAKER_31]: And if we are able to come into government and form a government, we're probably going to inherit a broken economy, a broken NHS, broken public services, in fact,

693
00:49:14,860 --> 00:49:15,961
[SPEAKER_31]: I've broken everything.

694
00:49:15,981 --> 00:49:19,145
[SPEAKER_31]: OK. And I'm not going to make promises that I can't keep.

695
00:49:19,165 --> 00:49:25,913
[SPEAKER_31]: So I'm doing, actually, a difficult thing, which is saying to the electorate, saying to you now, I can't do something... You accept these are choices.

696
00:49:25,933 --> 00:49:27,175
[SPEAKER_31]: ..which I know the benefits of it.

697
00:49:27,235 --> 00:49:28,737
[SPEAKER_31]: We need to deal with child poverty.

698
00:49:28,757 --> 00:49:29,017
[SPEAKER_00]: It's choices.

699
00:49:29,037 --> 00:49:31,059
[SPEAKER_31]: And we will have a strategy for child poverty.

700
00:49:31,360 --> 00:49:36,666
[SPEAKER_31]: But I think people are fed up with politicians who, before the election, say, we'll do everything.

701
00:49:36,646 --> 00:49:38,448
[SPEAKER_31]: And then after the election, they don't deliver.

702
00:49:38,468 --> 00:49:46,599
[SPEAKER_31]: So I've taken a decision, which is before the election, I'm going to tell you what we can't do, even though some of these things are good things to do.

703
00:49:46,699 --> 00:49:49,603
[SPEAKER_43]: So Kit, I'm going to interrupt now because I'm nearly out of time.

704
00:49:50,985 --> 00:49:52,828
[SPEAKER_43]: It would lift one million kids out of poverty.

705
00:49:52,928 --> 00:49:55,431
[SPEAKER_43]: And just to be clear, you're choosing not to do it.

706
00:49:55,411 --> 00:49:56,432
[SPEAKER_31]: It's a difficult choice.

707
00:49:56,452 --> 00:49:59,176
[SPEAKER_31]: We will have an anti-child poverty strategy, of course we will.

708
00:49:59,196 --> 00:50:01,359
[SPEAKER_31]: The last Labour government did, we will have one.

709
00:50:01,699 --> 00:50:06,706
[SPEAKER_31]: But the easiest thing in the world, it's what Rishi Sunak is doing, is to simply say you can have everything.

710
00:50:06,726 --> 00:50:11,692
[SPEAKER_31]: Unfunded commitments, unfunded promises, that's what got us into this problem in the first place.

711
00:50:11,933 --> 00:50:15,357
[SPEAKER_31]: And working people are paying the price with higher bills, their mortgages.

712
00:50:15,617 --> 00:50:19,242
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm not prepared to have a Labour government ever make that mistake again.

713
00:50:26,377 --> 00:50:31,708
[SPEAKER_43]: Zakir, some people feel that they don't really know you.

714
00:50:31,788 --> 00:50:35,936
[SPEAKER_43]: Some people say you change your mind all the time, and I hinted at some of that.

715
00:50:36,397 --> 00:50:38,761
[SPEAKER_43]: Some people say you're boring and stiff.

716
00:50:38,842 --> 00:50:41,407
[SPEAKER_43]: Tell me something...

717
00:50:41,427 --> 00:50:41,567
[SPEAKER_43]: Cheers!

718
00:50:41,587 --> 00:50:46,697
[SPEAKER_43]: Tell me something more about yourself that will change people's minds.

719
00:50:46,677 --> 00:50:51,107
[SPEAKER_31]: Well, look, all my life I've believed in service.

720
00:50:51,127 --> 00:50:57,561
[SPEAKER_31]: That is why I worked in Northern Ireland with the Police Service of Northern Ireland to ensure it had the confidence of both communities.

721
00:50:57,621 --> 00:50:59,024
[SPEAKER_31]: I thought that was a really important thing.

722
00:50:59,385 --> 00:51:02,712
[SPEAKER_31]: That's why I worked and headed up the Crown Prosecution Service.

723
00:51:02,692 --> 00:51:03,553
[SPEAKER_31]: public service.

724
00:51:04,094 --> 00:51:09,001
[SPEAKER_31]: That's why I came into politics when I finished as Director of Public Prosecutions and wondered what to do next.

725
00:51:09,061 --> 00:51:19,637
[SPEAKER_31]: My wife was ringing adverts in the papers about, you know, well-paid lawyers' jobs, and I said, no, I want to serve my country, which is why at a late stage, actually, I came into politics to serve my country.

726
00:51:19,617 --> 00:51:21,640
[SPEAKER_43]: your wife not keen for you to do this?

727
00:51:21,680 --> 00:51:22,901
[SPEAKER_43]: No, she wasn't at all.

728
00:51:23,022 --> 00:51:31,793
[SPEAKER_31]: She thought it would be far better to continue being a lawyer on a reasonable salary and not have all of the, you know, challenges that you get as a politician.

729
00:51:31,813 --> 00:51:36,960
[SPEAKER_31]: But I was clear in my mind I wanted to come into politics because I wanted to serve my country.

730
00:51:36,980 --> 00:51:39,664
[SPEAKER_31]: And I've waited nine years now in opposition.

731
00:51:39,704 --> 00:51:49,557
[SPEAKER_31]: I've worked four and a half years to put my party back in a position where I can put it before you and others, the voters, as the only party that's got a plan for the future.

732
00:51:49,537 --> 00:51:54,786
[SPEAKER_43]: If you become Prime Minister in three weeks' time, what do you fear the most?

733
00:51:56,229 --> 00:52:00,416
[SPEAKER_31]: Oh, the only real fear, I suppose, I have is for my family.

734
00:52:01,057 --> 00:52:06,728
[SPEAKER_31]: I've got a boy who is just turning 16, he's 15 and three quarters.

735
00:52:06,768 --> 00:52:08,190
[SPEAKER_31]: I've got a girl who's 13.

736
00:52:08,491 --> 00:52:10,654
[SPEAKER_31]: These are really difficult ages for children.

737
00:52:10,915 --> 00:52:12,658
[SPEAKER_31]: If they're under five, it would probably be easier.

738
00:52:12,638 --> 00:52:15,181
[SPEAKER_31]: If they were 20 or over, it'd be easier.

739
00:52:15,722 --> 00:52:19,407
[SPEAKER_31]: And my only fear, really, is the impact it's going to have on them.

740
00:52:19,427 --> 00:52:22,732
[SPEAKER_31]: That's why we never name them in public, never have a photo shoot with them.

741
00:52:23,092 --> 00:52:29,801
[SPEAKER_31]: I want them to be able to walk to school and have their own lives, unaffected as much as I can by what I'm doing.

742
00:52:29,821 --> 00:52:32,364
[SPEAKER_31]: And I don't fear the big decisions.

743
00:52:32,645 --> 00:52:35,369
[SPEAKER_31]: In fact, I relish the chance to change our country.

744
00:52:35,729 --> 00:52:38,673
[SPEAKER_31]: And on the first day, I want to start on our first steps.

745
00:52:38,993 --> 00:52:41,717
[SPEAKER_31]: I want you to see the change that we can bring about.

746
00:52:41,697 --> 00:52:47,593
[SPEAKER_31]: But my only fear is actually, and the only thing that sort of keeps me up at night is worrying about my children.

747
00:52:48,074 --> 00:52:49,498
[SPEAKER_31]: Any doubt that you're up to the job?

748
00:52:49,759 --> 00:52:50,421
[SPEAKER_31]: No, not at all.

749
00:52:50,461 --> 00:52:51,905
[SPEAKER_31]: I've led different organisations.

750
00:52:51,945 --> 00:52:52,787
[SPEAKER_31]: I've changed them.

751
00:52:53,229 --> 00:52:56,297
[SPEAKER_31]: And I want the opportunity to change the country.

752
00:53:01,373 --> 00:53:05,980
[SPEAKER_17]: on to the future and this growth process that you're going to go through?

753
00:53:06,000 --> 00:53:15,594
[SPEAKER_31]: Well thank you for raising that because we've got, what we've done is we've set out the big change that we want to make but also what the first steps will be that we can do on day one.

754
00:53:15,614 --> 00:53:23,466
[SPEAKER_31]: So the day after the election I want to start on our first step stabilising the economy to make sure we never go through a cost of living crisis like this before.

755
00:53:23,446 --> 00:53:27,192
[SPEAKER_31]: Set up Great British Energy so we can keep your bills down.

756
00:53:27,212 --> 00:53:33,022
[SPEAKER_31]: I want to start on the 40,000 appointments each and every week that we need to get the waiting list down in our NHS.

757
00:53:33,142 --> 00:53:36,267
[SPEAKER_31]: OK. We will be doing that the morning after the election.

758
00:53:36,487 --> 00:53:37,970
[SPEAKER_43]: I don't mean to interrupt.

759
00:53:37,990 --> 00:53:39,212
[SPEAKER_43]: Well, I do mean to interrupt.

760
00:53:39,472 --> 00:53:41,035
[SPEAKER_43]: We've got to get to the audience questions.

761
00:53:41,075 --> 00:53:41,716
[SPEAKER_43]: Thank you, sir.

762
00:53:43,038 --> 00:53:45,683
[SPEAKER_43]: Thank you so much for coming and doing that with us.

763
00:53:45,823 --> 00:53:47,946
[SPEAKER_43]: And now you've got some harder questions from this lot.

764
00:53:48,507 --> 00:53:49,549
[SPEAKER_43]: I'm looking forward to it.

765
00:53:49,569 --> 00:53:49,629
[SPEAKER_43]: OK.

766
00:53:49,649 --> 00:53:50,230
[SPEAKER_43]: Thank you.

767
00:53:56,487 --> 00:54:00,354
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, there you are, the audience questions getting underway a little bit early.

768
00:54:00,754 --> 00:54:04,280
[SPEAKER_33]: You heard what Sir Keir Starmer had to say to Beth Rigby there.

769
00:54:04,781 --> 00:54:14,057
[SPEAKER_33]: He said he was certain that Labour would lose that 2019 election, but he has put the party back in the service of working people, putting the country first, he said.

770
00:54:14,037 --> 00:54:22,086
[SPEAKER_33]: He also insisted there's nothing in the party's manifesto, launched tomorrow morning, that would require them to raise taxes for working people.

771
00:54:22,706 --> 00:54:29,234
[SPEAKER_33]: He said the party isn't considering wealth taxes, with all of their commitments fully costed.

772
00:54:29,934 --> 00:54:34,960
[SPEAKER_33]: And he also said that he would personally be happy to pay more tax.

773
00:54:34,980 --> 00:54:39,825
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, now it is your turn to put your questions to the Labour leader.

774
00:54:42,151 --> 00:54:42,772
[SPEAKER_43]: Right.

775
00:54:43,353 --> 00:54:47,038
[SPEAKER_43]: Now, our first question comes from Sharon, who is from Grimsby.

776
00:54:47,078 --> 00:54:48,119
[SPEAKER_43]: Sharon, where are you?

777
00:54:48,660 --> 00:54:49,241
[SPEAKER_43]: There she is.

778
00:54:49,281 --> 00:54:50,343
[SPEAKER_43]: Take it away, Sharon.

779
00:54:50,783 --> 00:54:54,869
[SPEAKER_10]: So as someone born and bred in Grimsby, I'm proud of our town.

780
00:54:54,889 --> 00:55:06,285
[SPEAKER_10]: But it has some of the most disadvantaged areas in the country, with high levels of child poverty, inadequate social housing, and increasing numbers having to use food banks.

781
00:55:06,265 --> 00:55:14,906
[SPEAKER_10]: How will Labour address these inequalities and improve outcomes for the most disadvantaged residents both here and across the UK?

782
00:55:15,327 --> 00:55:16,410
[SPEAKER_10]: Well, thank you for that.

783
00:55:21,166 --> 00:55:30,721
[SPEAKER_31]: And I've been to Grimsby a number of times now, and my strong impression is that you're absolutely right about the challenges that people are facing.

784
00:55:30,802 --> 00:55:41,198
[SPEAKER_31]: And we've had discussions about that even this morning with various groups around Grimsby, the very real challenges, the cost of living crisis, the challenge that people have with schooling and with health.

785
00:55:41,519 --> 00:55:43,562
[SPEAKER_31]: But what I've also been struck by

786
00:55:43,542 --> 00:55:52,938
[SPEAKER_31]: is the pride and ambition that people have in their place and in Grimsby and the sense that they want a government that matches their own ambition.

787
00:55:53,339 --> 00:55:59,469
[SPEAKER_31]: I think the way to do that is to ensure that the government works with local communities, local businesses.

788
00:55:59,750 --> 00:56:03,576
[SPEAKER_31]: We need a growth plan for Grimsby, which your fingerprints are on,

789
00:56:03,556 --> 00:56:14,287
[SPEAKER_31]: I don't want someone standing in Whitehall and Westminster looking at a map and deciding what they think is best for Grimsby, because I think with people with skin in the game are the people who make the best decisions.

790
00:56:14,567 --> 00:56:20,674
[SPEAKER_31]: So I want a government that partners with you, drives through the change, creates the conditions for businesses to thrive.

791
00:56:20,914 --> 00:56:27,741
[SPEAKER_31]: If that means changing the planning rules so we get our roads sorted out, the congestions and the potholes are an absolute nightmare,

792
00:56:27,721 --> 00:56:30,086
[SPEAKER_31]: create the conditions for businesses to thrive.

793
00:56:30,447 --> 00:56:47,063
[SPEAKER_31]: I was really struck, the time before last I was up here, I was looking at some of the offshore wind turbines and talking to apprentices here in Grimsby, brilliant young people, by the way, who all lived within about 20 or 30 minutes of where they were working.

794
00:56:47,043 --> 00:56:50,107
[SPEAKER_31]: they were very skilled going out to maintain those wind turbines.

795
00:56:50,127 --> 00:56:51,109
[SPEAKER_31]: We need more of that.

796
00:56:51,169 --> 00:56:57,598
[SPEAKER_31]: The supply chains for that should be in and around here, so they're not other parts of the country or abroad.

797
00:56:57,938 --> 00:57:01,503
[SPEAKER_31]: That's the sort of challenge that I relish.

798
00:57:01,543 --> 00:57:11,076
[SPEAKER_31]: It's what I want to do on day one, which is to get to this place where I can roll up my sleeves, work with you, have the respect to listen to what you're saying here,

799
00:57:11,056 --> 00:57:16,002
[SPEAKER_31]: not sit a long, long way away and make decisions about what should happen in Grimsby.

800
00:57:16,022 --> 00:57:23,651
[SPEAKER_31]: And I'm convinced that if there's a government that has ambition that matches the people of Grimsby, we can move this forward very, very quickly.

801
00:57:23,811 --> 00:57:36,466
[SPEAKER_31]: And I can see some of the green shoots there already, because some of the work that's going on... We had a roundtable this morning with some of the businesses, the community groups here in Grimsby, that were telling me not just the struggles and the challenges, but what they were doing about it.

802
00:57:36,886 --> 00:57:40,050
[SPEAKER_31]: I want to roll up my sleeves and work with them and to say the government

803
00:57:40,030 --> 00:57:40,832
[SPEAKER_31]: is on your side.

804
00:57:40,852 --> 00:57:43,820
[SPEAKER_31]: That would be a massive difference to the last 14 years.

805
00:57:50,459 --> 00:57:51,943
[SPEAKER_10]: How is it all going to be funded?

806
00:57:52,163 --> 00:57:54,971
[SPEAKER_10]: If taxes are not going up, how are you going to fund it?

807
00:57:54,991 --> 00:57:55,693
[SPEAKER_31]: We need to put...

808
00:57:59,335 --> 00:58:01,881
[SPEAKER_31]: We need to put money and resource into Grimsby.

809
00:58:01,901 --> 00:58:03,966
[SPEAKER_31]: We need resource decision-making to come.

810
00:58:04,266 --> 00:58:11,082
[SPEAKER_31]: So we have to be bold enough in government to release that so that there's more power here in Grimsby.

811
00:58:11,122 --> 00:58:12,565
[SPEAKER_31]: They're difficult things to do.

812
00:58:12,605 --> 00:58:15,572
[SPEAKER_31]: Governments haven't done that in the past, but we have to do that.

813
00:58:15,552 --> 00:58:17,474
[SPEAKER_31]: Some of it we can do straightaway.

814
00:58:17,514 --> 00:58:28,427
[SPEAKER_31]: The potholes that are driving everyone mad because their cars get damaged, it costs them hundreds of pounds, and if you need your car or your van for work, it's a complete nightmare because you can't actually use it.

815
00:58:28,447 --> 00:58:29,488
[SPEAKER_31]: That can be done straightaway.

816
00:58:29,508 --> 00:58:31,070
[SPEAKER_31]: We've been setting out our plans on that.

817
00:58:31,450 --> 00:58:34,614
[SPEAKER_31]: Childcare came up this morning in a discussion I was having.

818
00:58:35,375 --> 00:58:38,498
[SPEAKER_31]: We want to create 100,000 new places for childcare.

819
00:58:38,518 --> 00:58:44,445
[SPEAKER_31]: This is at 3,000 nurseries around schools, because I think primary schools are the best place for nurseries.

820
00:58:44,425 --> 00:58:52,995
[SPEAKER_31]: So that means children get the opportunity to develop the skills that they need before reception year, which isn't happening in the way it should at the moment, in my view.

821
00:58:53,456 --> 00:59:00,705
[SPEAKER_31]: But also, parents and carers can go back into work, which many of them want to do, and that then helps the local economy.

822
00:59:00,825 --> 00:59:01,806
[SPEAKER_31]: There are things that we can do.

823
00:59:01,826 --> 00:59:02,887
[SPEAKER_31]: It goes back to my point.

824
00:59:03,188 --> 00:59:06,872
[SPEAKER_31]: We've got first steps, the things we want to do, the day we get into government.

825
00:59:07,133 --> 00:59:14,061
[SPEAKER_31]: If we're elected in, that I want to start, and I've said to my Shadow Cabinet, I want you to prepare months ago

826
00:59:14,041 --> 00:59:15,204
[SPEAKER_31]: for the first day in government.

827
00:59:15,224 --> 00:59:17,430
[SPEAKER_31]: I don't want you picking up the phone on day one.

828
00:59:17,610 --> 00:59:18,613
[SPEAKER_31]: I want to know you're ready.

829
00:59:18,793 --> 00:59:26,653
[SPEAKER_31]: And that's why I'm so confident that we can do this as soon as we get the chance, if we do get a chance, to bring about the change this country so desperately needs.

830
00:59:26,673 --> 00:59:26,954
[SPEAKER_43]: OK.

831
00:59:27,315 --> 00:59:27,656
[SPEAKER_43]: Thank you.

832
00:59:27,676 --> 00:59:29,461
[SPEAKER_43]: I've got so many questions to look at them all.

833
00:59:29,962 --> 00:59:30,223
[SPEAKER_43]: That's right.

834
00:59:30,243 --> 00:59:30,784
[SPEAKER_43]: I've got so many questions.

835
00:59:31,844 --> 00:59:34,246
[SPEAKER_43]: And the next one comes from Jonathan.

836
00:59:34,286 --> 00:59:35,988
[SPEAKER_43]: He's a junior doctor from Leeds.

837
00:59:36,028 --> 00:59:37,449
[SPEAKER_43]: Jonathan, there he is.

838
00:59:37,509 --> 00:59:37,909
[SPEAKER_43]: Thank you.

839
00:59:38,570 --> 00:59:44,915
[SPEAKER_11]: So, I've been on strike because I earn more money per hour working part-time as a university student than I do as a newly qualified doctor.

840
00:59:45,776 --> 00:59:53,603
[SPEAKER_11]: Abysmal pay conditions and morale mean that more of my colleagues than ever are planning their exit, and I worry about what this means for my loved ones and the wider general public.

841
00:59:54,744 --> 00:59:57,686
[SPEAKER_11]: Scotland and Wales have decided that they can pay NHS doctors fairly.

842
00:59:58,207 --> 01:00:00,889
[SPEAKER_11]: How and when will you commit to doing the same in England?

843
01:00:01,105 --> 01:00:03,749
[SPEAKER_31]: Well, we won't be able to do anything unless we win the election.

844
01:00:03,790 --> 01:00:06,134
[SPEAKER_31]: We've obviously only been in opposition so far.

845
01:00:06,394 --> 01:00:11,262
[SPEAKER_31]: I have been frustrated, if I'm honest, that these strikes have gone on as long as they have gone on.

846
01:00:11,743 --> 01:00:13,807
[SPEAKER_31]: The strikes are very bad for patients.

847
01:00:13,827 --> 01:00:15,650
[SPEAKER_31]: People are very anxious about the strikes.

848
01:00:15,990 --> 01:00:18,515
[SPEAKER_31]: I don't think doctors want to be on strike.

849
01:00:18,975 --> 01:00:25,847
[SPEAKER_31]: As I said earlier, my wife works in one of the big London hospitals, so I know first-hand and relayed every night,

850
01:00:25,827 --> 01:00:27,990
[SPEAKER_31]: pressure that NHS staff are under.

851
01:00:28,050 --> 01:00:32,736
[SPEAKER_31]: It's been unrelenting during Covid, unrelenting now because of waiting lists.

852
01:00:32,756 --> 01:00:45,574
[SPEAKER_31]: So what we would do is instead of arguing about who gets in the room first to negotiate with the doctors, we would roll up our sleeves in a grown-up way, get in the room and settle this dispute so that patients can get the care they need.

853
01:00:45,554 --> 01:00:51,064
[SPEAKER_31]: Doctors can get back to work, and the country can move forward, because we can't go on like this anymore.

854
01:00:51,084 --> 01:00:57,214
[SPEAKER_31]: And the sooner we have a bit of grown-up politics in this, the better, I think, because we absolutely need to move forward as a country.

855
01:00:57,234 --> 01:01:00,019
[SPEAKER_43]: Are you going to pay them more?

856
01:01:00,657 --> 01:01:02,440
[SPEAKER_43]: Are you going to pay them more?

857
01:01:02,480 --> 01:01:05,024
[SPEAKER_31]: Because you've said that you won't meet their pay claims.

858
01:01:05,044 --> 01:01:06,667
[SPEAKER_31]: Well, the doctors say they want 35%.

859
01:01:06,767 --> 01:01:09,071
[SPEAKER_31]: And I've had to say... No, we don't.

860
01:01:09,091 --> 01:01:11,014
[SPEAKER_31]: We want a path to pay restoration.

861
01:01:11,034 --> 01:01:11,735
[SPEAKER_31]: No, I get that.

862
01:01:11,795 --> 01:01:14,700
[SPEAKER_31]: But, again, I want to be straight about this.

863
01:01:15,361 --> 01:01:16,943
[SPEAKER_11]: Our pay has been cut in real terms.

864
01:01:16,963 --> 01:01:17,825
[SPEAKER_11]: And we're looking to make that...

865
01:01:17,845 --> 01:01:18,666
[SPEAKER_11]: The 35% thing is...

866
01:01:18,646 --> 01:01:24,373
[SPEAKER_31]: pay progression conditions, and all of that could be negotiated on the 35%.

867
01:01:25,474 --> 01:01:28,838
[SPEAKER_31]: I don't think we can afford that as a country because of the damage that's been done to the economy.

868
01:01:29,039 --> 01:01:30,701
[SPEAKER_31]: I don't want to pretend to you that we can.

869
01:01:30,761 --> 01:01:37,429
[SPEAKER_31]: I'll sit down in a room and negotiate and find a way through this, just as has happened in other countries, because it's intolerable that we go on.

870
01:01:37,850 --> 01:01:43,016
[SPEAKER_31]: But I'm not going to start with the proposition that we simply accept whatever the other side is asking for.

871
01:01:43,056 --> 01:01:44,317
[SPEAKER_31]: That's not how negotiations go.

872
01:01:44,337 --> 01:01:46,700
[SPEAKER_31]: And you wouldn't respect a government if it operated that way.

873
01:01:46,720 --> 01:01:48,062
[SPEAKER_31]: And other people in other...

874
01:01:48,042 --> 01:01:52,655
[SPEAKER_31]: Walks of life have got constraints and pressures on their lives that have to be balanced.

875
01:01:52,976 --> 01:01:53,939
[SPEAKER_31]: But will we be grown?

876
01:01:54,380 --> 01:02:00,717
[SPEAKER_31]: All that's happened this year, and it's so frustrating, is the government say, we want a deal, but we won't go into the room first.

877
01:02:00,738 --> 01:02:01,660
[SPEAKER_31]: It's for the doctors to...

878
01:02:01,680 --> 01:02:03,064
[SPEAKER_31]: They've never wanted a deal, have they?

879
01:02:03,044 --> 01:02:11,199
[SPEAKER_31]: I think you may be right, and the fact they've left this to the election without fixing it and just booted it the other side of the election, I think is disgraceful.

880
01:02:11,239 --> 01:02:15,707
[SPEAKER_31]: It doesn't do you any good, it doesn't do patients any good, and it doesn't do the country any good.

881
01:02:15,927 --> 01:02:23,601
[SPEAKER_31]: But we've had a government that's chaotic, that's divided, has broken just about everything they've touched.

882
01:02:23,621 --> 01:02:27,448
[SPEAKER_31]: I don't know a period in history, and you will all think about this,

883
01:02:27,428 --> 01:02:32,254
[SPEAKER_31]: Almost everything is now in a worse state than when they started in government.

884
01:02:32,555 --> 01:02:35,258
[SPEAKER_31]: And this is not about Labour or Tory.

885
01:02:35,779 --> 01:02:41,567
[SPEAKER_31]: If you leave your country in a worse state than when you came into government, you should be booted out.

886
01:02:47,094 --> 01:02:47,154
[SPEAKER_32]: OK.

887
01:02:47,174 --> 01:02:47,715
[SPEAKER_32]: I've got so many questions.

888
01:02:50,024 --> 01:02:52,088
[SPEAKER_43]: I've got so many questions.

889
01:02:52,148 --> 01:02:54,513
[SPEAKER_43]: The next one comes from Hussein from London.

890
01:02:54,573 --> 01:02:55,655
[SPEAKER_43]: Where is he?

891
01:02:55,675 --> 01:02:56,557
[SPEAKER_56]: There you go, please.

892
01:02:57,659 --> 01:02:57,760
[SPEAKER_56]: Hi.

893
01:02:58,200 --> 01:03:07,459
[SPEAKER_56]: So I'm an average working parent from London, and I send my daughter to a private school, which in turn saves the government about £7,500 per year.

894
01:03:07,439 --> 01:03:13,385
[SPEAKER_56]: But by now having to pay 20% VAT, we would be priced out and we would have to send our children to state school.

895
01:03:14,206 --> 01:03:17,889
[SPEAKER_56]: The fact it, in fact, beats the objective of collecting tax.

896
01:03:18,090 --> 01:03:20,612
[SPEAKER_56]: Rather, it increases the influx in public schools.

897
01:03:21,393 --> 01:03:23,475
[SPEAKER_56]: So private schools is not only for the rich.

898
01:03:24,055 --> 01:03:26,418
[SPEAKER_56]: I mean, the rich would keep continue sending their children.

899
01:03:26,578 --> 01:03:28,640
[SPEAKER_56]: It's us who would have to make the change.

900
01:03:29,140 --> 01:03:33,405
[SPEAKER_56]: And the ultimate losers in all of this are the children who are meant to be our futures.

901
01:03:33,625 --> 01:03:34,085
[SPEAKER_56]: Yeah.

902
01:03:34,105 --> 01:03:36,788
[SPEAKER_56]: So would you reconsider taxing private education?

903
01:03:36,768 --> 01:03:40,454
[SPEAKER_31]: Look, let me be really clear about what we're doing here.

904
01:03:40,834 --> 01:03:42,657
[SPEAKER_31]: I have nothing against private schools.

905
01:03:43,058 --> 01:03:52,452
[SPEAKER_31]: I absolutely recognise that many parents work hard and save hard to send their children to private schools because they have aspiration for their children.

906
01:03:52,472 --> 01:03:59,282
[SPEAKER_31]: I equally accept that every parent, every parent has aspiration for their children, whether they go to private schools or not.

907
01:04:02,857 --> 01:04:06,561
[SPEAKER_31]: I absolutely respectfully want to make your point, because it is a concern.

908
01:04:06,641 --> 01:04:08,563
[SPEAKER_31]: It's a concern to you and to other people.

909
01:04:08,823 --> 01:04:14,308
[SPEAKER_31]: In our state secondary schools, we've got thousands of teachers missing in the subjects that we need.

910
01:04:14,588 --> 01:04:17,091
[SPEAKER_31]: So, in a state secondary school, let's take maths.

911
01:04:17,291 --> 01:04:28,442
[SPEAKER_31]: Too many students, young people, children, are being taught maths by sports teachers, by supply teachers, and that's not acceptable.

912
01:04:28,422 --> 01:04:44,260
[SPEAKER_31]: And for those children of state secondary school who don't have the teachers they need, that's not a one-year problem or a two-year budgeting problem, it's a lifelong problem, because if they don't get the qualifications they need at 15 and 16, they can't go and do what they want.

913
01:04:44,480 --> 01:04:56,533
[SPEAKER_31]: So we need to recruit 6,500 teachers for our state secondary schools to make sure every child, wherever they come from, whatever their background, whichever school they go to, has the same opportunity.

914
01:04:56,874 --> 01:04:58,075
[SPEAKER_31]: And I'll be pressed

915
01:04:58,055 --> 01:05:03,487
[SPEAKER_31]: When I say we're going to recruit 6,500 teachers, Beth and others will say to me, where's the money for that?

916
01:05:03,988 --> 01:05:14,650
[SPEAKER_31]: And I say we will get rid of the tax break for private schools and use that money directly to fund those teachers in our state secondary schools.

917
01:05:14,671 --> 01:05:14,871
[SPEAKER_32]: OK, but...

918
01:05:14,891 --> 01:05:15,372
[SPEAKER_32]: But, Kirstana, that's...

919
01:05:16,010 --> 01:05:17,612
[SPEAKER_31]: That's a political choice.

920
01:05:17,652 --> 01:05:19,154
[SPEAKER_31]: It's actually a tough choice.

921
01:05:19,615 --> 01:05:21,337
[SPEAKER_31]: I do understand what you're saying.

922
01:05:21,357 --> 01:05:24,842
[SPEAKER_31]: I don't think it will lead to lots of people going to state education.

923
01:05:24,862 --> 01:05:27,305
[SPEAKER_31]: We have done some analysis on this, but it's a choice.

924
01:05:27,485 --> 01:05:33,974
[SPEAKER_31]: I think every single child, whatever their background, wherever they're from, should have the chance and to believe, genuinely believe, that success belongs to them.

925
01:05:33,994 --> 01:05:35,616
[SPEAKER_31]: Zakir, I think he's saying he wants to come back.

926
01:05:35,636 --> 01:05:36,077
[SPEAKER_56]: Yeah, of course.

927
01:05:36,097 --> 01:05:40,903
[SPEAKER_56]: But this would mean that you would tax the working parents who send their children to private school.

928
01:05:40,883 --> 01:05:42,586
[SPEAKER_56]: Because the super rich will continue doing that.

929
01:05:42,967 --> 01:05:46,733
[SPEAKER_56]: And it's only the working parents who will have to make a decision or pay the taxes.

930
01:05:46,954 --> 01:05:49,498
[SPEAKER_56]: The position at the moment is there's a tax break.

931
01:05:49,879 --> 01:05:54,186
[SPEAKER_31]: So you pay VAT on other services, but you don't pay it for private schools.

932
01:05:54,647 --> 01:05:59,095
[SPEAKER_31]: Now, I understand why that's been in place, but it's a tax break that we are removing.

933
01:05:59,075 --> 01:06:01,057
[SPEAKER_31]: It's not an introduction of a new tax.

934
01:06:01,077 --> 01:06:13,730
[SPEAKER_31]: We're simply saying we need to find the money to properly fund our state secondary schools so that, in maths, to take an example, it's not the only example, I want every child to have a maths teacher teaching them maths, because it's...

935
01:06:13,750 --> 01:06:15,792
[SPEAKER_31]: The Prime Minister says he wants maths to the age of 18.

936
01:06:16,152 --> 01:06:22,058
[SPEAKER_31]: Let's first get the right teachers for every single child up to 16, because at the moment they don't have it.

937
01:06:22,298 --> 01:06:24,981
[SPEAKER_31]: And I genuinely worry, if you don't get maths,

938
01:06:24,961 --> 01:06:33,553
[SPEAKER_31]: at the right level in your GCSEs, it's really difficult to go on to A-levels, it's really difficult to go on to apprentices, and that child will be held back.

939
01:06:33,893 --> 01:06:39,941
[SPEAKER_31]: Now, this is difficult stuff, but I'm not going to tolerate the fact that we haven't got the right teachers in our state secondary schools.

940
01:06:39,981 --> 01:06:41,323
[SPEAKER_31]: That's the position we're in now.

941
01:06:41,543 --> 01:06:42,965
[SPEAKER_31]: It's a disgrace in that position.

942
01:06:43,065 --> 01:06:51,537
[SPEAKER_43]: I'm going to interrupt you because I've got so many audience questions and I'm going to be in trouble with them if I don't get through them, and you'll be gone and I'm the one in trouble.

943
01:06:52,198 --> 01:06:54,120
[SPEAKER_43]: So I've got Kerry from Grimsby.

944
01:06:54,140 --> 01:06:54,681
[SPEAKER_43]: Kerry?

945
01:06:54,661 --> 01:06:56,804
[SPEAKER_04]: Hi, good evening, Sakia.

946
01:06:57,425 --> 01:07:06,879
[SPEAKER_04]: My NHS dentist practice went private and gave us a choice of either staying and paying private or finding a new practice.

947
01:07:07,500 --> 01:07:14,290
[SPEAKER_04]: I've currently been on that waiting list for over a year with no idea of how long that waiting list is with my family.

948
01:07:14,310 --> 01:07:20,258
[SPEAKER_04]: How would you fix this crisis and stop dentists from going to the greed of private?

949
01:07:20,759 --> 01:07:22,221
[SPEAKER_31]: We need to make sure that...

950
01:07:25,525 --> 01:07:36,008
[SPEAKER_31]: This is a huge problem because we don't have enough NHS dentists for adults or for children, and some areas are deserts now where you simply can't get an NHS dentist.

951
01:07:36,028 --> 01:07:37,190
[SPEAKER_31]: So we've got to fix this.

952
01:07:37,652 --> 01:07:41,560
[SPEAKER_31]: There are two things that we would do, three things, but the first is...

953
01:07:41,540 --> 01:07:51,719
[SPEAKER_31]: to make the money available for 700,000 urgent appointments in NHS dentistry, including 100,000 for children, which is desperately needed.

954
01:07:52,180 --> 01:08:00,055
[SPEAKER_31]: The second is to incentivise newly qualified dentists to set up as NHS dentists by paying them money, by paying them money,

955
01:08:00,035 --> 01:08:07,081
[SPEAKER_31]: to put down their roots in the areas where they're most needed, so we can recreate those NHS dentist practices.

956
01:08:07,101 --> 01:08:08,182
[SPEAKER_31]: We have to do this.

957
01:08:08,443 --> 01:08:09,303
[SPEAKER_31]: I just...

958
01:08:09,323 --> 01:08:14,868
[SPEAKER_31]: In addition to the people who are frustrated in the way that you rightly are, I was genuinely shocked the other day.

959
01:08:14,888 --> 01:08:16,230
[SPEAKER_31]: I went to Alder Hey Children's Hospital.

960
01:08:16,270 --> 01:08:17,311
[SPEAKER_31]: This is a brilliant hospital.

961
01:08:17,871 --> 01:08:18,372
[SPEAKER_31]: Do you know what?

962
01:08:18,432 --> 01:08:26,139
[SPEAKER_31]: For six- to ten-year-olds, the most common cause of admission to hospital is rotting teeth to have their teeth taken out because they haven't seen a dentist.

963
01:08:26,159 --> 01:08:30,042
[SPEAKER_31]: It's a disgrace in 2024 England and Scotland and Wales.

964
01:08:30,022 --> 01:08:36,014
[SPEAKER_31]: APPLAUSE That was quicker, at least.

965
01:08:36,795 --> 01:08:37,476
[SPEAKER_31]: You were.

966
01:08:37,717 --> 01:08:40,021
[SPEAKER_31]: Do you use a private dentist?

967
01:08:40,402 --> 01:08:49,399
[SPEAKER_31]: Well, we're at an NHS dentist practice, but I'm private because I'm an adult and therefore don't get it on the NHS, but our kids get NHS dentistry, and I believe in it.

968
01:08:49,920 --> 01:08:50,081
[SPEAKER_31]: OK.

969
01:08:50,762 --> 01:08:52,806
[SPEAKER_57]: The nearest one available is somewhere over there.

970
01:08:53,225 --> 01:08:54,206
[SPEAKER_31]: And that's the problem.

971
01:08:54,246 --> 01:09:08,399
[SPEAKER_31]: You've got these vast areas where it's not just how much it is, it's also there just isn't a dentist there, which is why... And how have we got to this state in 2024, where basic things like dentistry are a problem in our country?

972
01:09:08,799 --> 01:09:11,822
[SPEAKER_31]: I mean, what on earth has happened to get us to this place?

973
01:09:12,002 --> 01:09:12,883
[SPEAKER_31]: We've got to fix it.

974
01:09:13,123 --> 01:09:17,187
[SPEAKER_31]: I look forward, on the first day we get into government, to starting on this job.

975
01:09:17,207 --> 01:09:22,371
[SPEAKER_31]: I find all of that much more interesting than all the sort of talking about what you're going to do.

976
01:09:22,391 --> 01:09:23,232
[SPEAKER_31]: I just want to get on with it.

977
01:09:23,212 --> 01:09:26,055
[SPEAKER_43]: The first day we get into government, bald.

978
01:09:29,218 --> 01:09:31,961
[SPEAKER_43]: OK, next question is from Cayman, who's from Yorkshire.

979
01:09:31,981 --> 01:09:33,142
[SPEAKER_43]: Cayman, where are you?

980
01:09:33,242 --> 01:09:33,443
[SPEAKER_22]: Hello.

981
01:09:33,743 --> 01:09:34,344
[SPEAKER_22]: Please go ahead.

982
01:09:34,364 --> 01:09:35,925
[SPEAKER_22]: Cayman, hi.

983
01:09:35,945 --> 01:09:42,952
[SPEAKER_22]: I admired how in touch you were with the public when you were obviously a solicitor and then you became Director of Public Prosecutions with CPS.

984
01:09:43,413 --> 01:09:48,739
[SPEAKER_22]: But over the last year, I feel like you've formed into more of a politician than the person that I would have voted for to run the country.

985
01:09:49,679 --> 01:09:52,122
[SPEAKER_22]: You seem more like a political robot.

986
01:09:52,675 --> 01:09:56,591
[SPEAKER_22]: How are you going to convince others like me to vote for you?

987
01:09:56,611 --> 01:10:01,150
[SPEAKER_30]: Well, the most...

988
01:10:02,277 --> 01:10:04,942
[SPEAKER_31]: Look, all I can say...

989
01:10:04,962 --> 01:10:07,586
[SPEAKER_31]: I went to run the Crown Prosecution Service.

990
01:10:07,606 --> 01:10:08,648
[SPEAKER_31]: You referenced that.

991
01:10:08,728 --> 01:10:22,732
[SPEAKER_31]: I was the chief prosecutor for five years, effectively bringing in every criminal prosecution in England and Wales, including here in Grimsby, in our courts, to make sure that where people broke the law, they were prosecuted and you were kept safe as a result of that.

992
01:10:22,772 --> 01:10:24,775
[SPEAKER_31]: Working, of course, with my staff.

993
01:10:24,755 --> 01:10:32,264
[SPEAKER_31]: I worked before that in Northern Ireland, so I've had this constant theme in my life of trying to serve the public.

994
01:10:32,704 --> 01:10:33,786
[SPEAKER_31]: That's why I worked in Northern Ireland.

995
01:10:33,806 --> 01:10:36,088
[SPEAKER_31]: That's why I worked in the Crown Prosecution Service.

996
01:10:36,108 --> 01:10:39,432
[SPEAKER_31]: That's why I took the decision to go into politics.

997
01:10:39,893 --> 01:10:41,775
[SPEAKER_31]: I came into politics quite late in life.

998
01:10:41,835 --> 01:10:43,497
[SPEAKER_31]: I'd done other things beforehand.

999
01:10:43,938 --> 01:10:52,047
[SPEAKER_31]: But I took the decision that I couldn't take the issues, make the changes that I thought were necessary, unless I went into politics.

1000
01:10:52,067 --> 01:10:52,708
[SPEAKER_31]: I was frustrated.

1001
01:10:52,728 --> 01:10:53,749
[SPEAKER_31]: Do you think you've changed?

1002
01:10:54,640 --> 01:11:03,358
[SPEAKER_31]: Well, I've been much clearer in my own mind that the country must come first and the party and party politics second.

1003
01:11:03,779 --> 01:11:07,386
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm really, you know, I don't apologise for that.

1004
01:11:07,487 --> 01:11:09,030
[SPEAKER_31]: I think that's really important.

1005
01:11:09,050 --> 01:11:13,459
[SPEAKER_31]: I think it probably is a result of coming into politics late because I'm not tribally political.

1006
01:11:13,439 --> 01:11:20,350
[SPEAKER_31]: I actually do believe there are good people who vote other than Labour who want their family, their community, and their country to go forward.

1007
01:11:20,631 --> 01:11:26,320
[SPEAKER_31]: And that's why I've said, if we are to come into power, I want a decade of national renewal.

1008
01:11:26,360 --> 01:11:34,333
[SPEAKER_31]: And I want everybody who wants the country to improve to feel that there's a place for them, whether or not they traditionally voted Labour, because I actually

1009
01:11:34,313 --> 01:11:38,978
[SPEAKER_31]: I genuinely think that the vast majority of people in this country are reasonable people.

1010
01:11:39,198 --> 01:11:43,123
[SPEAKER_31]: They're tolerant people who sort of live and let live.

1011
01:11:43,723 --> 01:11:51,032
[SPEAKER_31]: And if given the chance, would pull together to advance their community, to advance their family, and to advance their country.

1012
01:11:51,452 --> 01:11:55,116
[SPEAKER_31]: And I don't think you need to be tribally Labour for that.

1013
01:11:55,216 --> 01:11:57,739
[SPEAKER_31]: I think you can actually pull the country together.

1014
01:11:57,719 --> 01:11:59,724
[SPEAKER_31]: And that would be a real moment for us.

1015
01:11:59,744 --> 01:12:00,666
[SPEAKER_43]: I'm going to have to interrupt.

1016
01:12:00,706 --> 01:12:01,708
[SPEAKER_43]: Yeah, of course, that was a bit long.

1017
01:12:01,728 --> 01:12:02,189
[SPEAKER_43]: Apologies.

1018
01:12:02,249 --> 01:12:04,594
[SPEAKER_43]: Caiman, did he convince you, yes or no?

1019
01:12:05,136 --> 01:12:12,613
[SPEAKER_22]: I hope you don't answer the questions... How you answer the questions, I hope you never answered them the way that you did when you were a solicitor, because you don't seem to answer the question.

1020
01:12:12,633 --> 01:12:12,853
[SPEAKER_22]: OK.

1021
01:12:13,434 --> 01:12:14,597
[SPEAKER_42]: I'm going to...

1022
01:12:19,285 --> 01:12:24,031
[SPEAKER_43]: OK, well, I'm going to need a speedy answer because we're running out of time, but I have Kieran from Guildford.

1023
01:12:24,071 --> 01:12:24,992
[SPEAKER_43]: You've got under the line.

1024
01:12:25,012 --> 01:12:25,713
[SPEAKER_43]: Where are you?

1025
01:12:25,733 --> 01:12:26,453
[SPEAKER_09]: Please, go ahead.

1026
01:12:27,114 --> 01:12:27,435
[SPEAKER_09]: Good evening.

1027
01:12:28,316 --> 01:12:33,221
[SPEAKER_09]: Young people in this country have grown up knowing nothing but conservative austerity and political chaos.

1028
01:12:34,082 --> 01:12:38,708
[SPEAKER_09]: We didn't have the chance to vote for Brexit in 2016 because we were too young, and now we're inheriting that economy.

1029
01:12:38,728 --> 01:12:46,677
[SPEAKER_09]: We're graduating from university, less likely to own a home than our parents, all while paying a higher effective tax rate because of student loans that wasn't a thing generations ago.

1030
01:12:46,657 --> 01:12:55,483
[SPEAKER_09]: How can you convince us that you are truly going to be different and actually effective at making change, not just in terms of the economy, but also to improve our trust in political institutions?

1031
01:12:57,850 --> 01:12:58,371
[SPEAKER_31]: I need a quick answer too.

1032
01:13:00,308 --> 01:13:02,511
[SPEAKER_31]: I need a quick answer, please.

1033
01:13:02,531 --> 01:13:07,840
[SPEAKER_31]: First, by absolutely being clear that I understand the challenges that you are setting out.

1034
01:13:08,180 --> 01:13:18,216
[SPEAKER_31]: And that's because I do something which I think is underrated in politics and leadership, which is to listen, to use these, to listen to the challenges that people are talking to me about.

1035
01:13:18,196 --> 01:13:19,538
[SPEAKER_31]: I go around the country the whole time.

1036
01:13:19,779 --> 01:13:25,709
[SPEAKER_31]: The most important thing I say to everybody I meet, please tell me the change you want if we're able to come into government.

1037
01:13:25,729 --> 01:13:32,842
[SPEAKER_31]: And I will mull that over in my mind on the train or in the car on the way back, because you have the right to put your fingerprints on what comes next.

1038
01:13:32,862 --> 01:13:38,752
[SPEAKER_31]: But just to address the specific things, we need good quality, high skilled jobs for the future for our young people.

1039
01:13:38,952 --> 01:13:40,575
[SPEAKER_31]: That's why I was so impressed

1040
01:13:40,555 --> 01:13:47,386
[SPEAKER_31]: you know, when I saw those apprentices here in Hull who had skilled jobs that they were proud of doing with a future to them.

1041
01:13:47,406 --> 01:13:51,833
[SPEAKER_31]: We need to make sure we're building enough houses so that young people can get on the housing ladder.

1042
01:13:52,034 --> 01:13:58,564
[SPEAKER_31]: At the moment, the idea that you have to be in your mid to late 30s before you get your own roof over your head

1043
01:13:58,544 --> 01:14:10,898
[SPEAKER_31]: it is a sign of a broken system, because I know from growing up how important it is to have your own home as a base camp for your dreams, your aspirations, for the security of your family.

1044
01:14:10,918 --> 01:14:12,860
[SPEAKER_31]: So we will build those 1.5 million.

1045
01:14:12,880 --> 01:14:20,189
[SPEAKER_31]: That will only happen if we partner with business, if we get rid of some of the planning rules that are in the way... OK, it's OK, I'm going to have to interrupt.

1046
01:14:20,209 --> 01:14:24,834
[SPEAKER_31]: ..and if we have a set of arrangements with mayors and combined authorities to get that building done.

1047
01:14:25,174 --> 01:14:25,275
[SPEAKER_29]: OK.

1048
01:14:25,295 --> 01:14:26,156
[SPEAKER_31]: It's OK, we're out of time.

1049
01:14:26,176 --> 01:14:28,298
[SPEAKER_31]: Because otherwise, you simply will be in the same position.

1050
01:14:28,278 --> 01:14:29,280
[SPEAKER_43]: I'm going to have to interrupt.

1051
01:14:29,320 --> 01:14:44,044
[SPEAKER_43]: Sakir, thank you so much for joining us in Grimsby tonight.

1052
01:14:44,064 --> 01:14:44,745
Thank you very much for having me.

1053
01:14:44,765 --> 01:14:44,965
[SPEAKER_43]: Thank you.

1054
01:14:44,985 --> 01:14:47,109
[SPEAKER_43]: Well, that was Keir Starmer.

1055
01:14:47,389 --> 01:14:50,574
[SPEAKER_43]: Next up is the Prime Minister, Rishi Sunak.

1056
01:14:50,594 --> 01:14:51,636
[SPEAKER_43]: Don't go anywhere.

1057
01:15:28,167 --> 01:15:31,951
[SPEAKER_37]: Big stories don't always come from big cities.

1058
01:15:32,952 --> 01:15:36,557
[SPEAKER_37]: I'm Lisa Dowd, and I'm Sky's Midlands correspondent.

1059
01:15:36,677 --> 01:15:39,720
[SPEAKER_37]: And this is where I grew up.

1060
01:15:39,740 --> 01:15:47,028
[SPEAKER_37]: We can reveal that the driver who hit Harry Dunn is 42-year-old Anne Sekoulas.

1061
01:15:47,048 --> 01:15:50,572
[SPEAKER_23]: Just met the president, and we never thought we'd get this far.

1062
01:15:50,592 --> 01:15:53,996
[SPEAKER_37]: This is what they're up against, that the wind is the really big problems.

1063
01:15:54,036 --> 01:15:57,280
[SPEAKER_37]: It is back-breaking work, and the smoke is thick.

1064
01:15:59,386 --> 01:16:00,867
[SPEAKER_37]: It's been working well.

1065
01:16:01,308 --> 01:16:06,973
[SPEAKER_37]: Water levels are dropping, but no one knows what impact further rain will have.

1066
01:16:09,396 --> 01:16:12,458
[SPEAKER_36]: What would you do if this place wasn't open?

1067
01:16:14,440 --> 01:16:18,364
[SPEAKER_37]: We take you to the heart of the stories that shape our world.

1068
01:16:19,025 --> 01:16:20,126
[SPEAKER_37]: It's really scary.

1069
01:16:20,226 --> 01:16:21,827
[SPEAKER_37]: We're terrified.

1070
01:16:21,847 --> 01:16:27,773
[SPEAKER_37]: In this community, I'm told that everybody knows someone affected by COVID.

1071
01:16:27,938 --> 01:16:29,560
[SPEAKER_02]: Hopefully this will be the last wave.

1072
01:16:31,322 --> 01:16:33,124
[SPEAKER_02]: I never knew they would make it.

1073
01:16:33,525 --> 01:16:34,186
[SPEAKER_02]: It's amazing.

1074
01:16:34,926 --> 01:16:39,852
[SPEAKER_37]: Change seems tantalisingly close in this corner of the UK.

1075
01:16:40,213 --> 01:16:44,498
[SPEAKER_37]: Wales was the first to introduce the plastic bag charge.

1076
01:16:46,561 --> 01:16:49,604
[SPEAKER_37]: This is my patch, my specialism.

1077
01:16:50,125 --> 01:16:51,887
[SPEAKER_37]: It's also my home.

1078
01:18:35,868 --> 01:18:41,111
[SPEAKER_33]: Welcome back to The Battle for Number 10, live from Grimsby Town Hall.

1079
01:18:41,533 --> 01:18:45,270
[SPEAKER_33]: We've heard from the Labour leader, now it's the Prime Minister's turn.

1080
01:18:47,579 --> 01:18:50,782
[SPEAKER_43]: Prime Minister, thank you so much for joining us tonight in Grimsby.

1081
01:18:50,802 --> 01:18:51,383
[SPEAKER_43]: Pleased to be back.

1082
01:18:51,403 --> 01:18:51,884
[SPEAKER_00]: Appreciate your time.

1083
01:18:51,904 --> 01:18:52,464
[SPEAKER_43]: Thanks for having me.

1084
01:18:53,325 --> 01:18:57,670
[SPEAKER_43]: PM, polling day is three weeks tomorrow, but it's rough, isn't it?

1085
01:18:57,830 --> 01:19:04,497
[SPEAKER_43]: A poll out this week put the Conservatives on 18 points, just about neck and neck with Nigel Farage's reform.

1086
01:19:05,037 --> 01:19:10,343
[SPEAKER_43]: And your polling is now worse than in the dying days of the List Trust government.

1087
01:19:10,383 --> 01:19:12,405
[SPEAKER_43]: What's going so wrong?

1088
01:19:12,740 --> 01:19:22,572
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, I've got to say, Beth, it hasn't been an easy 18 months in general, so what I've done, though, is just keep going to try and do my best for people, and that's what I'm doing in this campaign.

1089
01:19:22,612 --> 01:19:34,006
[SPEAKER_27]: I'm excited to have the opportunity to talk to everyone, not just tonight, but across the campaign, out and about in the country, about our plans for the future, because I know we've been through a tough time, of course we have, and I'm sure we'll talk about it.

1090
01:19:34,026 --> 01:19:38,832
[SPEAKER_27]: It's been tough for all of you here tonight, everyone watching, but I do believe we've turned a corner,

1091
01:19:38,812 --> 01:19:44,902
[SPEAKER_27]: We've got a clear plan for the future to make a difference to people, to cut their taxes, to bring down immigration, to protect pensions.

1092
01:19:44,963 --> 01:19:46,906
[SPEAKER_27]: Those are all things that I think matter.

1093
01:19:47,046 --> 01:19:48,348
[SPEAKER_27]: I think those are things that people want.

1094
01:19:48,428 --> 01:19:50,913
[SPEAKER_27]: And so I'm going to keep fighting hard till the last day of this election.

1095
01:19:51,153 --> 01:19:55,460
[SPEAKER_43]: PM, Liz Truss never recovered from that disastrous mini-budget.

1096
01:19:55,921 --> 01:20:03,975
[SPEAKER_43]: Do you worry that your fateful decision to skip part of those D-Day commemorations could prove as terminal for you?

1097
01:20:03,955 --> 01:20:10,769
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, the last thing that I wanted to do was cause anyone, and particularly our veterans community, any hurt or upset.

1098
01:20:10,990 --> 01:20:15,760
[SPEAKER_27]: It was a mistake, and that's why I apologised unreservedly for that.

1099
01:20:16,261 --> 01:20:21,913
[SPEAKER_27]: And, you know, I'm deeply sad to have caused people hurt and upset by that.

1100
01:20:21,893 --> 01:20:38,198
[SPEAKER_27]: I was privileged to participate in all the commemoration events that I did, to speak to many veterans, to thank them in person for what they did, but also make sure that I can demonstrate to them how committed I am to making this the best country in the world to be a veteran for all the things that we are doing in government.

1101
01:20:38,178 --> 01:20:42,786
[SPEAKER_43]: And when you realised the mistake and you apologised, how were you feeling?

1102
01:20:43,327 --> 01:20:44,509
[SPEAKER_43]: Did you feel really awful?

1103
01:20:44,630 --> 01:20:45,952
[SPEAKER_43]: How was it for you?

1104
01:20:45,992 --> 01:20:50,180
[SPEAKER_27]: Yeah, I was incredibly sad to have caused people hurt and upset.

1105
01:20:50,300 --> 01:20:53,085
[SPEAKER_27]: That was actually the last thing that I wanted to do.

1106
01:20:53,185 --> 01:20:56,290
[SPEAKER_27]: And as I said, I hope people can find it in their hearts to forgive me.

1107
01:20:56,711 --> 01:20:59,376
[SPEAKER_27]: When I realised I'd made a mistake, I apologised.

1108
01:20:59,356 --> 01:21:18,529
[SPEAKER_27]: I've asked for forgiveness and also I have been speaking to veterans about the things that we are doing to make sure this is a good country for them after they've served because we owe them an enormous debt of gratitude and that's why I've made sure it's a priority to have a minister around the cabinet table to support them and focus on the things that matter to them.

1109
01:21:18,509 --> 01:21:21,094
[SPEAKER_43]: Prime Minister, let's go on to the Tory record.

1110
01:21:21,134 --> 01:21:29,649
[SPEAKER_43]: You say that you're the one who can deliver stability after all the turmoil, but for many voters the Conservatives are the turmoil.

1111
01:21:30,170 --> 01:21:36,361
[SPEAKER_43]: In this Parliament we've had three Prime Ministers, five Chancellors, five Home Secretaries, six Health Secretaries.

1112
01:21:36,801 --> 01:21:43,453
[SPEAKER_43]: How do we know that if you won the general election you'd still be Prime Minister in a year's time?

1113
01:21:50,588 --> 01:21:54,156
[SPEAKER_27]: Look, I can appreciate people's frustrations.

1114
01:21:54,196 --> 01:21:56,181
[SPEAKER_27]: Of course, we haven't got everything right.

1115
01:21:56,201 --> 01:21:57,323
[SPEAKER_27]: I don't think any government does.

1116
01:21:57,383 --> 01:21:59,728
[SPEAKER_27]: And I know it's been very difficult for many people.

1117
01:22:00,169 --> 01:22:06,123
[SPEAKER_27]: But what I can do is work as hard as I can to deliver the stability that I said I would.

1118
01:22:06,143 --> 01:22:07,606
[SPEAKER_27]: And I've had this job for 18 months.

1119
01:22:07,646 --> 01:22:09,390
[SPEAKER_27]: And I think, particularly on the economy,

1120
01:22:09,370 --> 01:22:18,340
[SPEAKER_27]: As I'm sure we'll get into, people can see that inflation is back to normal, the economy is growing, wages are rising, and that's why we're having this election now, to talk about the future.

1121
01:22:18,380 --> 01:22:32,616
[SPEAKER_27]: And yes, I've got a track record over the past 18 months, which I'm sure we'll talk about, but also I want to build on that and continue the progress we've made, whether it's cutting people's taxes, bringing down migration, or indeed protecting people's pensions.

1122
01:22:32,656 --> 01:22:35,479
[SPEAKER_27]: These are all things that now we're in a position to make more progress on.

1123
01:22:35,459 --> 01:22:42,553
[SPEAKER_43]: I'd like to come on to that, but many people do view Liz Truss's brief period in office as the symbol of that Tory chaos.

1124
01:22:42,613 --> 01:22:46,201
[SPEAKER_43]: Has her legacy cast a long shadow for you?

1125
01:22:46,241 --> 01:22:50,229
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, I think if people are thinking about that, they can think about what I did.

1126
01:22:50,930 --> 01:22:52,894
[SPEAKER_27]: You and I spent some time that summer.

1127
01:22:52,934 --> 01:22:53,996
[SPEAKER_27]: You interviewed me.

1128
01:22:54,096 --> 01:22:57,383
[SPEAKER_27]: I did an event like this at the time because I disagreed.

1129
01:22:57,548 --> 01:22:59,130
[SPEAKER_27]: with her economic policies.

1130
01:22:59,330 --> 01:23:02,212
[SPEAKER_27]: And actually, it wasn't easy for people to hear what I had to say.

1131
01:23:02,293 --> 01:23:05,355
[SPEAKER_27]: But I believed very deeply then in what I was saying.

1132
01:23:05,896 --> 01:23:09,079
[SPEAKER_27]: And I went around the country then talking about it, doing events like this.

1133
01:23:09,199 --> 01:23:11,722
[SPEAKER_27]: We did one similarly together as well.

1134
01:23:11,782 --> 01:23:12,943
[SPEAKER_27]: And you interviewed me.

1135
01:23:13,403 --> 01:23:19,809
[SPEAKER_27]: And that's who I am as a person, even though that wasn't an easy thing, even though back then, actually, it was difficult for me and I was behind.

1136
01:23:20,450 --> 01:23:23,513
[SPEAKER_27]: I was talking about what I believe was right for our country.

1137
01:23:23,833 --> 01:23:26,796
[SPEAKER_27]: And that's who I am as a person.

1138
01:23:26,776 --> 01:23:32,604
[SPEAKER_27]: And I was right about that, and that's why people can trust me now when it comes to what I say about the economy today.

1139
01:23:32,985 --> 01:23:35,008
[SPEAKER_43]: Well, look, let's get on to your pledges.

1140
01:23:35,048 --> 01:23:36,490
[SPEAKER_43]: Let's get on to you now.

1141
01:23:37,171 --> 01:23:40,736
[SPEAKER_43]: In January 2023, you made the British people five promises.

1142
01:23:40,796 --> 01:23:43,139
[SPEAKER_43]: You said, no tricks, no ambiguity.

1143
01:23:43,459 --> 01:23:45,983
[SPEAKER_43]: We're either delivering for you or we're not.

1144
01:23:45,963 --> 01:23:51,199
[SPEAKER_43]: So I ask you to judge us on the effort we put in and the results we achieve.

1145
01:23:51,399 --> 01:23:52,403
[SPEAKER_43]: Five promises.

1146
01:23:53,004 --> 01:23:54,228
[SPEAKER_43]: Let's talk about the promises.

1147
01:23:54,308 --> 01:23:57,538
[SPEAKER_43]: Promises one and two, halving inflation, growing the economy.

1148
01:23:57,578 --> 01:23:58,521
[SPEAKER_43]: You've done that.

1149
01:23:59,007 --> 01:24:01,950
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, the most important priority was the first one.

1150
01:24:02,090 --> 01:24:04,472
[SPEAKER_27]: Because when I got this job, inflation was at 11%.

1151
01:24:05,513 --> 01:24:09,677
[SPEAKER_27]: And I think everyone knows the last few years have been difficult, the impact that was having on all your bills.

1152
01:24:10,277 --> 01:24:13,420
[SPEAKER_27]: Every week, you were seeing the impact in your shop.

1153
01:24:13,761 --> 01:24:18,865
[SPEAKER_27]: And that's why my priority was to bring down inflation, to ease that burden.

1154
01:24:18,885 --> 01:24:20,146
[SPEAKER_27]: And it wasn't a given.

1155
01:24:20,727 --> 01:24:21,628
[SPEAKER_27]: And it was 11%.

1156
01:24:21,668 --> 01:24:26,432
[SPEAKER_27]: Now it's back to normal, ahead of our competitors, which is the result of a lot of hard work.

1157
01:24:26,472 --> 01:24:28,474
[SPEAKER_27]: But also- So let's just go through the pledges.

1158
01:24:28,893 --> 01:24:33,279
[SPEAKER_55]: Yeah.

1159
01:24:33,299 --> 01:24:36,644
[SPEAKER_27]: Yes, inflation is... Of course, of course, I know things are not...

1160
01:24:36,664 --> 01:24:38,146
[SPEAKER_27]: I know things are not easy.

1161
01:24:38,947 --> 01:24:39,949
[SPEAKER_27]: Of course I know that.

1162
01:24:40,049 --> 01:24:42,192
[SPEAKER_27]: They've been difficult for a while for all sorts of reasons.

1163
01:24:42,212 --> 01:24:42,272
[SPEAKER_00]: OK.

1164
01:24:42,292 --> 01:24:47,219
[SPEAKER_27]: But what I was absolutely set about doing was making things that little bit easier.

1165
01:24:47,239 --> 01:24:49,382
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, look, let's go... And that's why inflation was a priority.

1166
01:24:49,422 --> 01:24:50,443
[SPEAKER_27]: Let's go through the pledges.

1167
01:24:50,463 --> 01:24:55,450
[SPEAKER_27]: And it was precisely because the bills were continuing to go up that we needed to bring inflation down, and I'm pleased we were able to do that.

1168
01:24:55,470 --> 01:24:58,815
[SPEAKER_43]: One and two, half an inflation, economy grown, tick, tick.

1169
01:24:59,369 --> 01:25:01,554
[SPEAKER_43]: Promise number three, reducing national debt.

1170
01:25:01,594 --> 01:25:03,377
[SPEAKER_43]: It's gone up since you made the pledge, hasn't it?

1171
01:25:04,039 --> 01:25:04,299
[SPEAKER_43]: It has.

1172
01:25:04,319 --> 01:25:04,780
[SPEAKER_43]: Yeah.

1173
01:25:05,181 --> 01:25:10,051
[SPEAKER_43]: But it was always meant to come down over time, and that was always the time.

1174
01:25:10,071 --> 01:25:12,256
[SPEAKER_27]: I know, but that... What was it when you made the pledge?

1175
01:25:12,677 --> 01:25:16,244
[SPEAKER_27]: But we measure our debt according to... An independent body measures our debt.

1176
01:25:16,264 --> 01:25:19,150
[SPEAKER_43]: But it's higher now than it was when you made the pledge, right?

1177
01:25:19,130 --> 01:25:21,113
[SPEAKER_43]: Yes, it was always forecast to be high.

1178
01:25:21,153 --> 01:25:22,194
[SPEAKER_27]: Let me be clear, Beth.

1179
01:25:22,254 --> 01:25:24,337
[SPEAKER_27]: I was never saying it would come down overnight.

1180
01:25:24,637 --> 01:25:25,618
[SPEAKER_27]: I was very clear at the time.

1181
01:25:25,638 --> 01:25:27,681
[SPEAKER_27]: You made the pledge in January 2023.

1182
01:25:27,721 --> 01:25:29,803
[SPEAKER_43]: And when I made the pledge... And you're going into an election.

1183
01:25:29,844 --> 01:25:32,827
[SPEAKER_43]: I'm just making the point that you failed on that pledge as you go to the polls.

1184
01:25:32,907 --> 01:25:39,155
[SPEAKER_27]: No, because when I made the pledge, I was very clear that we measure our debt reduction according to an independent body.

1185
01:25:39,175 --> 01:25:40,117
[SPEAKER_27]: No tricks, no ambiguity.

1186
01:25:40,137 --> 01:25:41,819
[SPEAKER_27]: No tricks, no ambiguity.

1187
01:25:41,859 --> 01:25:43,160
[SPEAKER_27]: None at all, right?

1188
01:25:43,180 --> 01:25:44,462
[SPEAKER_27]: We have an independent...

1189
01:25:46,788 --> 01:25:49,695
[SPEAKER_27]: I'm happy to explain.

1190
01:25:49,755 --> 01:25:52,061
[SPEAKER_27]: So we measure our debt reduction independently.

1191
01:25:52,081 --> 01:25:53,224
[SPEAKER_27]: It's actually not me that does it.

1192
01:25:53,244 --> 01:25:55,410
[SPEAKER_27]: It's an independent body called the OBR.

1193
01:25:55,430 --> 01:25:59,400
[SPEAKER_27]: We set out the fiscal rules to bring debt down over five years, and that's how they measure it.

1194
01:25:59,781 --> 01:26:02,788
[SPEAKER_27]: And they have confirmed every budget, and you can go look at it online.

1195
01:26:02,768 --> 01:26:03,169
[SPEAKER_27]: All right.

1196
01:26:03,189 --> 01:26:04,831
[SPEAKER_27]: ..that we are meeting those fiscal rules.

1197
01:26:04,891 --> 01:26:04,971
[SPEAKER_27]: OK.

1198
01:26:04,991 --> 01:26:07,234
[SPEAKER_27]: When I made the announcement, I think you were there at the press conference...

1199
01:26:07,254 --> 01:26:07,494
[SPEAKER_00]: I was there.

1200
01:26:07,514 --> 01:26:11,539
[SPEAKER_27]: ..when I did, I actually was asked a question and I explained then, they said, how are you measuring this?

1201
01:26:11,619 --> 01:26:16,025
[SPEAKER_27]: And I said, we're measuring it according to the independent body... OK. ..which will adjudicate our rules.

1202
01:26:16,105 --> 01:26:17,146
[SPEAKER_27]: And we've met all those rules... Let's crack on.

1203
01:26:17,166 --> 01:26:18,268
[SPEAKER_27]: ..because that's really important to me.

1204
01:26:18,288 --> 01:26:18,849
[SPEAKER_43]: Let's crack on.

1205
01:26:18,989 --> 01:26:20,130
[SPEAKER_43]: But... No, just before we...

1206
01:26:20,150 --> 01:26:22,113
[SPEAKER_43]: Cutting NHS waiting lists, that's pledge four.

1207
01:26:22,654 --> 01:26:25,637
[SPEAKER_43]: When you made the promise, the list was at 7.21 million.

1208
01:26:25,657 --> 01:26:28,161
[SPEAKER_43]: It's now at 7.54 million cases.

1209
01:26:28,221 --> 01:26:29,282
[SPEAKER_43]: It's gone up.

1210
01:26:29,330 --> 01:26:29,870
[SPEAKER_27]: Yes, it has.

1211
01:26:30,751 --> 01:26:31,672
[SPEAKER_27]: Yes, I was very good.

1212
01:26:31,692 --> 01:26:35,456
[SPEAKER_27]: We've not made as much progress on cutting waiting lists as I would have liked.

1213
01:26:35,796 --> 01:26:38,839
[SPEAKER_27]: And that was something that I was keen to do.

1214
01:26:38,879 --> 01:26:40,160
[SPEAKER_27]: And it has proved more difficult.

1215
01:26:40,200 --> 01:26:42,522
[SPEAKER_27]: And it's been proved more difficult for a number of reasons.

1216
01:26:42,582 --> 01:26:45,244
[SPEAKER_27]: Obviously, recovering from the pandemic is not easy.

1217
01:26:45,525 --> 01:26:47,046
[SPEAKER_27]: But we are now making progress.

1218
01:26:47,066 --> 01:26:52,871
[SPEAKER_27]: And actually, the number that you gave is just over 200,000 lower than it was a few months ago.

1219
01:26:52,971 --> 01:26:55,334
[SPEAKER_43]: Because now- It's gone up from when you made the pledge.

1220
01:26:55,354 --> 01:26:55,734
[SPEAKER_43]: Yes, it has.

1221
01:26:56,034 --> 01:26:56,334
[SPEAKER_27]: It has.

1222
01:26:56,475 --> 01:26:57,596
[SPEAKER_27]: I'm being very clear about that.

1223
01:26:58,136 --> 01:26:59,117
[SPEAKER_27]: And now it's coming down.

1224
01:26:59,097 --> 01:27:01,140
[SPEAKER_27]: OK. Because we are now, the plans are working.

1225
01:27:01,160 --> 01:27:01,921
[SPEAKER_27]: You made the pledge in January 20th.

1226
01:27:01,941 --> 01:27:02,943
[SPEAKER_27]: We've resolved the industrial action.

1227
01:27:03,103 --> 01:27:03,844
[SPEAKER_43]: And they're going up.

1228
01:27:03,944 --> 01:27:05,707
[SPEAKER_43]: OK. Let's go to the fifth pledge.

1229
01:27:05,827 --> 01:27:09,092
[SPEAKER_27]: I think you had a question earlier from, I think there was a junior doctor here.

1230
01:27:09,152 --> 01:27:12,016
[SPEAKER_27]: And I think everyone knows the impact the industrial action has had.

1231
01:27:12,076 --> 01:27:13,698
[SPEAKER_27]: That's why we haven't made as much.

1232
01:27:13,718 --> 01:27:16,903
[SPEAKER_43]: So it's the doctor's fault.

1233
01:27:17,812 --> 01:27:28,872
[SPEAKER_43]: Let's not dwell on this, but PM, the point is that when you made the pledge there were several NHS industrial disputes happening at the time.

1234
01:27:29,212 --> 01:27:37,487
[SPEAKER_43]: Ambulance workers were on strikes, nurses had announced strikes, junior doctors were balloting and you still made the pledge and the numbers are up.

1235
01:27:37,507 --> 01:27:38,188
[SPEAKER_43]: Let's move on.

1236
01:27:38,348 --> 01:27:39,330
[SPEAKER_27]: But having resolved

1237
01:27:39,310 --> 01:27:41,674
[SPEAKER_27]: all of the industrial action except the junior doctors.

1238
01:27:42,235 --> 01:27:46,102
[SPEAKER_27]: Except the junior doctors, what you're now seeing is that the numbers are coming down.

1239
01:27:46,122 --> 01:27:48,106
[SPEAKER_27]: And we are making progress.

1240
01:27:48,126 --> 01:27:53,595
[SPEAKER_43]: I might have not done brilliantly at maths at school, but I know that 7.2... 1,000,007.5 is going up.

1241
01:27:53,615 --> 01:27:54,076
[SPEAKER_43]: Let's move on.

1242
01:27:54,096 --> 01:28:00,087
[SPEAKER_43]: Let's move on to...

1243
01:28:01,383 --> 01:28:03,706
[SPEAKER_43]: Your fifth promise was stopping the small boats.

1244
01:28:04,347 --> 01:28:05,890
[SPEAKER_43]: Boat crossings are going up, aren't they?

1245
01:28:06,410 --> 01:28:08,133
[SPEAKER_27]: Yes, they were down last year by a third.

1246
01:28:08,193 --> 01:28:11,138
[SPEAKER_27]: They're down over the last 12 months by a little less than that.

1247
01:28:11,418 --> 01:28:17,207
[SPEAKER_27]: This year, there's what we've seen is one particular country, Vietnam, accounting for the majority of the increase.

1248
01:28:17,868 --> 01:28:26,901
[SPEAKER_27]: But actually, the plans that we've put in place last year show that it is possible to make a difference to this problem, which, by the way, before I got this job, everybody said was impossible.

1249
01:28:26,881 --> 01:28:29,043
[SPEAKER_27]: Everybody said it was impossible to get the numbers down at all.

1250
01:28:29,063 --> 01:28:30,945
[SPEAKER_27]: But we showed last year that that was possible.

1251
01:28:31,266 --> 01:28:34,710
[SPEAKER_27]: And now we have a clear plan to put a deterrent in place.

1252
01:28:34,750 --> 01:28:37,152
[SPEAKER_43]: And that means... And I will come on to it.

1253
01:28:37,172 --> 01:28:37,693
[SPEAKER_27]: OK, yeah.

1254
01:28:37,713 --> 01:28:47,724
[SPEAKER_43]: But look, crossings have risen by 40% this year against last year, to 11,247 people crossing on small boats this year.

1255
01:28:47,744 --> 01:28:49,826
[SPEAKER_43]: It's going to be a record year.

1256
01:28:49,886 --> 01:28:52,049
[SPEAKER_43]: You have failed to deliver on this pledge.

1257
01:28:52,529 --> 01:28:54,171
[SPEAKER_43]: If you... Just please acknowledge it.

1258
01:28:54,151 --> 01:29:02,447
[SPEAKER_27]: No, no, if you look at the sum total of the time that I've been Prime Minister, because you've picked one particular period, if you look at the sum total of the time that I've been Prime Minister, the numbers are down.

1259
01:29:02,748 --> 01:29:04,752
[SPEAKER_43]: The numbers were down last year.

1260
01:29:04,792 --> 01:29:07,578
[SPEAKER_43]: The numbers in 2023 were down on 2022.

1261
01:29:07,598 --> 01:29:10,303
[SPEAKER_43]: It's because of the work that we've done.

1262
01:29:10,283 --> 01:29:12,326
[SPEAKER_43]: that, well, it's a record year this year.

1263
01:29:12,346 --> 01:29:14,789
[SPEAKER_43]: They've gone up by 40% in the past six months of this year.

1264
01:29:14,849 --> 01:29:20,576
[SPEAKER_27]: Yes, because these things are cyclical, because what you've seen is one new country, Vietnam, accounting for a lot of the new arrivals.

1265
01:29:20,717 --> 01:29:21,017
[SPEAKER_43]: All right.

1266
01:29:21,037 --> 01:29:24,682
[SPEAKER_43]: And just as we dealt with Albania, I can give you... OK, let's go back to bases.

1267
01:29:24,722 --> 01:29:26,784
[SPEAKER_43]: You said you were stopping small boats.

1268
01:29:26,945 --> 01:29:28,507
[SPEAKER_43]: Boat crossings are going up this year.

1269
01:29:28,887 --> 01:29:31,110
[SPEAKER_43]: Let's talk about Rwanda.

1270
01:29:31,090 --> 01:29:32,412
[SPEAKER_43]: You acknowledge that, don't you?

1271
01:29:32,433 --> 01:29:34,396
[SPEAKER_43]: OK, let's move on.

1272
01:29:34,877 --> 01:29:37,743
[SPEAKER_43]: You will get the flights off the ground in July.

1273
01:29:37,783 --> 01:29:38,784
[SPEAKER_43]: You promised that.

1274
01:29:39,285 --> 01:29:39,466
[SPEAKER_43]: Yes.

1275
01:29:40,167 --> 01:29:41,770
[SPEAKER_43]: Flights off the ground, no ifs, no buts.

1276
01:29:42,191 --> 01:29:45,076
[SPEAKER_43]: How many flights and how many people are you going to send over the summer?

1277
01:29:45,337 --> 01:29:48,643
[SPEAKER_27]: What we've done is already started detaining people.

1278
01:29:48,623 --> 01:29:50,805
[SPEAKER_27]: Airfields on standby, planes are booked.

1279
01:29:51,306 --> 01:29:55,590
[SPEAKER_27]: The date for the first flight is out on the 24th, I think it is, of July.

1280
01:29:55,650 --> 01:30:01,695
[SPEAKER_27]: We haven't given more details beyond that to not compromise the operational security, but there will be a regular rhythm of flights, not just one.

1281
01:30:02,196 --> 01:30:09,102
[SPEAKER_27]: And the important point here is this is about establishing a deterrent, because I believe that if people come here illegally, they shouldn't be able to stay.

1282
01:30:09,443 --> 01:30:12,966
[SPEAKER_27]: We need to have somewhere safe to remove them, and that's how we will stop the boats.

1283
01:30:13,246 --> 01:30:14,968
[SPEAKER_27]: And that's what Rwanda is about.

1284
01:30:16,265 --> 01:30:19,811
[SPEAKER_43]: Can I just ask you one thing?

1285
01:30:20,352 --> 01:30:35,758
[SPEAKER_43]: If you were so confident about getting these flights off in July, that this was the apex, really, of stopping the boats, why did you call an election before voters could actually see it was happening?

1286
01:30:35,779 --> 01:30:35,859
[SPEAKER_43]: Why?

1287
01:30:35,879 --> 01:30:36,079
Because...

1288
01:30:39,383 --> 01:30:41,666
[SPEAKER_27]: Because an election is an important moment for our country.

1289
01:30:41,686 --> 01:30:44,851
[SPEAKER_27]: And my priority when I got this job was to restore economic stability.

1290
01:30:44,871 --> 01:30:51,039
[SPEAKER_27]: And we talked about bringing inflation down and getting the economy growing, and then being in a position, as we are now, to cut people's taxes.

1291
01:30:51,400 --> 01:30:58,870
[SPEAKER_27]: And for me, with that economic foundation established, it was the right moment to have an election to then discuss the future of our country.

1292
01:30:58,890 --> 01:31:00,513
[SPEAKER_27]: And this election is about the future.

1293
01:31:00,613 --> 01:31:01,414
[SPEAKER_27]: And you're right.

1294
01:31:01,514 --> 01:31:03,517
[SPEAKER_27]: On migration, there is a choice at this election.

1295
01:31:03,557 --> 01:31:04,859
[SPEAKER_27]: And elections have consequences.

1296
01:31:04,899 --> 01:31:06,681
[SPEAKER_27]: I've got a plan about what I want to do.

1297
01:31:06,801 --> 01:31:08,023
[SPEAKER_27]: And I'm going to come up to that.

1298
01:31:08,003 --> 01:31:12,915
[SPEAKER_27]: Keir Starmer doesn't agree with that plan and can't tell you what he would do with illegal migrants.

1299
01:31:12,935 --> 01:31:15,000
[SPEAKER_27]: And that's a choice for everyone here and everyone watching.

1300
01:31:15,060 --> 01:31:19,551
[SPEAKER_27]: If you want to stop the boats, there's a choice of how you think that needs to be dealt with.

1301
01:31:19,571 --> 01:31:21,155
[SPEAKER_27]: And I'm the one that's got an answer for you.

1302
01:31:21,175 --> 01:31:24,443
[SPEAKER_43]: And I would like to talk to you about a bigger issue that people are concerned about.

1303
01:31:24,423 --> 01:31:26,005
[SPEAKER_43]: which is legal migration.

1304
01:31:26,426 --> 01:31:29,871
[SPEAKER_43]: For many years, people were frustrated that immigration kept going up.

1305
01:31:30,332 --> 01:31:36,841
[SPEAKER_43]: It was the number one reason for voters in the run-up to the EU referendum, one of the main reasons for Brexit.

1306
01:31:37,102 --> 01:31:38,183
[SPEAKER_43]: That's right, isn't it?

1307
01:31:38,804 --> 01:31:39,806
[SPEAKER_43]: Immigration is too high.

1308
01:31:40,226 --> 01:31:45,914
[SPEAKER_43]: No, one of the reasons people voted for Brexit was to take back control of our borders, right?

1309
01:31:46,756 --> 01:31:47,016
[SPEAKER_26]: Yeah?

1310
01:31:47,036 --> 01:31:48,038
[SPEAKER_26]: Yes.

1311
01:31:48,278 --> 01:31:48,338
[SPEAKER_43]: OK.

1312
01:31:48,318 --> 01:31:58,370
[SPEAKER_43]: Yes, OK. Well, let's just go and look at the record, because what was the total net migration figure into the UK in the past three years?

1313
01:31:59,051 --> 01:32:00,032
[SPEAKER_43]: You'll have it there, so...

1314
01:32:00,372 --> 01:32:02,154
[SPEAKER_43]: But the audience, do you want me to tell them?

1315
01:32:02,575 --> 01:32:04,737
[SPEAKER_43]: I don't have the numbers off my head for the past three years.

1316
01:32:04,758 --> 01:32:07,160
[SPEAKER_43]: OK, it's 1.9 million people in the last three years.

1317
01:32:07,661 --> 01:32:16,992
[SPEAKER_43]: What was the total net migration figure in the last three years, running up to the 2016 referendum, when we had freedom of movement?

1318
01:32:18,322 --> 01:32:18,843
[SPEAKER_43]: Do you know it?

1319
01:32:19,084 --> 01:32:20,887
[SPEAKER_43]: I don't have it offhand.

1320
01:32:20,908 --> 01:32:22,230
[SPEAKER_43]: It was 836,000 people.

1321
01:32:24,736 --> 01:32:28,043
[SPEAKER_43]: And I'm sure many people in this room would have voted for Brexit.

1322
01:32:28,063 --> 01:32:32,432
[SPEAKER_43]: 70% of people in Grimsby voted for Brexit.

1323
01:32:34,302 --> 01:32:45,804
[SPEAKER_43]: How do you think they feel about that when they hear that net migration into this country has more than doubled in the last three years from before we left the European Union?

1324
01:32:46,304 --> 01:32:48,729
[SPEAKER_27]: It's too high.

1325
01:32:49,130 --> 01:32:50,552
[SPEAKER_27]: I've been very clear that it's too high.

1326
01:32:50,673 --> 01:32:53,959
[SPEAKER_27]: And I'm sure people feel frustrated and angry about it.

1327
01:32:53,979 --> 01:32:56,243
[SPEAKER_43]: You were the original Brexiteer.

1328
01:32:56,662 --> 01:32:59,706
[SPEAKER_43]: Well, you were one of the...

1329
01:32:59,746 --> 01:33:01,228
[SPEAKER_43]: Yes, I did support Brexit.

1330
01:33:01,248 --> 01:33:02,570
[SPEAKER_43]: You were always a Brexiteer.

1331
01:33:02,590 --> 01:33:04,893
[SPEAKER_43]: Yes, and I believe that was the right decision for our country.

1332
01:33:04,913 --> 01:33:06,275
[SPEAKER_43]: Can you see why people feel frustrated?

1333
01:33:06,295 --> 01:33:06,936
[SPEAKER_43]: Absolutely.

1334
01:33:07,217 --> 01:33:09,440
[SPEAKER_27]: I just said I'm sure people feel frustrated about that.

1335
01:33:09,840 --> 01:33:11,563
[SPEAKER_27]: And again, the numbers are too high.

1336
01:33:11,723 --> 01:33:12,684
[SPEAKER_27]: Of course they're too high.

1337
01:33:12,704 --> 01:33:16,309
[SPEAKER_27]: What I can tell you is what I've done since I've had this job, and that's last year...

1338
01:33:16,329 --> 01:33:16,950
[SPEAKER_55]: But you've been in charge.

1339
01:33:17,451 --> 01:33:18,833
[SPEAKER_27]: Yes, and the numbers are too high.

1340
01:33:19,073 --> 01:33:21,116
[SPEAKER_27]: I'm not making any bones about that.

1341
01:33:21,156 --> 01:33:22,838
[SPEAKER_27]: The numbers are too high, Beth.

1342
01:33:23,273 --> 01:33:29,286
[SPEAKER_27]: But what I can tell you is, what I've done in the time I've had this job is already start to bring them down because we've taken action to change things.

1343
01:33:29,607 --> 01:33:32,193
[SPEAKER_27]: So last year, the numbers were down by 10% already.

1344
01:33:32,293 --> 01:33:36,462
[SPEAKER_27]: And this year, the number of visas that we've issued is down by around a quarter.

1345
01:33:37,184 --> 01:33:41,974
[SPEAKER_27]: And the forecast show that we're on track to halve net migration in just over a year's time.

1346
01:33:41,954 --> 01:33:45,379
[SPEAKER_27]: So that shows and hopefully gives people some confidence we're now heading in the right direction.

1347
01:33:45,439 --> 01:33:58,720
[SPEAKER_27]: To give you an example of some of the things we've done, we've clamped down on abuse of the social care visa, tightened up the number of dependents that students can bring, and also raised the salary so that you have to earn £38,500 to come here on a work visa.

1348
01:33:59,201 --> 01:34:01,485
[SPEAKER_27]: Now, these measures are now starting to have an impact.

1349
01:34:01,505 --> 01:34:07,995
[SPEAKER_27]: You've seen that this year, as I said, numbers down by a quarter, forecast to fall by half overall for net migration.

1350
01:34:07,975 --> 01:34:10,038
[SPEAKER_43]: So are you making that pledge now?

1351
01:34:10,098 --> 01:34:12,882
[SPEAKER_43]: What's your promise to drive that migration down to?

1352
01:34:13,122 --> 01:34:21,854
[SPEAKER_27]: What we've said we will do is have actually a migration cap that's voted on in Parliament, so all your Members of Parliament will vote every year on the number of migrants that will come.

1353
01:34:21,874 --> 01:34:22,435
[SPEAKER_27]: What's the number?

1354
01:34:22,455 --> 01:34:27,942
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, as I said, the forecast at the moment is for the numbers to halve and then what we want to do is continue reducing it every year thereafter.

1355
01:34:27,922 --> 01:34:35,933
[SPEAKER_27]: But the key thing is here is there will be, for the first time, a legal cap on all migration so that we can guarantee that the numbers do continue to come down.

1356
01:34:35,993 --> 01:34:40,199
[SPEAKER_43]: David Cameron, 2010, tens of thousands reduced net migration.

1357
01:34:40,599 --> 01:34:44,364
[SPEAKER_43]: May 2017, Theresa May, reduced net migration to tens of thousands.

1358
01:34:44,665 --> 01:34:55,279
[SPEAKER_43]: Boris Johnson, 2019, committed to making sure overall numbers come down below the then net migration figure of just over a quarter of a million people.

1359
01:34:55,259 --> 01:35:00,527
[SPEAKER_43]: Why should anyone believe anything that you say on immigration?

1360
01:35:06,548 --> 01:35:17,709
[SPEAKER_27]: And I can completely understand people's cynicism about this, but you can add to the end of that list, since I've been in charge, numbers down 10% and visas issued this year down by a quarter.

1361
01:35:18,170 --> 01:35:18,530
[SPEAKER_27]: OK.

1362
01:35:18,550 --> 01:35:27,427
[SPEAKER_27]: So I've had this job for 18 months, numbers were down last year, they're down considerably at the start of this year and they will keep coming down because of the measures that I've already announced.

1363
01:35:27,447 --> 01:35:30,312
[SPEAKER_43]: 1.9 million people in the last three years, OK.

1364
01:35:30,292 --> 01:35:33,057
[SPEAKER_43]: But it's, you know, that's the record.

1365
01:35:33,778 --> 01:35:34,840
[SPEAKER_43]: Let's go on to tax.

1366
01:35:35,321 --> 01:35:40,089
[SPEAKER_43]: You say that you will cut taxes, as at your manifesto launch yesterday.

1367
01:35:40,149 --> 01:35:54,554
[SPEAKER_43]: Our economics editor, Ed Conway, calculates that the tax burden on the country will be higher now, higher than it is now, under a future Conservative government, even taking into account your proposed tax cuts.

1368
01:35:54,574 --> 01:35:55,776
[SPEAKER_43]: That's right, isn't it?

1369
01:35:55,756 --> 01:36:00,041
[SPEAKER_27]: No, I haven't seen that analysis, and I'm not sure that that is right.

1370
01:36:00,101 --> 01:36:01,803
[SPEAKER_27]: What we announced yesterday and all...

1371
01:36:01,823 --> 01:36:02,464
[SPEAKER_27]: He said wrong.

1372
01:36:03,024 --> 01:36:08,731
[SPEAKER_27]: I haven't seen his analysis, so I can't comment on it because I haven't seen it.

1373
01:36:08,911 --> 01:36:22,746
[SPEAKER_27]: But what I can tell you is what our manifesto announced is, you know, tax cuts for people at every stage of their life, for people in work, for people who are setting up small businesses and self-employed, for those young people who want to buy their first home, for pensioners and for families.

1374
01:36:23,067 --> 01:36:25,189
[SPEAKER_27]: So tax cuts for people at every stage.

1375
01:36:25,169 --> 01:36:28,715
[SPEAKER_27]: of their lives, because I believe people should keep more of their hard-earned money.

1376
01:36:28,775 --> 01:36:30,518
[SPEAKER_27]: That's how you build financial security.

1377
01:36:30,558 --> 01:36:32,822
[SPEAKER_27]: And again, that's a choice for people of this election.

1378
01:36:32,923 --> 01:36:38,352
[SPEAKER_27]: I believe in cutting people's taxes, now that we're in a position to do so, having restored economic stability.

1379
01:36:38,392 --> 01:36:47,548
[SPEAKER_43]: Can I just have a moment of honesty about this, though, because today taxes as a proportion of national income are at 36.5%.

1380
01:36:47,528 --> 01:36:54,517
[SPEAKER_43]: they will be at 36.7% of national income by the end of the coming Parliament with all your changes.

1381
01:36:54,577 --> 01:37:03,428
[SPEAKER_43]: So I know that you have introduced tax cut, but overall, taxes will still be going up, won't they, under a Conservative government?

1382
01:37:03,448 --> 01:37:08,014
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, the tax burden is too high, and that is a reflection of the decision.

1383
01:37:08,034 --> 01:37:08,515
[SPEAKER_43]: That wasn't my question.

1384
01:37:08,775 --> 01:37:11,038
[SPEAKER_43]: Is it going up in the next Parliament?

1385
01:37:12,014 --> 01:37:12,795
[SPEAKER_27]: It will go up.

1386
01:37:13,076 --> 01:37:15,019
[SPEAKER_27]: Taxes for people will continue to come down.

1387
01:37:15,360 --> 01:37:17,784
[SPEAKER_27]: That's the manifesto that we've announced.

1388
01:37:17,804 --> 01:37:19,026
[SPEAKER_27]: I haven't seen Ed's analysis.

1389
01:37:19,106 --> 01:37:20,669
[SPEAKER_27]: It's very hard for me to comment on it there.

1390
01:37:20,689 --> 01:37:30,446
[SPEAKER_27]: But what I can tell you is that the tax cuts that we've announced reduce the tax burden by about 1 percentage point of GDP a year, compared to the spring budget last year.

1391
01:37:30,467 --> 01:37:32,470
[SPEAKER_43]: And he's run the numbers, and tax is still going up.

1392
01:37:32,450 --> 01:37:33,432
[SPEAKER_27]: I haven't seen his numbers.

1393
01:37:33,512 --> 01:37:34,454
[SPEAKER_27]: I can tell you my numbers.

1394
01:37:34,474 --> 01:37:35,135
[SPEAKER_27]: But I can give you a...

1395
01:37:35,155 --> 01:37:35,676
[SPEAKER_43]: So you're saying that...

1396
01:37:35,696 --> 01:37:43,632
[SPEAKER_43]: So hang on, just to be clear, you're saying that taxes as a proportion of national income will come down at the end of the next parliament under a Conservative government?

1397
01:37:43,652 --> 01:37:45,615
[SPEAKER_27]: The tax cuts that we announced yesterday...

1398
01:37:45,756 --> 01:37:47,539
[SPEAKER_27]: It's just a yes or no.

1399
01:37:47,519 --> 01:37:54,070
[SPEAKER_27]: I don't have a forecast for the economy of five years' time, but what I can tell you is stamp duty for first-time buyers, abolished.

1400
01:37:54,531 --> 01:37:56,955
[SPEAKER_27]: National insurance for self-employed, abolished.

1401
01:37:57,175 --> 01:38:01,362
[SPEAKER_27]: Further cuts for national insurance, the triple lock plus to cut taxes for pensioners.

1402
01:38:01,382 --> 01:38:03,165
[SPEAKER_27]: No, but these are the practical tax cuts.

1403
01:38:03,145 --> 01:38:06,389
[SPEAKER_27]: that will be delivered, and they'll impact everyone in a slightly different way.

1404
01:38:06,730 --> 01:38:10,154
[SPEAKER_27]: But the choice at this election is clear, because I want to keep cutting people's taxes.

1405
01:38:10,494 --> 01:38:12,196
[SPEAKER_27]: And look, you did mention the tax burden.

1406
01:38:12,256 --> 01:38:14,059
[SPEAKER_27]: I actually can have a second to address that.

1407
01:38:14,079 --> 01:38:24,632
[SPEAKER_27]: Of course it's high, but that's because I had to take decisions that were difficult as Chancellor after providing the support that we did during the pandemic for the NHS, for furlough, but also for energy bills.

1408
01:38:25,073 --> 01:38:31,000
[SPEAKER_27]: And the reasonable thing to do, the right thing to do for the country, is to make sure that we secure our future and pay that back.

1409
01:38:31,020 --> 01:38:32,562
[SPEAKER_43]: And that requires difficult decisions.

1410
01:38:32,542 --> 01:38:38,492
[SPEAKER_43]: Isn't the truth that your problem is broken promises and it's deeper than the last couple of years?

1411
01:38:38,632 --> 01:38:39,537
[SPEAKER_43]: It's Brexit too.

1412
01:38:39,899 --> 01:38:41,185
[SPEAKER_43]: It's migration.

1413
01:38:46,565 --> 01:38:47,487
[SPEAKER_43]: It's migration.

1414
01:38:47,527 --> 01:38:49,270
[SPEAKER_43]: The NHS was meant to get better.

1415
01:38:49,290 --> 01:38:53,598
[SPEAKER_43]: We all remember 350 million quid on the side of a bus, don't we?

1416
01:38:53,618 --> 01:38:55,080
[SPEAKER_43]: It's levelling up.

1417
01:38:55,100 --> 01:38:57,685
[SPEAKER_43]: It's a catalogue of broken promises.

1418
01:38:57,765 --> 01:39:04,477
[SPEAKER_43]: You must surely see why so many voters think it's time for you and the Conservatives to get your P45.

1419
01:39:04,918 --> 01:39:06,801
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, I can absolutely...

1420
01:39:11,742 --> 01:39:14,565
[SPEAKER_27]: Of course I can understand people's frustrations.

1421
01:39:14,625 --> 01:39:16,266
[SPEAKER_27]: It's been a very difficult few years.

1422
01:39:16,706 --> 01:39:24,594
[SPEAKER_27]: We've been through two once-in-a-century shocks, which have had an enormous impact on everyone, on public services, on people's standard of living.

1423
01:39:24,614 --> 01:39:25,374
[SPEAKER_27]: Of course it has.

1424
01:39:25,414 --> 01:39:34,142
[SPEAKER_27]: When energy bills double, when inflation goes up to 11%, when a pandemic shuts down our economy, with all the impact on everyone's livelihoods, of course that's taken its toll.

1425
01:39:34,563 --> 01:39:38,106
[SPEAKER_27]: But this election now is about the future, and I do believe that we've turned a corner.

1426
01:39:38,546 --> 01:39:41,749
[SPEAKER_27]: And I appreciate that people want to see positive change,

1427
01:39:41,729 --> 01:39:46,457
[SPEAKER_27]: And my only point would be that you don't get any change unless you've got a plan and you're prepared to do bold things.

1428
01:39:46,517 --> 01:39:49,181
[SPEAKER_27]: And that's what our manifesto sets out, a way to do that.

1429
01:39:49,341 --> 01:39:52,747
[SPEAKER_43]: Let me just ask you, we'll come to you in a moment.

1430
01:39:52,907 --> 01:39:54,029
[SPEAKER_43]: I've got running out of time.

1431
01:39:54,389 --> 01:39:55,711
[SPEAKER_43]: Now, I just want to ask you one more thing.

1432
01:39:55,731 --> 01:39:57,975
[SPEAKER_43]: You were once popular, you were dishy-wishy.

1433
01:39:58,876 --> 01:39:59,337
[SPEAKER_43]: Do you remember?

1434
01:39:59,938 --> 01:40:04,345
[SPEAKER_43]: Can you tell our audience something about you that might make them like you a bit more again?

1435
01:40:06,434 --> 01:40:15,742
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, actually, people seem to think I have a very kind of healthy lifestyle, and I go to the gym, and there's this obsession about my fasting.

1436
01:40:16,143 --> 01:40:23,149
