2297
02:40:36,550 --> 02:40:57,732
[SPEAKER_52]: speaking to people on the doorstep that they feel like they've been taken for granted for a very very long time and certainly as Liberal Democrats we're not going to take their votes for granted and so we'll be fighting every single day, day in day out until 10pm on polling day to make sure that we can persuade people to put their trust and their votes in us because we have a plan to fix our NHS, to tackle the cost of living crisis and to protect our local environment.

2298
02:40:59,129 --> 02:41:07,520
[SPEAKER_39]: So you say that we don't know the outcome of the election, which could mean that, you know, Labour get a majority that's much smaller than people are predicting, or even no majority at all.

2299
02:41:07,920 --> 02:41:11,565
[SPEAKER_39]: Would you be prepared to go into a coalition with the Labour Party?

2300
02:41:11,585 --> 02:41:13,047
[SPEAKER_39]: You say that parties need to be straight.

2301
02:41:13,067 --> 02:41:13,848
[SPEAKER_39]: What's your straight answer?

2302
02:41:16,792 --> 02:41:20,837
[SPEAKER_52]: Straight answer is I will not be thinking about anything beyond 10pm on polling day.

2303
02:41:21,217 --> 02:41:24,241
[SPEAKER_52]: Seriously, I think, you know, there are millions... That's not a straight answer.

2304
02:41:24,261 --> 02:41:24,522
[SPEAKER_00]: Come on.

2305
02:41:24,982 --> 02:41:26,284
[SPEAKER_52]: People are feeling...

2306
02:41:26,568 --> 02:41:31,097
[SPEAKER_52]: Well, it is a straight answer, because honestly, I've been in politics since 2008.

2307
02:41:31,117 --> 02:41:38,553
[SPEAKER_52]: And I've seen time and time again when political parties of all stripes start talking about and thinking about what's going to happen after an election.

2308
02:41:38,733 --> 02:41:42,180
[SPEAKER_52]: And when they do that, they end up losing votes in the meantime.

2309
02:41:42,160 --> 02:41:44,664
[SPEAKER_52]: We are absolutely determined not to do that.

2310
02:41:44,864 --> 02:41:49,631
[SPEAKER_52]: Our job in this election as Liberal Democrats is to unseat as many Conservative MPs as possible.

2311
02:41:49,891 --> 02:41:57,763
[SPEAKER_52]: We are the key challengers to the Conservatives in around 80 seats around the country and will keep campaigning until 10pm on polling day to unseat as many of them as possible.

2312
02:42:00,447 --> 02:42:01,408
[SPEAKER_39]: Thank you very much indeed.

2313
02:42:01,428 --> 02:42:05,434
[SPEAKER_39]: Daisy Cooper there, the Deputy Leader of the Liberal Democrats, speaking to us tonight.

2314
02:42:07,996 --> 02:42:12,501
[SPEAKER_39]: Right, well let's hear now from the woman of the hour, tonight's Inquisitor, our political editor Beth Fridby.

2315
02:42:12,521 --> 02:42:13,843
[SPEAKER_39]: I feel like I want to give you a hug.

2316
02:42:13,863 --> 02:42:16,325
[SPEAKER_43]: Oh, I think I need one Sophie, thank you.

2317
02:42:16,606 --> 02:42:17,447
[SPEAKER_43]: How are you doing?

2318
02:42:17,467 --> 02:42:18,768
[SPEAKER_43]: We're both in pink again.

2319
02:42:18,808 --> 02:42:19,389
[SPEAKER_39]: I can't believe it.

2320
02:42:19,409 --> 02:42:21,111
[SPEAKER_39]: This is our luck, isn't it?

2321
02:42:21,591 --> 02:42:28,039
[SPEAKER_39]: What was your sense, because we were watching it all here and through all the spin room, but what was your sense in the room of what happened?

2322
02:42:28,279 --> 02:42:32,063
[SPEAKER_43]: Well, there were a few things, like I think from

2323
02:42:32,043 --> 02:42:36,475
[SPEAKER_43]: Rishi Sunak, we got more emotion about the D-Day commemoration.

2324
02:42:36,516 --> 02:42:38,080
[SPEAKER_43]: He talked about how he felt bad.

2325
02:42:38,220 --> 02:42:47,065
[SPEAKER_43]: I think being in front of an audience made a real difference to both men because they were kind of used to being interviewed by me.

2326
02:42:47,045 --> 02:42:51,594
[SPEAKER_43]: But they weren't really talking to me, they were talking to the audience as well.

2327
02:42:51,654 --> 02:42:55,461
[SPEAKER_43]: I thought we got a bit more clarity about labour and tax.

2328
02:42:55,521 --> 02:43:00,430
[SPEAKER_43]: I don't know about you, Sophie, but I came away thinking, yeah, they're going to put up some taxes.

2329
02:43:00,470 --> 02:43:02,935
[SPEAKER_43]: And actually, he didn't deny that.

2330
02:43:02,975 --> 02:43:06,842
[SPEAKER_43]: He was clear about taxes for working people.

2331
02:43:06,822 --> 02:43:16,535
[SPEAKER_43]: In terms of the dynamics in the room and with the audience, I would say that it was hard going for Rishi Sunak.

2332
02:43:16,555 --> 02:43:31,395
[SPEAKER_43]: It's the first big public appearance since the D-Day commemorations and I think actually the strongest question from the audience around that was that lady who had been a conservative back when she said, I just don't know what to do anymore.

2333
02:43:31,375 --> 02:43:40,183
[SPEAKER_43]: For Starmer, I think there was a, but I should say, I also thought he, you know, he came and made the argument, and he's keeping fighting, and he's keeping going.

2334
02:43:40,804 --> 02:43:51,513
[SPEAKER_43]: For Starmer, I thought the most revealing moment for me, actually, Sophie, was he was doing the Q&A, and he said, when I'm in government, and I went, what?

2335
02:43:51,734 --> 02:43:55,397
[SPEAKER_43]: No, because you would have done the same, because you would have gone, whoa.

2336
02:43:55,457 --> 02:44:01,062
[SPEAKER_43]: Because every time you say, do you think you're going to win, he always says, if I'm,

2337
02:44:01,042 --> 02:44:02,488
[SPEAKER_43]: Lucky enough.

2338
02:44:02,589 --> 02:44:04,236
[SPEAKER_43]: I'm humble enough to learn everything.

2339
02:44:04,256 --> 02:44:06,365
[SPEAKER_43]: And I just went, whoa, so you are going to win.

2340
02:44:06,386 --> 02:44:07,310
[SPEAKER_43]: You think you are going to win.

2341
02:44:07,330 --> 02:44:08,193
[SPEAKER_43]: And he just went, whoa.

2342
02:44:08,575 --> 02:44:09,921
[SPEAKER_43]: So I think that was a...

2343
02:44:10,525 --> 02:44:19,278
[SPEAKER_43]: I think there's a change in dynamic here where Labour really are feeling more confident now.

2344
02:44:19,559 --> 02:44:26,129
[SPEAKER_43]: And for Starmer to do that, I felt it was one of those tiny things that probably other people wouldn't notice.

2345
02:44:26,149 --> 02:44:31,457
[SPEAKER_43]: But as Starmer watchers as we both were, that really stood out for me.

2346
02:44:31,477 --> 02:44:32,057
[SPEAKER_39]: Yeah, it's interesting.

2347
02:44:32,077 --> 02:44:33,039
[SPEAKER_39]: It's that confidence, isn't it?

2348
02:44:33,059 --> 02:44:35,082
[SPEAKER_39]: It's that confidence.

2349
02:44:35,062 --> 02:44:37,685
[SPEAKER_39]: Let me know, how did you prep for it?

2350
02:44:37,725 --> 02:44:39,548
[SPEAKER_39]: What was the half an hour before?

2351
02:44:39,588 --> 02:44:41,050
[SPEAKER_39]: Were you having cups of tea?

2352
02:44:41,110 --> 02:44:42,071
[SPEAKER_39]: Were you listening to Beyonce?

2353
02:44:42,271 --> 02:44:43,773
[SPEAKER_43]: What were you doing?

2354
02:44:44,414 --> 02:44:47,818
[SPEAKER_43]: The way you prepped for it, and Kay Burley always told me this.

2355
02:44:48,359 --> 02:44:50,242
[SPEAKER_43]: I hope she doesn't mind me spilling her advice.

2356
02:44:50,262 --> 02:44:51,363
[SPEAKER_43]: Sorry, Kay.

2357
02:44:51,824 --> 02:44:55,829
[SPEAKER_43]: She always said, fail to prepare, prepare to fail.

2358
02:44:56,329 --> 02:44:59,213
[SPEAKER_43]: This is my television motto and it's Kay's.

2359
02:44:59,193 --> 02:45:04,479
[SPEAKER_43]: I just prepared a lot so that by the time you get to do it, you're kind of ready to go.

2360
02:45:04,519 --> 02:45:04,759
[SPEAKER_43]: Yeah.

2361
02:45:04,779 --> 02:45:06,221
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, I'm going to let you go and take a breather.

2362
02:45:06,241 --> 02:45:06,501
[SPEAKER_39]: Thank you.

2363
02:45:06,581 --> 02:45:07,102
[SPEAKER_39]: Thank you very much.

2364
02:45:07,142 --> 02:45:09,284
[SPEAKER_39]: Beth Rigby speaking to us there.

2365
02:45:09,304 --> 02:45:18,874
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, we've been talking to Beth, we've been talking to people in the spin room and the politicians, of course, but really some of the people that matter more than any of those people is the audience here in Grimsby.

2366
02:45:18,894 --> 02:45:20,997
[SPEAKER_39]: How did the two leaders go down with them?

2367
02:45:21,457 --> 02:45:26,803
[SPEAKER_39]: We can cross now to Sarah Jamie, who is with a very, what's the word?

2368
02:45:26,783 --> 02:45:29,181
[SPEAKER_39]: vibrant audience in Grimsby.

2369
02:45:29,202 --> 02:45:30,330
[SPEAKER_39]: They didn't hold back.

2370
02:45:31,880 --> 02:45:32,621
[SPEAKER_33]: They certainly didn't.

2371
02:45:32,701 --> 02:45:33,982
[SPEAKER_33]: Three turned into four.

2372
02:45:34,022 --> 02:45:40,107
[SPEAKER_33]: They wanted you to stick around, Sophie, to tell you exactly what they thought of the two leaders who are on this stage tonight.

2373
02:45:40,127 --> 02:45:45,832
[SPEAKER_33]: Of course, it's all about what people watching at home made of what unfolded over the course of those 90 minutes.

2374
02:45:45,852 --> 02:45:51,757
[SPEAKER_33]: They were represented here by a live audience from Grimsby and across the UK, and I'm pleased to say four of them are with me.

2375
02:45:52,077 --> 02:45:52,738
[SPEAKER_33]: Thank you so much.

2376
02:45:52,778 --> 02:45:53,538
[SPEAKER_33]: Sharon, I'll start with you.

2377
02:45:53,558 --> 02:45:55,840
[SPEAKER_33]: We've got Sharon, Holly, Kerry and Humza here.

2378
02:45:56,561 --> 02:46:01,245
[SPEAKER_33]: Sharon, you opened the show with your question to Keir Starmer, and you're from here in Grimsby.

2379
02:46:01,225 --> 02:46:02,747
[SPEAKER_33]: It was a big opening question.

2380
02:46:02,847 --> 02:46:08,975
[SPEAKER_33]: It was about disadvantaged communities, like those here in Grimsby, and what Labour are going to do to help you.

2381
02:46:08,995 --> 02:46:10,937
[SPEAKER_33]: What did you think of his answer?

2382
02:46:10,957 --> 02:46:19,869
[SPEAKER_10]: I think that he gave me some of the answer, but I would have probably liked a bit more and more clarity.

2383
02:46:19,889 --> 02:46:25,596
[SPEAKER_10]: I was particularly impressed with the fact that he's recognising

2384
02:46:25,576 --> 02:46:34,815
[SPEAKER_10]: that he does need to bring it to a local level and that central government shouldn't be making all the decisions for local towns and cities.

2385
02:46:35,456 --> 02:46:45,677
[SPEAKER_10]: So using local councils to inform and advise how money should be sent in our own areas is really important, so I did like that.

2386
02:46:45,657 --> 02:47:01,236
[SPEAKER_10]: and I totally agree that we do need that business progress as well, that we need to grow the economy through businesses and supporting especially small businesses, something we really need to do here in Grimsby and giving our children those opportunities.

2387
02:47:01,216 --> 02:47:05,742
[SPEAKER_33]: So you've got some of the answers, and that's the constraint, isn't it, of a TV format?

2388
02:47:05,782 --> 02:47:09,606
[SPEAKER_33]: We only get 90 minutes to talk to both leaders, and there's so much to get through.

2389
02:47:09,927 --> 02:47:12,270
[SPEAKER_33]: Holly, so sorry, you didn't get to ask your question tonight.

2390
02:47:12,290 --> 02:47:15,233
[SPEAKER_33]: OK. And it was about a really important one as well, childcare.

2391
02:47:15,654 --> 02:47:15,914
[SPEAKER_33]: Yeah.

2392
02:47:15,934 --> 02:47:24,545
[SPEAKER_33]: But Sir Keir Starmer did touch on childcare when he talked about the potential tax on private schools, putting VAT on private schools.

2393
02:47:24,565 --> 02:47:28,590
[SPEAKER_33]: He said it's not a tax add-on, it's actually just getting rid of a tax break.

2394
02:47:28,925 --> 02:47:39,970
[SPEAKER_57]: Yeah, so I feel like the Labour Party in the last couple of days have actually made their plans quite clear of how they're gonna actually staff and create these childcare places.

2395
02:47:40,532 --> 02:47:47,187
[SPEAKER_57]: I particularly wanted to ask my question to Rishi Sunak because I don't think it's something that the Tory party have done so far.

2396
02:47:47,167 --> 02:48:01,362
[SPEAKER_57]: It's all well and good saying here's a few funded hours that you can all have, but if you're not funding it, you have no workforce strategy behind it, then, you know, all you're doing is creating a massive demand without the supply.

2397
02:48:01,422 --> 02:48:09,350
[SPEAKER_57]: So frustrating I didn't get to ask him what he's going to do about that loss of childcare places and how they're going to create those places.

2398
02:48:10,010 --> 02:48:14,575
[SPEAKER_57]: And it is disappointing that there is no mention of childcare in their manifesto whatsoever.

2399
02:48:14,555 --> 02:48:17,222
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, look, we've got 22 days left to go to polling day.

2400
02:48:17,243 --> 02:48:21,815
[SPEAKER_33]: I'm sure at some point we will get your question to the Prime Minister.

2401
02:48:22,337 --> 02:48:29,577
[SPEAKER_33]: Humza, you took on the big subject of the NHS, which, you know, got the audience sort of...

2402
02:48:29,557 --> 02:48:36,231
[SPEAKER_33]: Really buzzing because, you know, there was a point where both leaders mentioned their family, their personal connection to the NHS.

2403
02:48:36,271 --> 02:48:38,857
[SPEAKER_33]: There was a lot of eye-rolling, there was a lot of guffaws.

2404
02:48:39,157 --> 02:48:45,731
[SPEAKER_33]: We've heard it all before because everyone here has a particular affinity to the NHS, no more so than you and your family.

2405
02:48:45,811 --> 02:48:48,477
[SPEAKER_33]: What is it you asked and what is it you heard?

2406
02:48:48,457 --> 02:48:50,339
[SPEAKER_16]: So, yeah, I agree.

2407
02:48:50,399 --> 02:48:57,887
[SPEAKER_16]: I mean, what I asked was mainly in response to how we can sort of return to an NHS that we can be proud of.

2408
02:48:58,328 --> 02:49:03,614
[SPEAKER_16]: I feel over the last 14 years, the NHS has massively been degraded, completely underfunded.

2409
02:49:03,674 --> 02:49:05,616
[SPEAKER_16]: There's not been the attention that we really need.

2410
02:49:05,956 --> 02:49:10,481
[SPEAKER_16]: It was clear during the COVID pandemic that we weren't ready at all as a country for a pandemic.

2411
02:49:11,062 --> 02:49:12,724
[SPEAKER_16]: Who knows if we're ready for the next one?

2412
02:49:12,804 --> 02:49:16,268
[SPEAKER_16]: I mean, I've been in the NHS for about five years now.

2413
02:49:16,668 --> 02:49:18,210
[SPEAKER_16]: I worked throughout COVID.

2414
02:49:18,190 --> 02:49:24,799
[SPEAKER_16]: And you can see very, very clearly the lack of funding and the effects that it has on NHS.

2415
02:49:24,819 --> 02:49:30,768
[SPEAKER_33]: You told a really personal story as well about spending eight hours on a stretcher in a corridor, and I know you've got an operation tomorrow, so good luck for that.

2416
02:49:30,828 --> 02:49:31,408
[SPEAKER_33]: Thank you.

2417
02:49:31,428 --> 02:49:36,215
[SPEAKER_33]: And finally, Kerry, you asked about dentistry to Sir Keir Starmer.

2418
02:49:36,235 --> 02:49:39,359
[SPEAKER_33]: You've been waiting over a year to see a dentist.

2419
02:49:39,380 --> 02:49:44,046
[SPEAKER_33]: Did he give you a clear plan of, if he were to get the case number 10, what he'd do to help?

2420
02:49:44,347 --> 02:49:46,050
[SPEAKER_04]: Most respect to Sakia.

2421
02:49:47,172 --> 02:49:56,328
[SPEAKER_04]: It's OK for a politician to stand on a stage and give out numbers of how many new dentists are going to be trained, how much money is going to be invested.

2422
02:49:56,348 --> 02:49:59,995
[SPEAKER_04]: I would like to have heard where this money is going to be coming from.

2423
02:50:00,796 --> 02:50:03,360
[SPEAKER_04]: All we're hearing about is tax cuts.

2424
02:50:05,023 --> 02:50:07,688
[SPEAKER_04]: To me, if you do tax cuts,

2425
02:50:07,668 --> 02:50:09,151
[SPEAKER_04]: where's this money going to come from?

2426
02:50:09,652 --> 02:50:14,883
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm quite happy to have my tax increase so that we can go back to how we was with the NHS.

2427
02:50:14,903 --> 02:50:18,070
[SPEAKER_33]: But you need to know that it's going directly to the areas that need it most.

2428
02:50:18,110 --> 02:50:19,153
[SPEAKER_33]: Kerry, thank you so much.

2429
02:50:19,173 --> 02:50:19,934
[SPEAKER_33]: We've run out of time.

2430
02:50:20,255 --> 02:50:23,281
[SPEAKER_33]: As we keep talking about, there's so much to get through, there's never enough time.

2431
02:50:23,321 --> 02:50:24,424
[SPEAKER_33]: Thank you for being in our audience tonight.

2432
02:50:24,484 --> 02:50:25,947
[SPEAKER_33]: We're going to hand back to Sophie in the spin room.

2433
02:50:28,002 --> 02:50:29,986
[SPEAKER_39]: Sarah-Jane, thank you very much indeed.

2434
02:50:30,106 --> 02:50:34,534
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, tonight we've spoken to the Greens, Plaid Cymru, Reform UK and the Lib Dems.

2435
02:50:35,075 --> 02:50:40,786
[SPEAKER_39]: Next up, it is the SNP and I'm very pleased to say that we're joined now by the Deputy First Minister, Kate Forbes.

2436
02:50:40,846 --> 02:50:43,090
[SPEAKER_39]: What did she make of the Leaders event tonight?

2437
02:50:43,110 --> 02:50:44,813
[SPEAKER_39]: Who do you think came out on top?

2438
02:50:45,367 --> 02:50:46,088
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, good evening.

2439
02:50:46,349 --> 02:50:57,049
[SPEAKER_03]: And I think looking at the debate this evening, with only a passing mention of Scotland, voters are very angry with the Conservatives and they're very uninspired with Labour.

2440
02:50:57,109 --> 02:51:01,738
[SPEAKER_03]: And of course, in Scotland, there is an alternative to vote for the SNP.

2441
02:51:02,119 --> 02:51:07,830
[SPEAKER_03]: But there's still a lot of unanswered questions that we have, not least about our public finances.

2442
02:51:07,810 --> 02:51:10,976
[SPEAKER_03]: We know that in this election, voters really want to see change.

2443
02:51:11,036 --> 02:51:16,487
[SPEAKER_03]: They want to get rid of the Conservatives because they've given us austerity, Brexit and the cost of living crisis.

2444
02:51:17,008 --> 02:51:23,601
[SPEAKER_03]: And the question is whether Labour will double down on Tory austerity or do something different.

2445
02:51:23,781 --> 02:51:29,532
[SPEAKER_03]: And Sir Keir Starmer seemed pretty clear tonight that he was doubling down on Tory austerity.

2446
02:51:31,688 --> 02:51:37,418
[SPEAKER_39]: I'm interested in your take on the challenge of the public finances, if you like, after the next election.

2447
02:51:37,478 --> 02:51:41,745
[SPEAKER_39]: It's an area I know you've got experience in yourself in Scotland.

2448
02:51:42,707 --> 02:51:46,473
[SPEAKER_39]: Keir Starmer was really pressed by Beg Thrifty when it came to taxes.

2449
02:51:47,034 --> 02:51:52,684
[SPEAKER_39]: Do you think a Labour government would put up taxes and should they be a bit more honest about what that might look like?

2450
02:51:53,356 --> 02:51:55,699
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, I think they definitely should be honest.

2451
02:51:55,779 --> 02:52:01,828
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, they are engaged in a conspiracy of silence when it comes to the realities of our public finances.

2452
02:52:01,888 --> 02:52:05,493
[SPEAKER_03]: And that's not my words, that's the Institute for Fiscal Studies.

2453
02:52:05,994 --> 02:52:15,067
[SPEAKER_03]: We know that from the last Tory budget, the IFS were predicting about £18 billion worth of cuts to frontline public services.

2454
02:52:15,668 --> 02:52:22,317
[SPEAKER_03]: And what Labour have outlined is that where they are increasing revenue, it's all going on the new projects.

2455
02:52:22,297 --> 02:52:27,365
[SPEAKER_03]: which means there's still £18 billion worth of cuts baked in to our public services.

2456
02:52:27,445 --> 02:52:30,249
[SPEAKER_03]: Now, that's hugely concerning to voters in Scotland.

2457
02:52:30,890 --> 02:52:40,305
[SPEAKER_03]: In Scotland, we've tried to mitigate against that austerity with some progressive changes taxation, but Labour seem to be completely ignorant

2458
02:52:40,285 --> 02:52:46,114
[SPEAKER_03]: and disinterested in how we reverse 14 years of austerity to our public finances.

2459
02:52:46,595 --> 02:52:54,047
[SPEAKER_03]: And to quote the Labour Health Secretary, when it comes to devolved public services, all roads lead back to Westminster.

2460
02:52:54,428 --> 02:52:56,291
[SPEAKER_03]: So this really is a change election.

2461
02:52:56,691 --> 02:53:02,901
[SPEAKER_03]: Unfortunately, I don't think voters going down the Labour route are going to see much in the way of change.

2462
02:53:03,382 --> 02:53:05,365
[SPEAKER_03]: And we need strong Scottish voices

2463
02:53:05,345 --> 02:53:12,503
[SPEAKER_03]: SNP MPs to hold Labour's feet to the fire and make sure they don't forget about Scottish voters.

2464
02:53:14,204 --> 02:53:16,227
[SPEAKER_39]: Okay, Kate Forbes, thank you very much indeed.

2465
02:53:16,247 --> 02:53:17,668
[SPEAKER_39]: Always good to have you on the programme.

2466
02:53:17,728 --> 02:53:21,573
[SPEAKER_39]: Sorry we're very short for time today, but interesting to get your perspective.

2467
02:53:22,434 --> 02:53:30,985
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, we're talking to politicians, we're talking to the members of the audience, and now I think the thing that's really interesting is the polling that we've done.

2468
02:53:31,106 --> 02:53:36,212
[SPEAKER_39]: How has this debate, how has this leaders event changed public opinion, if at all?

2469
02:53:36,352 --> 02:53:38,575
[SPEAKER_39]: We can speak now to our Deputy Political Editor.

2470
02:53:38,555 --> 02:53:44,507
[SPEAKER_39]: Sam Coates, and also we've got you guys, Patrick English, standing by, who's been looking at some of that snap polling for us.

2471
02:53:44,947 --> 02:53:47,853
[SPEAKER_39]: Sam, the headline polling was quite something, wasn't it?

2472
02:53:48,234 --> 02:53:51,220
[SPEAKER_25]: I think today was quite possibly a major campaign moment.

2473
02:53:51,781 --> 02:53:55,768
[SPEAKER_25]: Look, we saw the images of Rishi Sunak looking somewhat crestfallen.

2474
02:53:56,029 --> 02:53:59,736
[SPEAKER_25]: We heard the audience, but the decisiveness

2475
02:53:59,716 --> 02:54:00,737
[SPEAKER_25]: of the viewing public.

2476
02:54:00,857 --> 02:54:04,842
[SPEAKER_25]: 64% said that Keir Starmer was the winner.

2477
02:54:04,862 --> 02:54:08,226
[SPEAKER_25]: 36% said that it was Rishi Sunak.

2478
02:54:08,246 --> 02:54:08,907
[SPEAKER_25]: A 2-1 margin.

2479
02:54:09,268 --> 02:54:10,469
[SPEAKER_25]: Incredibly painful.

2480
02:54:11,030 --> 02:54:19,040
[SPEAKER_25]: Look, Patrick's about to give us a lot of detail about the specifics underlining those headline figures, but this is not what they wanted to see.

2481
02:54:19,100 --> 02:54:24,306
[SPEAKER_25]: The election moved further into Keir Starmer's court because of what happened tonight in Grimsby.

2482
02:54:24,286 --> 02:54:28,121
[SPEAKER_39]: Yes, really the opposite of what they wanted when it comes to public opinion.

2483
02:54:28,382 --> 02:54:30,650
[SPEAKER_39]: Patrick, I can see you there holding a piece of paper.

2484
02:54:31,152 --> 02:54:32,457
[SPEAKER_39]: What numbers can you give us?

2485
02:54:32,504 --> 02:54:42,635
[SPEAKER_60]: Yes, I think the headline number is very striking, and then underneath that is another very striking number, in that one third of the debate watchers who voted Conservative in 2019 said that Starmer won.

2486
02:54:42,936 --> 02:54:45,539
[SPEAKER_39]: And these are people who voted Conservative at the last election?

2487
02:54:45,559 --> 02:54:46,019
[SPEAKER_60]: That's exactly it.

2488
02:54:46,039 --> 02:54:52,967
[SPEAKER_60]: These are people who voted Conservative, who backed Boris Johnson, who were part of that coalition that delivered a seat for every day of the year for Boris Johnson back in 2019.

2489
02:54:53,267 --> 02:54:57,432
[SPEAKER_60]: They told us tonight that it was Starmer who performed best.

2490
02:54:57,985 --> 02:55:03,354
[SPEAKER_39]: Do you see any way of the Conservative Party coming back at this stage in the campaign?

2491
02:55:03,374 --> 02:55:04,816
[SPEAKER_60]: It is getting very, very late indeed.

2492
02:55:04,836 --> 02:55:07,700
[SPEAKER_60]: I think some of the rest of the results speak to the problems that they face.

2493
02:55:07,741 --> 02:55:18,297
[SPEAKER_60]: Keir Starmer came off as more trustworthy, more likeable, more in touch with ordinary people, more prime ministerial, which is a big shift, a very important thing to note.

2494
02:55:18,337 --> 02:55:19,960
[SPEAKER_60]: He won on the issues of the economy,

2495
02:55:19,940 --> 02:55:22,242
[SPEAKER_60]: things that matter to young people and the NHS.

2496
02:55:22,262 --> 02:55:27,488
[SPEAKER_60]: The only place where there was, let's say, a crumb of silver lining for Rishi Sunak was on tax.

2497
02:55:27,648 --> 02:55:30,671
[SPEAKER_60]: And that, of course, has been something that the Conservatives have focused on a lot over the past week.

2498
02:55:30,972 --> 02:55:33,775
[SPEAKER_60]: And there, the debate watching public were very split on who performed best.

2499
02:55:34,475 --> 02:55:37,619
[SPEAKER_39]: A quick thought from you, Sam, as we're about to hand over to Gillian.

2500
02:55:37,739 --> 02:55:45,086
[SPEAKER_25]: We are halfway through this campaign now, but most of the major moments have happened, perhaps no bigger than the one tonight.

2501
02:55:45,607 --> 02:55:49,491
[SPEAKER_25]: Can Rishi Sunak do anything to save this campaign that he called?

2502
02:55:49,859 --> 02:55:52,122
[SPEAKER_39]: Thank you so much for being with us.

2503
02:55:52,223 --> 02:55:54,065
[SPEAKER_39]: Really interesting to get those numbers as well.

2504
02:55:54,105 --> 02:55:55,648
[SPEAKER_39]: Patrick English, Sam Cates, thank you.

2505
02:55:56,749 --> 02:56:04,341
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, we knew it could be a big moment in the campaign, but if that polling is anything to go by, then it is not the move that number 10 wanted.

2506
02:56:04,781 --> 02:56:08,487
[SPEAKER_39]: What a forensic evening we've had here on Sky News.

2507
02:56:08,607 --> 02:56:11,952
[SPEAKER_39]: It's been an extraordinarily forensic day.

2508
02:56:11,932 --> 02:56:16,322
[SPEAKER_39]: Those questions from Beth and of course the stellar audience here in Grimsby.

2509
02:56:16,342 --> 02:56:16,863
[SPEAKER_39]: Stay with us.

2510
02:56:17,244 --> 02:56:19,309
[SPEAKER_39]: News at 10 with Gillian Joseph is coming next.

2511
02:56:19,750 --> 02:56:25,523
[SPEAKER_39]: She is live here in Grimsby with a full roundup of what's happened here tonight and all of the day's other news.

2512
02:56:25,944 --> 02:56:27,729
[SPEAKER_39]: But that is it from us for now.

2513
02:56:27,829 --> 02:56:29,232
[SPEAKER_39]: That's it from me.

2514
02:57:38,990 --> 02:58:05,757
Yeah.

2515
02:58:34,188 --> 02:58:50,256
Yeah.

2516
02:59:03,736 --> 02:59:05,697
you

2517
02:59:48,252 --> 03:00:02,850
[SPEAKER_46]: It's ten o'clock.

2518
03:00:03,171 --> 03:00:10,079
[SPEAKER_46]: This is Sky News at ten, live from outside the Grimsby Town Hall, the home of the battle for number ten.

2519
03:00:11,020 --> 03:00:17,989
[SPEAKER_46]: Zakir Starmer and Rishi Sunak have pushed on the cost of living, the NHS, education and immigration.

2520
03:00:18,543 --> 03:00:19,504
[SPEAKER_27]: The numbers are too high.

2521
03:00:19,644 --> 03:00:20,626
[SPEAKER_27]: Of course they're too high.

2522
03:00:20,646 --> 03:00:24,431
[SPEAKER_27]: What I can tell you is what I've done since I've had this job, and that's last year.

2523
03:00:24,451 --> 03:00:25,352
[SPEAKER_27]: But he's been in charge.

2524
03:00:25,372 --> 03:00:26,774
[SPEAKER_27]: Yes, and the numbers are too high.

2525
03:00:26,994 --> 03:00:29,057
[SPEAKER_27]: I'm not making any bones about that.

2526
03:00:29,077 --> 03:00:31,080
[SPEAKER_31]: The numbers are too high, Beth.

2527
03:00:31,100 --> 03:00:37,168
[SPEAKER_31]: Well, nothing in our manifesto requires tax rises over and above those that we have specifically set out.

2528
03:00:37,469 --> 03:00:39,511
[SPEAKER_31]: So no tax rises in the next parliament?

2529
03:00:39,531 --> 03:00:41,935
[SPEAKER_31]: No tax rises needed in the plans in our manifesto.

2530
03:00:41,955 --> 03:00:42,656
[SPEAKER_31]: In the plans?

2531
03:00:42,996 --> 03:00:44,398
[SPEAKER_31]: No tax rises.

2532
03:00:45,813 --> 03:00:51,160
[SPEAKER_46]: After questions from Sky News and from the audience, tax was one of the main issues tonight.

2533
03:00:51,641 --> 03:00:56,046
[SPEAKER_46]: We will cut through what they said in our campaign check.

2534
03:00:56,066 --> 03:01:01,653
[SPEAKER_46]: We are in Grimsby, one of the key target towns of this general election campaign for both parties.

2535
03:01:03,556 --> 03:01:12,107
[SPEAKER_46]: On the campaign trail, the Green Party launches its manifesto, but is warned against its £70 billion tax hike on the wealthy.

2536
03:01:14,213 --> 03:01:21,162
[SPEAKER_46]: Also tonight on Sky News at 10, Sky News speaks to the family of an Israeli hostage rescued from Gaza.

2537
03:01:23,485 --> 03:01:31,715
[SPEAKER_46]: Jurors in the new Lucy Letby trial have been told her previous convictions should be taken into account as an important piece of evidence.

2538
03:01:34,239 --> 03:01:40,727
[SPEAKER_46]: And we'll take a first look at tomorrow's front pages in our press preview from 10.30 right through to midnight.

2539
03:01:48,723 --> 03:01:53,849
[SPEAKER_46]: Good evening and welcome to this very special Sky News at 10, live from Grimsby.

2540
03:01:53,869 --> 03:02:01,378
[SPEAKER_46]: Rishi Sunak and Sakhir Starmer have been trying to convince voters that they should get your vote in the upcoming general election.

2541
03:02:02,079 --> 03:02:10,950
[SPEAKER_46]: They've been questioned by audience members and by Sky's political editor, Beth Rigby, about tax, the NHS and immigration.

2542
03:02:10,930 --> 03:02:16,177
[SPEAKER_46]: Sakhir Sarma insisted he would not be raising taxes to fix public finances.

2543
03:02:16,618 --> 03:02:20,202
[SPEAKER_46]: He also promised to sit down and negotiate with the NHS.

2544
03:02:21,003 --> 03:02:29,715
[SPEAKER_46]: Rishi Sunak acknowledged that people were frustrated over immigration numbers since Brexit, but did give a date for the first flight to Rwanda.

2545
03:02:30,033 --> 03:02:41,268
[SPEAKER_46]: Coming up, we will be hearing from the audience, we will be testing out some of the claims made by the leaders and we will be bringing you the details of that poll to find out who came out on top.

2546
03:02:42,029 --> 03:02:47,877
[SPEAKER_46]: But first, Sky's deputy political editor Sam Coates reports now on the battle for number 10.

2547
03:02:47,897 --> 03:02:56,108
[SPEAKER_25]: 200 miles from Downing Street, the battle for number 10 now playing out in Grimsby.

2548
03:02:56,729 --> 03:03:01,981
[SPEAKER_25]: The two men vying for the keys to that door know they need to win voters like these.

2549
03:03:02,703 --> 03:03:06,672
[SPEAKER_25]: This place voted Tory last time, but now Labour wants it back.

2550
03:03:07,133 --> 03:03:10,902
[SPEAKER_25]: Keir Starmer first up to be interviewed by Sky's political editor, Beth Rigby.

2551
03:03:11,283 --> 03:03:15,092
[SPEAKER_25]: He wants to convince this audience and the country he can be trusted.

2552
03:03:15,072 --> 03:03:18,558
[SPEAKER_25]: but it's a long journey since his last election campaign.

2553
03:03:18,939 --> 03:03:23,767
[SPEAKER_43]: You said, I do think Jeremy Corbyn would make a great Prime Minister.

2554
03:03:24,268 --> 03:03:26,111
[SPEAKER_43]: Jeremy Corbyn, did you mean that?

2555
03:03:26,632 --> 03:03:29,357
[SPEAKER_43]: I was certain that we would lose the 2019 election.

2556
03:03:29,397 --> 03:03:31,120
[SPEAKER_43]: Did you not mean it when you said it?

2557
03:03:31,140 --> 03:03:32,422
[SPEAKER_43]: I was certain that we would lose.

2558
03:03:32,682 --> 03:03:36,449
[SPEAKER_43]: Now will you actually say, yes, I thought that, or I didn't think that at the time?

2559
03:03:36,589 --> 03:03:38,312
[SPEAKER_43]: Just be honest.

2560
03:03:38,613 --> 03:03:41,997
[SPEAKER_31]: I honestly didn't think that we had a chance of winning that election.

2561
03:03:42,017 --> 03:03:42,818
[SPEAKER_43]: So you said it anyway.

2562
03:03:43,219 --> 03:03:45,101
[SPEAKER_25]: Tax, a constant issue in this campaign.

2563
03:03:45,321 --> 03:03:46,923
[SPEAKER_43]: Do Labour's plans add up?

2564
03:03:46,943 --> 03:03:49,546
[SPEAKER_43]: But the Tories say you will go further.

2565
03:03:49,967 --> 03:03:51,008
[SPEAKER_43]: They're right, aren't they?

2566
03:03:51,289 --> 03:03:51,989
[SPEAKER_43]: You will.

2567
03:03:52,009 --> 03:03:56,935
[SPEAKER_31]: Well, the first thing I'd say is the Tories are in no position to lecture anyone about tax rises.

2568
03:03:57,296 --> 03:03:59,018
[SPEAKER_31]: We've got the highest tax burden.

2569
03:04:00,128 --> 03:04:02,691
[SPEAKER_31]: So, no tax rises in the next Parliament?

2570
03:04:02,991 --> 03:04:05,373
[SPEAKER_31]: No tax rises needed in the plans in our manifesto.

2571
03:04:05,393 --> 03:04:06,154
[SPEAKER_31]: In the plans?

2572
03:04:06,435 --> 03:04:08,817
[SPEAKER_31]: No tax rises for working people.

2573
03:04:08,877 --> 03:04:12,160
[SPEAKER_31]: That's income tax, national insurance, and VAT.

2574
03:04:12,180 --> 03:04:13,882
[SPEAKER_43]: OK, so you're not ruling out.

2575
03:04:14,223 --> 03:04:20,749
[SPEAKER_43]: I just decode that for you guys, because when a politician says, no plans, it does mean I might.

2576
03:04:21,110 --> 03:04:22,731
[SPEAKER_43]: Well, Beth, I'm not...

2577
03:04:22,751 --> 03:04:24,133
[SPEAKER_43]: I've done this a bit.

2578
03:04:24,153 --> 03:04:24,313
[SPEAKER_43]: It does.

2579
03:04:25,610 --> 03:04:30,100
[SPEAKER_25]: No plans for a wealth tax, but he is a top earner himself.

2580
03:04:30,822 --> 03:04:33,528
[SPEAKER_25]: Would you personally be happy to pay more tax?

2581
03:04:33,729 --> 03:04:34,350
[SPEAKER_25]: Yes, of course.

2582
03:04:35,032 --> 03:04:38,078
[SPEAKER_25]: A hint of domestic life and personal troubles.

2583
03:04:38,099 --> 03:04:40,384
[SPEAKER_43]: Was Vic, your wife, not keen for you to do this?

2584
03:04:40,484 --> 03:04:41,687
[SPEAKER_31]: No, she wasn't at all.

2585
03:04:41,787 --> 03:04:42,268
[SPEAKER_31]: She thought...

2586
03:04:42,248 --> 03:04:50,520
[SPEAKER_31]: It would be far better to continue being a lawyer on a reasonable salary and not have all of the challenges that you get as a politician.

2587
03:04:50,540 --> 03:04:56,269
[SPEAKER_31]: But I was clear in my mind I wanted to come into politics because I wanted to serve my country.

2588
03:04:56,289 --> 03:04:59,654
[SPEAKER_25]: The audience asking questions too, and some not holding back.

2589
03:04:59,954 --> 03:05:05,202
[SPEAKER_22]: Over the last year, I feel like you've formed into more of a politician than the person that I would have voted for to run the country.

2590
03:05:06,123 --> 03:05:08,627
[SPEAKER_22]: You seem more like a political robot.

2591
03:05:09,113 --> 03:05:13,031
[SPEAKER_22]: How are you... How are you going to convince others like me to vote for you?

2592
03:05:13,674 --> 03:05:16,868
[SPEAKER_30]: Well, erm...

2593
03:05:16,888 --> 03:05:17,571
[SPEAKER_30]: The most...

2594
03:05:18,732 --> 03:05:21,377
[SPEAKER_31]: Look, all I can say...

2595
03:05:21,397 --> 03:05:24,042
[SPEAKER_31]: I went to run the Crown Prosecution Service.

2596
03:05:24,062 --> 03:05:25,084
[SPEAKER_31]: You referenced that.

2597
03:05:25,164 --> 03:05:27,568
[SPEAKER_31]: I was the chief prosecutor for five years.

2598
03:05:27,829 --> 03:05:28,209
[SPEAKER_31]: Apologies.

2599
03:05:28,249 --> 03:05:30,594
[SPEAKER_31]: Heyman, did he convince you, yes or no?

2600
03:05:31,135 --> 03:05:38,628
[SPEAKER_22]: I hope you don't answer the questions... How you answer the questions, I hope you never answered them the way that you did when you were a solicitor, because you don't seem to answer the question.

2601
03:05:39,430 --> 03:05:39,710
[SPEAKER_42]: OK.

2602
03:05:39,730 --> 03:05:40,572
[SPEAKER_42]: I'm going to...

2603
03:05:42,745 --> 03:05:47,091
[SPEAKER_25]: Some frustration at the lack of detail, but this man not giving much away.

2604
03:05:47,552 --> 03:05:50,676
[SPEAKER_25]: Rishi Sunak needs a big win in this room and beyond.

2605
03:05:51,017 --> 03:05:53,721
[SPEAKER_25]: But can he escape the chaotic record of his party?

2606
03:05:54,021 --> 03:06:00,190
[SPEAKER_43]: In this parliament, we've had three prime ministers, five chancellors, five home secretaries, six health secretaries.

2607
03:06:00,630 --> 03:06:07,420
[SPEAKER_43]: How do we know that if you won the general election, you'd still be prime minister in a year's time?

2608
03:06:14,437 --> 03:06:17,982
[SPEAKER_27]: Look, I can appreciate people's frustrations.

2609
03:06:18,022 --> 03:06:20,044
[SPEAKER_27]: Of course, we haven't got everything right.

2610
03:06:20,064 --> 03:06:21,166
[SPEAKER_27]: I don't think any government does.

2611
03:06:21,226 --> 03:06:23,529
[SPEAKER_27]: And I know it's been very difficult for many people.

2612
03:06:24,009 --> 03:06:29,937
[SPEAKER_27]: But what I can do is work as hard as I can to deliver the stability that I said I would.

2613
03:06:29,977 --> 03:06:31,419
[SPEAKER_27]: And I've had this job for 18 months.

2614
03:06:31,859 --> 03:06:34,463
[SPEAKER_25]: The PM tested like rarely before on his promises.

2615
03:06:35,083 --> 03:06:37,086
[SPEAKER_25]: One, to get waiting lists down.

2616
03:06:37,066 --> 03:06:37,887
[SPEAKER_43]: No, just before we...

2617
03:06:37,948 --> 03:06:40,011
[SPEAKER_43]: Cutting NHS waiting lists, that's pledge four.

2618
03:06:40,552 --> 03:06:43,537
[SPEAKER_43]: When you made the promise, the list was at 7.21 million.

2619
03:06:43,577 --> 03:06:46,061
[SPEAKER_43]: It's now at 7.54 million cases.

2620
03:06:46,121 --> 03:06:46,682
[SPEAKER_43]: It's gone up.

2621
03:06:47,324 --> 03:06:47,804
[SPEAKER_27]: Yes, it has.

2622
03:06:48,686 --> 03:06:53,394
[SPEAKER_27]: Yes, I was very... We've not made as much progress on cutting waiting lists as I would have liked.

2623
03:06:54,015 --> 03:06:54,636
[SPEAKER_27]: The point...

2624
03:06:55,038 --> 03:07:00,488
[SPEAKER_25]: Rishi Sunak facing boos, losing some in the crowd and, at times, looking crestfallen.

2625
03:07:00,508 --> 03:07:03,032
[SPEAKER_25]: Immigration, the next challenge for him to overcome.

2626
03:07:03,333 --> 03:07:10,144
[SPEAKER_43]: Why did you call an election before voters could actually see it was happening?

2627
03:07:10,165 --> 03:07:10,245
Why?

2628
03:07:10,265 --> 03:07:10,465
Because...

2629
03:07:13,583 --> 03:07:15,866
[SPEAKER_27]: Because an election is an important moment for our country.

2630
03:07:15,906 --> 03:07:19,050
[SPEAKER_27]: And my priority when I got this job was to restore economic stability.

2631
03:07:19,070 --> 03:07:25,239
[SPEAKER_27]: And we talked about bringing inflation down and getting the economy growing, and then being in a position, as we are now, to cut people's taxes.

2632
03:07:25,639 --> 03:07:28,643
[SPEAKER_25]: Legal immigration, another example of failure.

2633
03:07:28,964 --> 03:07:30,926
[SPEAKER_25]: And again, the audience hostile.

2634
03:07:31,227 --> 03:07:40,519
[SPEAKER_43]: What was the total net migration figure in the last three years, running up to the 2016 referendum, when we had freedom of movement?

2635
03:07:41,883 --> 03:07:42,404
[SPEAKER_43]: Do you know it?

2636
03:07:42,645 --> 03:07:44,450
[SPEAKER_43]: I don't have it offhand.

2637
03:07:44,470 --> 03:07:45,794
[SPEAKER_43]: It was 836,000 people.

2638
03:07:46,075 --> 03:07:51,591
[SPEAKER_43]: And I'm sure many people in this room would have voted for Brexit.

2639
03:07:51,631 --> 03:07:55,943
[SPEAKER_43]: 70% of people in Grimsby voted for Brexit.

2640
03:07:57,863 --> 03:08:09,358
[SPEAKER_43]: How do you think they feel about that when they hear that net migration into this country has more than doubled in the last three years from before we left the European Union?

2641
03:08:09,858 --> 03:08:12,281
[SPEAKER_27]: It's too high.

2642
03:08:12,682 --> 03:08:14,104
[SPEAKER_27]: I've been very clear that it's too high.

2643
03:08:14,224 --> 03:08:17,288
[SPEAKER_25]: And I'm sure people feel frustrated and angry about it.

2644
03:08:17,909 --> 03:08:18,910
[SPEAKER_25]: Trying to show he gets it.

2645
03:08:19,230 --> 03:08:22,875
[SPEAKER_25]: But after 14 years in power, the audience seemed low on patience.

2646
03:08:22,855 --> 03:08:27,803
[SPEAKER_16]: You say that you're coming from an NHS background and you have this instilled value of caring for the NHS.

2647
03:08:27,883 --> 03:08:31,529
[SPEAKER_16]: How are we going to do that if you try and undermine it at every level?

2648
03:08:33,412 --> 03:08:35,234
[SPEAKER_27]: With greatest respect, that's not what we're doing.

2649
03:08:35,615 --> 03:08:37,638
[SPEAKER_27]: We're investing record sums into it.

2650
03:08:38,059 --> 03:08:40,563
[SPEAKER_27]: We're training more doctors and nurses than we ever have.

2651
03:08:40,723 --> 03:08:44,509
[SPEAKER_27]: And there are more doctors and nurses in the NHS today than it's also had.

2652
03:08:44,489 --> 03:08:46,753
[SPEAKER_49]: Because there's shortages of the staff already.

2653
03:08:46,994 --> 03:08:48,296
[SPEAKER_49]: We're short of radiographers.

2654
03:08:48,817 --> 03:08:52,825
[SPEAKER_49]: All the trades, all the different specialities throughout the hospitals, we're short of staff.

2655
03:08:53,086 --> 03:08:58,336
[SPEAKER_49]: So building another building that's going to move it from the hospital is not going to cure the problem.

2656
03:08:59,879 --> 03:09:00,540
[SPEAKER_49]: It's just going to make it worse.

2657
03:09:00,520 --> 03:09:03,746
[SPEAKER_25]: It was a bruising experience for the Prime Minister.

2658
03:09:03,927 --> 03:09:06,572
[SPEAKER_25]: His campaign needed a win, but it didn't come here.

2659
03:09:07,253 --> 03:09:12,002
[SPEAKER_25]: An exclusive snap poll suggests a decisive verdict.

2660
03:09:12,042 --> 03:09:17,412
[SPEAKER_25]: 64% said that Keir Starmer won, just 36% said Rishi Sunak.

2661
03:09:17,733 --> 03:09:20,959
[SPEAKER_25]: Not the result the Prime Minister needed.

2662
03:09:21,496 --> 03:09:24,421
[SPEAKER_25]: Halfway through this campaign, tonight a major moment.

2663
03:09:24,722 --> 03:09:26,845
[SPEAKER_25]: Both sides will try to claim their man won.

2664
03:09:27,246 --> 03:09:30,692
[SPEAKER_25]: But the reactions in the room and from the viewing public tell a different story.

2665
03:09:31,053 --> 03:09:33,537
[SPEAKER_25]: Can Rishi Sunak turn it around from here?

2666
03:09:34,018 --> 03:09:35,961
[SPEAKER_25]: Sam Coates, Sky News, Grimsby.

2667
03:09:38,692 --> 03:09:39,593
[SPEAKER_46]: So, who won?

2668
03:09:39,773 --> 03:09:43,158
[SPEAKER_46]: YouGov, as you've heard, have already done their polling, and here it is.

2669
03:09:43,638 --> 03:09:51,709
[SPEAKER_46]: The question was, leaving aside your own party preference, who do you think performed best overall in tonight's televised leaders event?

2670
03:09:52,590 --> 03:09:57,797
[SPEAKER_46]: 36% Rishi Sunak, 64% Sakhir Starmer.

2671
03:09:59,870 --> 03:10:07,203
[SPEAKER_46]: As we saw tonight, we had a live studio audience made up of people who live locally and those who travelled for the event.

2672
03:10:08,064 --> 03:10:12,492
[SPEAKER_46]: Great Grimsby and Cleethorpes is a key battleground for the Conservatives and for Labour.

2673
03:10:13,053 --> 03:10:17,440
[SPEAKER_46]: It could create a swing that can impact the outcome of the election.

2674
03:10:17,420 --> 03:10:31,035
[SPEAKER_46]: Sky's national correspondent Tom Parmenter has spent the last few weeks here finding out what matters most to the people and today he's been gauging the audience response before and after we heard from Rishi Sunak and Keir Starmer.

2675
03:10:33,077 --> 03:10:37,602
[SPEAKER_20]: Who would walk into Grimsby Town Hall and really test the leaders?

2676
03:10:38,723 --> 03:10:42,567
[SPEAKER_20]: Members of the public looking for straight answers.

2677
03:10:42,665 --> 03:10:54,961
[SPEAKER_10]: I really care about Grinsby and I'm tired of the inequalities that we're experiencing and I'm tired about the fact that we seem to have been forgotten and that needs to change.

2678
03:10:55,902 --> 03:11:08,138
[SPEAKER_28]: Things aren't going well in so many different areas, the NHS, care, housing, mortgages, cost of living, it's all impacting real people, my family included.

2679
03:11:08,779 --> 03:11:11,322
[SPEAKER_28]: People were drawn from across the nation.

2680
03:11:11,470 --> 03:11:18,072
[SPEAKER_44]: I'm undecided and I feel like a lot of the country is undecided, so I just think these are opportunities they really need to grasp.

2681
03:11:18,473 --> 03:11:22,739
[SPEAKER_20]: used to be very loyal to the Conservative Party but for you that's gone?

2682
03:11:23,039 --> 03:11:24,141
[SPEAKER_50]: Yeah, gone completely.

2683
03:11:24,702 --> 03:11:36,599
[SPEAKER_50]: I would really like to come out of the debate tonight knowing who I'm going to vote for but I have come with an open mind to try and see if these two gentlemen can convince me who should be the next leader of the country.

2684
03:11:36,619 --> 03:11:46,793
[SPEAKER_20]: Everyone wanted their say but inside the audience had the chance to come face to face with the two men vying to become Prime Minister.

2685
03:11:48,629 --> 03:11:50,632
[SPEAKER_20]: As they left, we caught up with them.

2686
03:11:51,132 --> 03:11:57,842
[SPEAKER_10]: One thing I was impressed is when Keir Starmer did say that he would like to, you know, we need to bring it back to local level.

2687
03:11:58,122 --> 03:12:07,355
[SPEAKER_10]: We need to bring it to our local councils and make those decisions rather than central government dictating all the time what we should be doing.

2688
03:12:07,535 --> 03:12:08,697
[SPEAKER_20]: So who won the battle here?

2689
03:12:10,077 --> 03:12:22,824
[SPEAKER_44]: I think the people, not to sound political, but they asked the questions that they wanted to ask and the answers that these two gave will decide what people want to vote for.

2690
03:12:23,085 --> 03:12:25,550
[SPEAKER_20]: You were part of a very unforgiving audience there.

2691
03:12:26,271 --> 03:12:26,612
[SPEAKER_28]: We were.

2692
03:12:26,652 --> 03:12:29,959
[SPEAKER_28]: It was hard for both of them and I appreciate what they did.

2693
03:12:30,327 --> 03:12:35,577
[SPEAKER_28]: And I also think the format was so much better in having them not shouting over the top of each other.

2694
03:12:35,878 --> 03:12:41,529
[SPEAKER_28]: We did actually get to sort of the humanity of them a little bit and hear a little bit more.

2695
03:12:41,910 --> 03:12:44,455
[SPEAKER_28]: And perhaps you read between the lines of the things they don't answer.

2696
03:12:44,956 --> 03:12:46,459
[SPEAKER_20]: Many were left wanting more.

2697
03:12:46,820 --> 03:12:49,585
[SPEAKER_20]: For you, the battle for number 10.

2698
03:12:49,565 --> 03:12:50,066
[SPEAKER_20]: It's still on.

2699
03:12:50,626 --> 03:12:51,287
[SPEAKER_20]: It's still on.

2700
03:12:51,387 --> 03:12:52,789
[SPEAKER_50]: It's still on for me, yeah, absolutely.

2701
03:12:53,229 --> 03:12:54,771
[SPEAKER_20]: This was a tough crowd.

2702
03:12:55,451 --> 03:12:57,734
[SPEAKER_20]: For some, it has made a difference.

2703
03:12:58,515 --> 03:13:01,518
[SPEAKER_20]: Just three weeks before the nation decides.

2704
03:13:02,739 --> 03:13:05,282
[SPEAKER_20]: Tom Parmenter, Sky News, Grimsby.

2705
03:13:07,485 --> 03:13:10,648
[SPEAKER_46]: Well, our deputy political editor, Sam Coates, joins me now.

2706
03:13:10,949 --> 03:13:12,650
[SPEAKER_46]: And Sam, you've been here throughout the course of the day.

2707
03:13:12,690 --> 03:13:16,855
[SPEAKER_46]: Just how important was tonight for both men?

2708
03:13:17,915 --> 03:13:22,862
[SPEAKER_25]: Look, I think, Gillian, I think we had a really critical campaign moment this evening.

2709
03:13:23,523 --> 03:13:29,232
[SPEAKER_25]: Look, first we saw from Keir Starmer, and we did learn things about him.

2710
03:13:29,272 --> 03:13:37,304
[SPEAKER_25]: We saw his determination not to give very much more away, but in the context of somebody who has changed his mind repeatedly as a politician.

2711
03:13:37,905 --> 03:13:45,677
[SPEAKER_25]: So I think the interview with my colleague Beth Rigby drew out the question, are we really sure what a Keir Starmer premiership would look like?

2712
03:13:46,872 --> 03:13:54,051
[SPEAKER_25]: But for me, the transformative moment of tonight was the performance of the Prime Minister, Rishi Sunak.

2713
03:13:54,071 --> 03:14:03,936
[SPEAKER_25]: Whether it was the reaction of those in the room, the reaction of those viewers at home that decisively decided that he was not the winner by a 2-1 margin, or even just...

2714
03:14:03,916 --> 03:14:04,838
[SPEAKER_25]: The look on his face.

2715
03:14:05,439 --> 03:14:10,709
[SPEAKER_25]: You'll have seen now the pictures of Rishi Sunak looking almost haunted, perhaps crestfallen.

2716
03:14:11,290 --> 03:14:19,045
[SPEAKER_25]: He really struggled on questions of his own priorities and his own delivery and his own promises.

2717
03:14:19,566 --> 03:14:23,294
[SPEAKER_25]: And I think it was very instructive to watch the way that he handled that.

2718
03:14:23,354 --> 03:14:26,059
[SPEAKER_25]: And you could feel the audience.

2719
03:14:26,039 --> 03:14:30,764
[SPEAKER_25]: uncomfortable with the answers and wanting to push back about the way that he was doing it.

2720
03:14:30,784 --> 03:14:34,709
[SPEAKER_25]: I felt that Rishi Sunak knew that too, and at points it was a painful watch.

2721
03:14:35,049 --> 03:14:49,345
[SPEAKER_25]: We are exactly halfway through this general election campaign right now, Gillian, and I'm really starting to wonder if after that, in that room behind us, in that town hall, Rishi Sunak can do anything to pull back this election campaign.

2722
03:14:49,925 --> 03:14:54,190
[SPEAKER_46]: Would you go as far as to say that he seems to be a broken man?

2723
03:14:56,077 --> 03:15:07,508
[SPEAKER_25]: I think I would encourage every viewer to watch the slightly haunted figure that we saw on that very big stage today and draw their own conclusions.

2724
03:15:08,028 --> 03:15:11,892
[SPEAKER_25]: I think the evidence was there across 45 minutes.

2725
03:15:12,793 --> 03:15:15,715
[SPEAKER_25]: And the verdict of our viewers was clear.

2726
03:15:16,556 --> 03:15:24,784
[SPEAKER_25]: It feels really hard to see him instilling the confidence that you would need to be to continue in the job as Prime Minister after what we witnessed tonight.

2727
03:15:25,270 --> 03:15:26,594
[SPEAKER_46]: OK, Sam, thanks very much for the moment.

2728
03:15:26,614 --> 03:15:29,021
[SPEAKER_46]: But do stay right here next to me.

2729
03:15:29,261 --> 03:15:31,588
[SPEAKER_46]: We're going to stay with Sam when we come back.

2730
03:15:31,608 --> 03:15:33,413
[SPEAKER_46]: But I want to get more of our analysis now.

2731
03:15:33,895 --> 03:15:36,181
[SPEAKER_46]: Ed Conway is at the screen tonight.

2732
03:15:36,542 --> 03:15:40,393
[SPEAKER_46]: And Ed, there was a focus on tax for both party leaders, wasn't there?

2733
03:15:40,593 --> 03:15:41,755
[SPEAKER_14]: Yeah, there was a big focus on tax.

2734
03:15:41,815 --> 03:15:48,364
[SPEAKER_14]: It's interesting, there wasn't like one single number that dominated this like it did in the first time they debated that £2,000 figure.

2735
03:15:48,744 --> 03:15:52,670
[SPEAKER_14]: But tax was this issue that kept coming up actually for both of the candidates that you saw today.

2736
03:15:53,111 --> 03:15:59,860
[SPEAKER_14]: One interesting thing, the Prime Minister saying that he wasn't aware of this analysis, which is strange because we've been showing it for the last 24 hours.

2737
03:16:00,140 --> 03:16:01,302
[SPEAKER_14]: I know it's well thought of.

2738
03:16:01,282 --> 03:16:04,185
[SPEAKER_14]: or at least it's been considered in Conservative Party headquarters.

2739
03:16:04,445 --> 03:16:06,828
[SPEAKER_14]: This is showing you the tax burden in the UK.

2740
03:16:06,848 --> 03:16:08,229
[SPEAKER_14]: It goes all the way over to the 1940s.

2741
03:16:08,249 --> 03:16:09,911
[SPEAKER_14]: The higher this line is, the more we are taxed.

2742
03:16:09,931 --> 03:16:11,032
[SPEAKER_14]: And there's every tax.

2743
03:16:11,092 --> 03:16:11,893
[SPEAKER_14]: It's national insurance.

2744
03:16:12,193 --> 03:16:12,674
[SPEAKER_14]: It's VAT.

2745
03:16:12,714 --> 03:16:13,395
[SPEAKER_14]: It's the whole lot.

2746
03:16:13,695 --> 03:16:16,398
[SPEAKER_14]: It goes up a lot after the energy price shock and COVID.

2747
03:16:16,818 --> 03:16:19,441
[SPEAKER_14]: It's forecast to go higher in the next few years.

2748
03:16:19,681 --> 03:16:21,183
[SPEAKER_14]: We just had the Conservative manifesto.

2749
03:16:21,203 --> 03:16:27,870
[SPEAKER_14]: And the key issue, the key question, really, is whether those tax cuts talked about in the manifesto are going to bring that line so it starts going down.

2750
03:16:28,190 --> 03:16:31,153
[SPEAKER_14]: But actually, when you look at them, they're not.

2751
03:16:31,133 --> 03:16:36,720
[SPEAKER_14]: It's still going up, albeit less sharply than it is before, albeit not quite as steeply.

2752
03:16:37,041 --> 03:16:44,330
[SPEAKER_14]: But nonetheless, if you draw a line between where it gets to and back in history, this is the highest level it's going to be since the 1940s.

2753
03:16:44,811 --> 03:16:51,820
[SPEAKER_14]: So even after all of those manifesto pledges, it's worth saying a few other things that the prime minister talked about as well that's worth just kind of discussing.

2754
03:16:51,900 --> 03:16:56,586
[SPEAKER_14]: First of all, he talked about migration, saying that they were bringing down migration, this government.

2755
03:16:56,606 --> 03:17:00,972
[SPEAKER_14]: Well, if you look at what's happened to migration, I think for a lot of people, it won't quite feel like that.

2756
03:17:00,952 --> 03:17:05,304
[SPEAKER_14]: When those Brexit rules, post-Brexit rules, came into force, there was a very big increase in migration.

2757
03:17:05,524 --> 03:17:06,828
[SPEAKER_14]: And that's last year's estimate.

2758
03:17:06,868 --> 03:17:09,394
[SPEAKER_14]: It's been upgraded since then and upgraded again.

2759
03:17:09,836 --> 03:17:14,949
[SPEAKER_14]: So while it's certainly true it's coming down, it keeps getting revised ever higher.

2760
03:17:14,969 --> 03:17:16,834
[SPEAKER_14]: So there's a bit of caution about that.

2761
03:17:16,814 --> 03:17:23,264
[SPEAKER_14]: And there was a little bit, I don't know if I go so far as saying a porky pie, but it's one of those statistical things that you've got to be a bit cautious about.

2762
03:17:23,585 --> 03:17:30,937
[SPEAKER_14]: When the Prime Minister was talking about a record number of police officers, yeah, it's true in terms of the total number of police officers.

2763
03:17:30,957 --> 03:17:37,928
[SPEAKER_14]: Look, this bar here, the higher the bars are, the more police officers, that bar is definitely the highest on record, or at least going back to 2010.

2764
03:17:37,908 --> 03:17:40,492
[SPEAKER_14]: But adjust it by the numbers of people in the population.

2765
03:17:40,612 --> 03:17:40,933
[SPEAKER_14]: Look at this.

2766
03:17:40,953 --> 03:17:41,914
[SPEAKER_14]: We're going to do that adjustment.

2767
03:17:42,175 --> 03:17:44,418
[SPEAKER_14]: So that's per 1,000 head of the population.

2768
03:17:44,478 --> 03:17:45,921
[SPEAKER_14]: And now look at this line, OK?

2769
03:17:45,941 --> 03:17:47,283
[SPEAKER_14]: We'll go back, back, back, back, back.

2770
03:17:47,964 --> 03:17:51,049
[SPEAKER_14]: Oh, actually, it was higher pre-austerity, OK?

2771
03:17:51,089 --> 03:17:52,972
[SPEAKER_14]: So there were a few things to pick out there.

2772
03:17:53,192 --> 03:17:58,240
[SPEAKER_14]: But even when it came to Keir Starmer as well, some question marks in particular about tax and about spending.

2773
03:17:58,681 --> 03:18:03,949
[SPEAKER_14]: A big question, I think, that Beth talked about is, which taxes would you rise if you need to raise spending?

2774
03:18:03,929 --> 03:18:08,965
[SPEAKER_14]: Essentially, Keir Starmer is saying he didn't want to raise the rates of income tax, National Insurance, VAT.

2775
03:18:09,326 --> 03:18:13,279
[SPEAKER_14]: Obviously, there's question marks about whether you're going to be raising the total amount you're getting from it.

2776
03:18:13,600 --> 03:18:15,947
[SPEAKER_14]: But if you knock those out...

2777
03:18:16,147 --> 03:18:18,290
[SPEAKER_14]: Where is Labour actually going to raise those taxes?

2778
03:18:18,310 --> 03:18:21,173
[SPEAKER_14]: Obviously, we're going to get their manifesto tomorrow, so we might hear more about it.

2779
03:18:21,193 --> 03:18:24,297
[SPEAKER_14]: But that's why people are wondering about things like capital gains tax.

2780
03:18:24,317 --> 03:18:28,122
[SPEAKER_14]: They're wondering about fuel duties, because there's only so many things you can actually raise.

2781
03:18:28,682 --> 03:18:35,731
[SPEAKER_14]: But you do potentially need to raise them, because there is a big, some people call it conspiracy of silence, there's a big hole in the spending numbers in the future.

2782
03:18:35,891 --> 03:18:45,563
[SPEAKER_14]: While it looks like there's big increases in spending, well, relatively big increases in spending, and while it looks like protected parts of governments have big increases in the coming years,

2783
03:18:45,543 --> 03:18:53,195
[SPEAKER_14]: The unprotected parts of government, this is based on the numbers that we already have in the Office of Budget Responsibility, are very, very poor.

2784
03:18:53,215 --> 03:18:57,762
[SPEAKER_14]: A big fall of 3.5% following 20% real-terms cuts before.

2785
03:18:58,063 --> 03:19:05,755
[SPEAKER_14]: So there is still some extra spending needed to be found if you're going to bring spending back to levels that is going to improve public services.

2786
03:19:05,815 --> 03:19:07,798
[SPEAKER_14]: So still some big questions for Keir Starmer.

2787
03:19:07,818 --> 03:19:12,546
[SPEAKER_14]: Obviously, we get the manifesto from the Labour Party, and we'll bring you the full analysis of that as well.

2788
03:19:16,087 --> 03:19:17,170
[SPEAKER_46]: Ed, thank you.

2789
03:19:17,190 --> 03:19:20,621
[SPEAKER_46]: He didn't go as far as Porky Pies, but almost.

2790
03:19:21,263 --> 03:19:22,386
[SPEAKER_46]: Sam is still with me.

2791
03:19:22,407 --> 03:19:28,746
[SPEAKER_46]: Sam, what did we get to know about the vision for both potential governments, both sides?

2792
03:19:29,300 --> 03:19:37,851
[SPEAKER_25]: I think what we learn is that when it comes to that manifesto detail for both sides, we're in the middle of manifesto week, the public are paying really, really close attention.

2793
03:19:37,871 --> 03:19:41,796
[SPEAKER_25]: And the way that Rishi Sunak handled it and the audience reaction was really instructive.

2794
03:19:42,437 --> 03:19:47,083
[SPEAKER_25]: There were boos when he blamed the junior doctors for waiting lists.

2795
03:19:47,504 --> 03:19:48,625
[SPEAKER_25]: There was...

2796
03:19:48,605 --> 03:19:59,080
[SPEAKER_25]: disbelief when Beth Rigby read out the immigration figures all these years after Brexit when migration was meant to be taken back, we were meant to take back control of immigration.

2797
03:19:59,140 --> 03:20:08,474
[SPEAKER_25]: And there was disbelief again when Rishi Sunak tried to sort of reframe his promises on debt to say he would meet them in five years' time.

2798
03:20:08,734 --> 03:20:10,917
[SPEAKER_25]: I can tell you, I checked the original speech, that was never the promise.

2799
03:20:11,438 --> 03:20:16,165
[SPEAKER_25]: All of that went down very badly with the audience and it's quite clear that the precision

2800
03:20:16,145 --> 03:20:19,173
[SPEAKER_25]: promises of politicians are really important.

2801
03:20:19,193 --> 03:20:25,289
[SPEAKER_25]: So let's look at Keir Starmer, because at the moment, it's his to lose still, and that debate's done nothing to change that.

2802
03:20:26,031 --> 03:20:31,926
[SPEAKER_25]: And he was really, really cautious, not just in what he said, but what he didn't say.

2803
03:20:31,906 --> 03:20:42,361
[SPEAKER_25]: And it's quite clear from that interview with Beth Rigby that there is huge scope, actually, for Labour, for instance, to put up taxes, as Ed was saying.

2804
03:20:42,541 --> 03:20:48,810
[SPEAKER_25]: There was a great line from my colleague, you know, when you say you have no plans, that means you might well.

2805
03:20:49,431 --> 03:20:57,643
[SPEAKER_25]: And I think whether it's fuel duty, whether it's capital gains tax, it feels like, whether it's council tax re-evaluation,

2806
03:20:57,623 --> 03:21:01,171
[SPEAKER_25]: What we saw today was Keir Starmer refusing to rule those out.

2807
03:21:01,492 --> 03:21:10,431
[SPEAKER_25]: If there is the kind of black hole that Ed was just talking about, I think we learned tonight those options, raising those taxes, very much on the table.

2808
03:21:10,451 --> 03:21:12,215
[SPEAKER_46]: OK, Sam, thank you so much for your analysis.

2809
03:21:12,255 --> 03:21:13,438
[SPEAKER_46]: Thank you.

2810
03:21:13,418 --> 03:21:23,134
[SPEAKER_46]: Elsewhere on the campaign trail, the Green Party has launched its manifesto today and promised a £70 billion tax hike on the rich to fund the NHS.

2811
03:21:23,715 --> 03:21:34,532
[SPEAKER_46]: But the Institute for Fiscal Studies warns the party's tax plans would disincentivise work and investment and could increase borrowing by around £80 billion a year.

2812
03:21:35,133 --> 03:21:40,422
[SPEAKER_46]: Sky's political correspondent Girpreet Narwan reports now on the Greens' pitch to the voters.

2813
03:21:43,034 --> 03:21:48,141
[SPEAKER_48]: A break from the past with a fairer tax system to fund public services.

2814
03:21:50,485 --> 03:21:52,407
[SPEAKER_48]: That's the pitch from the Greens.

2815
03:21:52,948 --> 03:21:55,692
[SPEAKER_47]: We would overhaul our tax system to make it fairer.

2816
03:21:56,013 --> 03:22:00,259
[SPEAKER_47]: At the heart of this would be a tax on the very richest, the top 1% of people.

2817
03:22:00,639 --> 03:22:07,489
[SPEAKER_47]: Greens have the courage to say that we would change the tax system to make it fairer and make this investment possible.

2818
03:22:11,452 --> 03:22:18,401
[SPEAKER_48]: But these are significant numbers, £170 billion a year, and not just for the richest.

2819
03:22:19,182 --> 03:22:25,391
[SPEAKER_48]: The changes to national insurance mean that people earning over £50,000 a year will be paying more tax.

2820
03:22:25,411 --> 03:22:27,173
[SPEAKER_48]: That's one in five taxpayers.

2821
03:22:27,794 --> 03:22:30,257
[SPEAKER_48]: How do you justify that in a cost of living crisis?

2822
03:22:30,558 --> 03:22:35,905
[SPEAKER_15]: The cost of that for somebody on £55,000 a year would be an extra £5 a week.

2823
03:22:36,546 --> 03:22:39,089
[SPEAKER_15]: People earning under £50,000 would not be affected.

