03:42:17,474 --> 03:42:24,111
[SPEAKER_07]: you know, a little bit more exposed than they have been in other encounters or at question time, for example.

2999
03:42:24,833 --> 03:42:26,397
[SPEAKER_46]: Jack, what did you think about that?

3000
03:42:26,417 --> 03:42:30,748
[SPEAKER_46]: That it was sort of, I suppose, less combative because they insisted on not meeting each other?

3001
03:42:30,949 --> 03:42:31,490
[SPEAKER_19]: Yeah, completely.

3002
03:42:31,510 --> 03:42:33,475
[SPEAKER_19]: Obviously, different formats have different merits.

3003
03:42:33,455 --> 03:42:38,022
[SPEAKER_19]: One of the good things about this one for voters is that they couldn't pivot into an attack on the other.

3004
03:42:38,062 --> 03:42:41,588
[SPEAKER_19]: They couldn't take some flack and then sort of throw that back at the other person.

3005
03:42:41,628 --> 03:42:45,995
[SPEAKER_19]: Well, you know, you say I'm doing this, but the other person would do it twice as worse.

3006
03:42:46,476 --> 03:42:47,838
[SPEAKER_19]: And so they were exposed with this.

3007
03:42:48,179 --> 03:42:51,184
[SPEAKER_19]: Obviously, the Grimsby audience tonight didn't disappoint.

3008
03:42:51,905 --> 03:42:58,956
[SPEAKER_19]: These are the exact type of voters that they are going to have to win over if they're going to be wanting to become the next prime minister.

3009
03:42:58,936 --> 03:43:08,060
[SPEAKER_19]: obviously went Tory in 2019 with Boris Johnson's massive landslide, was Labour for a long time before that, big Brexit voting area, fishing town.

3010
03:43:08,641 --> 03:43:11,529
[SPEAKER_19]: It's all the sort of things that Keir Starmer is desperate to claw back.

3011
03:43:11,549 --> 03:43:13,975
[SPEAKER_19]: And at the moment, it looks like he's probably going to do that.

3012
03:43:13,955 --> 03:43:21,323
[SPEAKER_07]: And I've got to say, Grimsby gave it a really warm welcome, as we can see, cordoning off the area that was needed for this massive outside broadcast.

3013
03:43:21,343 --> 03:43:27,651
[SPEAKER_07]: A lot of people turning up outside earlier on when the leaders were arriving, demonstrations.

3014
03:43:27,671 --> 03:43:30,754
[SPEAKER_07]: So I think that, you know, one should take one's hat off to Grimsby as well.

3015
03:43:30,814 --> 03:43:35,299
[SPEAKER_07]: And again, that's something different from all the other election events we're seeing.

3016
03:43:35,680 --> 03:43:39,304
[SPEAKER_07]: This really gave you a flavour of real people and the politicians.

3017
03:43:39,284 --> 03:43:46,377
[SPEAKER_46]: They didn't go head-to-head, but Rishi Sunak, from my memory, did refer to Sir Keir Starmer.

3018
03:43:46,517 --> 03:43:48,240
[SPEAKER_46]: He hasn't got a plan for immigration.

3019
03:43:48,260 --> 03:43:50,244
[SPEAKER_46]: He's not saying what he wants to do.

3020
03:43:50,284 --> 03:43:55,133
[SPEAKER_46]: So he did try to make it combative, even though he wasn't in the same room with him at the same time.

3021
03:43:55,113 --> 03:43:56,275
[SPEAKER_19]: Oh yeah, he pulled no punches.

3022
03:43:57,056 --> 03:44:01,001
[SPEAKER_19]: He was often attacked on taxes, migration, NHS.

3023
03:44:01,021 --> 03:44:09,652
[SPEAKER_19]: He is saying that Keir Starmer's got no plan to do it, playing into that sort of Tory playbook that Keir Starmer is playing it very, very safe.

3024
03:44:09,852 --> 03:44:15,920
[SPEAKER_19]: He's not prepared to really put his head over the parapet and say big, bold things that he would do differently.

3025
03:44:16,081 --> 03:44:17,082
[SPEAKER_19]: He doesn't want to rock the boat.

3026
03:44:17,322 --> 03:44:18,724
[SPEAKER_19]: On the contrast, Sunak

3027
03:44:18,704 --> 03:44:19,645
[SPEAKER_19]: for the past few weeks.

3028
03:44:19,765 --> 03:44:21,427
[SPEAKER_19]: It's been a complete policy blitz.

3029
03:44:21,748 --> 03:44:30,018
[SPEAKER_19]: You've seen national service, you've seen tax cuts, stamp duty cuts, the manifesto was a festival of goodies and giveaways.

3030
03:44:30,619 --> 03:44:33,643
[SPEAKER_19]: Starmer, on the other hand, playing it much more safe, he doesn't want to rock the boat.

3031
03:44:33,883 --> 03:44:39,210
[SPEAKER_07]: But it was interesting that it actually took a long time for

3032
03:44:39,190 --> 03:44:41,394
[SPEAKER_07]: the Prime Minister to get on to that attack.

3033
03:44:41,414 --> 03:44:46,744
[SPEAKER_07]: It was almost as if he sort of woke up for, well, I've only got five minutes to go, I better get the attack lines in.

3034
03:44:47,104 --> 03:44:53,476
[SPEAKER_07]: And even then, as Jack said, he didn't try and repeat this rather controversial £2,000 tax claim.

3035
03:44:53,496 --> 03:44:55,760
[SPEAKER_07]: He just said, generally, Labour will put your taxes up.

3036
03:44:56,321 --> 03:44:57,383
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm cutting them.

3037
03:44:57,403 --> 03:45:00,068
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think one of the most telling moments

3038
03:45:00,048 --> 03:45:11,743
[SPEAKER_07]: in his time was when Beth Rigby raised what Ed Conway had done, actually analysing the spending plans, showing that they're going up, and he basically pleaded the Fifth Amendment.

3039
03:45:11,763 --> 03:45:12,624
[SPEAKER_07]: So he hadn't seen...

3040
03:45:12,744 --> 03:45:13,946
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't know anything about that.

3041
03:45:14,186 --> 03:45:15,147
[SPEAKER_46]: He hadn't seen the projections.

3042
03:45:15,728 --> 03:45:17,130
[SPEAKER_46]: Do you think he was a little bit...

3043
03:45:17,150 --> 03:45:20,054
[SPEAKER_46]: I mean, we'll have a look at the Sun front page.

3044
03:45:20,554 --> 03:45:23,238
[SPEAKER_46]: Grim evening, I think, their headline.

3045
03:45:23,658 --> 03:45:29,025
[SPEAKER_46]: Do you think the Prime Minister was a little bit subdued at the start of the...

3046
03:45:29,005 --> 03:45:33,700
[SPEAKER_46]: the debate because the D-Day commemorations, that was mentioned fairly early on.

3047
03:45:33,781 --> 03:45:40,551
[SPEAKER_19]: Yeah, and the polls show that this massive D-Day blunder, which he's rightly apologised for, has actually cut through with voters.

3048
03:45:41,132 --> 03:45:48,643
[SPEAKER_19]: And a lot of the time in Westminster, we can think that a row is dominating the country, whereas actually it's just pretty much contained within London.

3049
03:45:49,505 --> 03:45:54,472
[SPEAKER_19]: I think this was one of those moments where actually, wherever you are in the country, it really did cut through.

3050
03:45:54,492 --> 03:45:55,534
[SPEAKER_19]: It hurt.

3051
03:45:55,894 --> 03:45:57,557
[SPEAKER_19]: And I think Sunak has recognised that.

3052
03:45:57,577 --> 03:46:00,261
[SPEAKER_19]: And it was brought up today, I think twice,

3053
03:46:00,241 --> 03:46:03,966
[SPEAKER_19]: once by Beth Rigby and then once by a member of the audience, unprompted.

3054
03:46:04,306 --> 03:46:04,967
[SPEAKER_19]: It's clearly...

3055
03:46:06,789 --> 03:46:09,092
[SPEAKER_19]: It's clearly got him, you know, struggling at the moment.

3056
03:46:09,192 --> 03:46:13,798
[SPEAKER_19]: And I think that, you know, he's tried to neutralise that and put the row behind him, but it's just going to stay in people's minds.

3057
03:46:13,838 --> 03:46:19,485
[SPEAKER_19]: You know, as much as he tried to almost rip the plaster off early with that apology, it does something... You know, it is something that's got to him, I think.

3058
03:46:19,785 --> 03:46:25,152
[SPEAKER_07]: I think the worst moment for him was that lady, quite literally, Tom, who just said,

3059
03:46:25,132 --> 03:46:27,916
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm a lifelong Conservative voter.

3060
03:46:28,256 --> 03:46:31,541
[SPEAKER_07]: But she actually brought up the parties as well under Boris Johnson.

3061
03:46:32,002 --> 03:46:36,027
[SPEAKER_07]: Then she mentioned D-Day, and she just said, look, I can't support the Conservatives right now.

3062
03:46:36,087 --> 03:46:40,874
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think, according to the opinion polls, she's speaking for quite a lot of people in this country at the moment.

3063
03:46:40,954 --> 03:46:45,661
[SPEAKER_07]: And Sunak can only raise his hand.

3064
03:46:45,741 --> 03:46:51,148
[SPEAKER_07]: And she even made the point that Rishi Sunak had actually got a fixed penalty notice for the party.

3065
03:46:51,208 --> 03:46:53,772
[SPEAKER_07]: So she wasn't even letting him off the hook.

3066
03:46:54,325 --> 03:47:02,157
[SPEAKER_46]: Do you think, Jack, that he simply can't get away from this now, and that really has been the turning point in the election campaign, that he can't claw back from that?

3067
03:47:02,558 --> 03:47:03,519
[SPEAKER_19]: It's so difficult.

3068
03:47:03,539 --> 03:47:10,209
[SPEAKER_19]: If you look at the polls, they really haven't shifted since 2023, when he first became Prime Minister, or near enough, anyway.

3069
03:47:10,390 --> 03:47:16,519
[SPEAKER_19]: And as Lyndon Crosby, the great Tory strategist, used to say, you can't fatten a pig on market day.

3070
03:47:16,499 --> 03:47:27,476
[SPEAKER_19]: He's been trying, beyond hope, to put radical policies in the minds of voters that he hopes will make them sit up and consider voting for him.

3071
03:47:28,277 --> 03:47:33,084
[SPEAKER_19]: The problem is that for so many of them now, they are just putting their fingers in their ears, and they're not willing to listen.

3072
03:47:33,505 --> 03:47:35,308
[SPEAKER_19]: We've got three weeks to go until the election.

3073
03:47:35,328 --> 03:47:41,497
[SPEAKER_19]: Now, potentially, you might have some huge moment of significance that does something to shift the needle.

3074
03:47:41,818 --> 03:47:45,223
[SPEAKER_19]: But it's going to have to be bloody well big, because at the moment, they're not shifting at all.

3075
03:47:45,203 --> 03:47:49,491
[SPEAKER_07]: And the most significant thing, as you say, Gillian, has been the D-Day business.

3076
03:47:50,253 --> 03:47:59,269
[SPEAKER_07]: You know, to which he hasn't really got an answer, he just has to say, you know, I apologise, I hope you've got in your heart to forgive me, which is, you know, it's not a great way to be going into an election.

3077
03:47:59,290 --> 03:48:01,153
[SPEAKER_46]: Yes, and with the

3078
03:48:01,994 --> 03:48:06,803
[SPEAKER_46]: The D-Day commemorations, it wasn't a gaffe, it was a deliberate decision.

3079
03:48:06,823 --> 03:48:10,369
[SPEAKER_46]: I think that's what makes it very difficult for people to understand.

3080
03:48:10,730 --> 03:48:17,983
[SPEAKER_46]: And especially when he wasn't rushing back to do a live interview, it was a pre-recorded interview, played out tonight, incidentally.

3081
03:48:19,005 --> 03:48:20,207
[SPEAKER_46]: There didn't seem to be a real reason.

3082
03:48:20,227 --> 03:48:23,293
[SPEAKER_07]: There were actually complaints in that interview that things overran.

3083
03:48:23,794 --> 03:48:24,475
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

3084
03:48:24,455 --> 03:48:28,180
[SPEAKER_07]: So, compounding... You couldn't make the argument, he's trying to be polite, though.

3085
03:48:28,200 --> 03:48:31,884
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, he was being polite, but it's sort of revealing of his attitude, I think, to the whole thing.

3086
03:48:31,904 --> 03:48:34,187
[SPEAKER_19]: It's uncomfortable in the context of what happened, definitely.

3087
03:48:34,468 --> 03:48:46,463
[SPEAKER_19]: I think a lot of people, and the fact we're still talking about it obviously just goes to show how damaging it is to him, but I think that most people, when they saw the pictures and that beach, probably just thought that they just want to be there for that moment, you know.

3088
03:48:46,443 --> 03:48:58,004
[SPEAKER_19]: 80th anniversary for many of those veterans that stormed those beaches would be the last time and no matter what schedule you've got you probably just feel like no actually I have to be there rather than anywhere else and that's why it's so bruising for him.

3089
03:48:58,325 --> 03:49:00,969
[SPEAKER_46]: Just lastly on that Adam do you think we know the full story?

3090
03:49:01,009 --> 03:49:05,177
[SPEAKER_46]: Do you think that there might have been another reason that he had to to rush back?

3091
03:49:06,288 --> 03:49:07,049
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think so.

3092
03:49:07,149 --> 03:49:14,941
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, I think we know that this was discussed in advance, on the day, and afterwards, on all occasions.

3093
03:49:15,101 --> 03:49:28,802
[SPEAKER_07]: He just simply felt he didn't need to be at that final international commemoration with the two presidents and the Prime Minister, the Chancellor of Germany, you know, and it's just a misjudgment.

3094
03:49:29,761 --> 03:49:36,578
[SPEAKER_46]: Let's take a look at the Times, page six and seven, the headline there from Sunak, I'm doing my best.

3095
03:49:36,899 --> 03:49:42,994
[SPEAKER_46]: Jack, do you believe that the audience tonight thought that the Prime Minister was doing his very best?

3096
03:49:43,295 --> 03:49:44,617
[SPEAKER_19]: Well, I think they gave him a fair hearing.

3097
03:49:44,697 --> 03:49:50,844
[SPEAKER_19]: Obviously, it's incredibly tough for him because he made lots of pledges when he first became prime minister.

3098
03:49:50,864 --> 03:49:51,765
[SPEAKER_19]: I think it was January 23.

3099
03:49:51,866 --> 03:49:53,448
[SPEAKER_19]: He made five pledges.

3100
03:49:53,928 --> 03:49:56,992
[SPEAKER_19]: And Beth Rigby, quite rightly, took him through all of them.

3101
03:49:57,352 --> 03:49:59,475
[SPEAKER_19]: Now, you can say that you've cut inflation.

3102
03:49:59,795 --> 03:50:03,800
[SPEAKER_19]: How much credit you can take for that, obviously, people will lay at the door of the Bank of England a lot of the time.

3103
03:50:03,980 --> 03:50:04,822
[SPEAKER_19]: I don't think that's reasonable.

3104
03:50:05,402 --> 03:50:06,183
[SPEAKER_19]: But he's ticked that one.

3105
03:50:07,044 --> 03:50:07,665
[SPEAKER_19]: Growth?

3106
03:50:07,645 --> 03:50:12,210
[SPEAKER_19]: Obviously, he got a smidgen of growth last month.

3107
03:50:12,290 --> 03:50:16,534
[SPEAKER_19]: But actually, throughout his tenure, it has been pretty sluggish.

3108
03:50:17,154 --> 03:50:19,637
[SPEAKER_19]: And then you look at NHS waiting lists, hasn't made progress.

3109
03:50:19,957 --> 03:50:24,722
[SPEAKER_19]: Small boats, well, they're currently higher than they were last year, tracking higher coming across the channel.

3110
03:50:24,762 --> 03:50:31,489
[SPEAKER_19]: And so it's very difficult for him now to come out and say, my record has been a stonking success.

3111
03:50:31,589 --> 03:50:34,952
[SPEAKER_19]: Because as Beth put it to him, the numbers don't lie.

3112
03:50:34,932 --> 03:50:39,681
[SPEAKER_46]: But he did sort of make the admission that he knows it's been tough for people.

3113
03:50:39,781 --> 03:50:44,810
[SPEAKER_46]: He can understand their frustration and their anger, but things are improving.

3114
03:50:45,311 --> 03:50:51,422
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, but the problem is when you say I've done my best, the voters are at liberty to say, well,

3115
03:50:51,402 --> 03:50:53,104
[SPEAKER_07]: not good enough.

3116
03:50:53,224 --> 03:51:04,320
[SPEAKER_07]: And that in a sense was the position which he was in, having to make the best of a grim situation, which it was quite clear he wasn't the only one who had contributed to that.

3117
03:51:04,800 --> 03:51:09,246
[SPEAKER_07]: Although people did seem in the audience quite willing to personalise it.

3118
03:51:09,867 --> 03:51:17,157
[SPEAKER_07]: Again, picked up on his support for Brexit and the consequences of it, which obviously in this area, which was

3119
03:51:17,137 --> 03:51:24,348
[SPEAKER_07]: heavily Brexit, blamed the European Union in part for the destruction, or in large part, of the fishing industry.

3120
03:51:24,888 --> 03:51:38,128
[SPEAKER_07]: But when it came up, that question from Beth Rigby linking immigration and the increase in immigration to what was promised at the time of Brexit, the audience went silent.

3121
03:51:38,208 --> 03:51:39,630
[SPEAKER_07]: There were gasps at some point.

3122
03:51:39,730 --> 03:51:40,832
[SPEAKER_07]: They were persuaded.

3123
03:51:41,605 --> 03:51:49,276
[SPEAKER_19]: There was a point there where Beth Rigby read out the numbers for the three years after Brexit, net migration was about 1.9 million, a figure the PM didn't seem to know.

3124
03:51:49,777 --> 03:51:52,741
[SPEAKER_19]: And then the three years before Brexit, it was about 800,000.

3125
03:51:52,801 --> 03:52:03,377
[SPEAKER_19]: Now, many people in this area would have voted for Brexit for one of the key pillars of it was to control migration and to control the numbers coming in here using freedoms which leaving the EU afforded us.

3126
03:52:03,357 --> 03:52:12,351
[SPEAKER_19]: And the fact that the Tories, for 14 years, David Cameron in the tens of thousands, after that Boris Johnson pledged to get it down, Rishi Sunak's now pledging to get it down again.

3127
03:52:12,431 --> 03:52:14,935
[SPEAKER_19]: People just don't believe them anymore on that.

3128
03:52:14,955 --> 03:52:18,620
[SPEAKER_19]: And they've pledged some big radical policy about a net migration annual cap.

3129
03:52:19,301 --> 03:52:21,304
[SPEAKER_19]: Problem is, for a lot of people, they just think it's too little, too late.

3130
03:52:21,845 --> 03:52:29,517
[SPEAKER_46]: Yeah, he did actually go a bit further, the furthest we've heard him so far, and gave a date for the first flight to Rwanda, didn't he?

3131
03:52:30,256 --> 03:52:33,680
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, he's always been saying that it's going to happen, take place in July.

3132
03:52:33,740 --> 03:52:39,407
[SPEAKER_07]: But then the question came back to him, well, in that case, why didn't you wait for it to prove that this policy is working?

3133
03:52:39,707 --> 03:52:47,376
[SPEAKER_07]: I think we've seen another survey today showing that there's a great deal of scepticism about politics and trust.

3134
03:52:48,177 --> 03:52:54,745
[SPEAKER_07]: And you can say it now, but if you're saying it before it happens, people just don't seem to be prepared to take it on trust.

3135
03:52:55,332 --> 03:52:57,094
[SPEAKER_46]: But he did, I think it was the 24th.

3136
03:52:57,114 --> 03:52:57,954
[SPEAKER_19]: 24th of July, yeah.

3137
03:52:58,034 --> 03:52:59,236
[SPEAKER_46]: Is that the first time we've heard that?

3138
03:52:59,356 --> 03:53:01,478
[SPEAKER_19]: It came out in high court documents last week.

3139
03:53:01,558 --> 03:53:06,382
[SPEAKER_19]: But it's the first time I think he has openly admitted that that is exactly what he wants to send flights to Rwanda.

3140
03:53:06,702 --> 03:53:10,866
[SPEAKER_19]: Obviously challenged as well about the timing of the election and the timing of Rwanda flights.

3141
03:53:10,886 --> 03:53:19,394
[SPEAKER_19]: Because the smart money in Westminster for a long time is that he would call an election in the autumn to allow time for Rwanda flights to get off the ground.

3142
03:53:19,774 --> 03:53:24,158
[SPEAKER_19]: He could then point to maybe some dip in numbers coming across the channel.

3143
03:53:24,138 --> 03:53:27,702
[SPEAKER_19]: and could say to Keir Starmer, look, I have a plan to stop small boats.

3144
03:53:27,962 --> 03:53:28,643
[SPEAKER_19]: What are you going to do?

3145
03:53:28,663 --> 03:53:30,605
[SPEAKER_19]: Because you said you'd ask this on day one.

3146
03:53:31,607 --> 03:53:39,896
[SPEAKER_19]: So the fact he didn't do that is seen by a lot of people as a tacit admission that potentially, actually, he doesn't think it would lead to a dip in the numbers.

3147
03:53:39,916 --> 03:53:42,639
[SPEAKER_19]: And then, actually, he would have egg on his face if that happened.

3148
03:53:42,659 --> 03:53:49,547
[SPEAKER_19]: Now, he's obviously committing to that, doggedly, and he's still going into it, the election, with that Rwanda pledge.

3149
03:53:51,449 --> 03:53:53,672
[SPEAKER_19]: The problem is now is that it might never happen.

3150
03:53:54,344 --> 03:53:56,347
[SPEAKER_46]: Adam, take us to the Mail.

3151
03:53:57,048 --> 03:53:59,733
[SPEAKER_46]: Keir Starmer, prospect of a super majority.

3152
03:53:59,773 --> 03:54:12,774
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, this is actually very interesting because this comes out of an interview on the radio, I think it was on Times Radio, that the Defence Secretary Grant Shapps did this morning in advance of today's event.

3153
03:54:12,795 --> 03:54:14,918
[SPEAKER_07]: And he was saying

3154
03:54:14,898 --> 03:54:20,008
[SPEAKER_07]: don't allow Labour a massive majority because it would be very bad for democracy.

3155
03:54:20,068 --> 03:54:23,895
[SPEAKER_07]: It's always bad when a party has a big majority.

3156
03:54:23,995 --> 03:54:30,628
[SPEAKER_07]: And that was taken by many people as being really a tacit admission that even someone a senior in the

3157
03:54:30,608 --> 03:54:39,260
[SPEAKER_07]: Conservative Party's Grant Shapps doesn't think they are going to win and is now in the business of trying to talk down the size of the defeat of the Conservatives.

3158
03:54:39,901 --> 03:54:44,929
[SPEAKER_07]: Certainly, a lot of the focus of Conservative policies have seemed to be aiming at that.

3159
03:54:45,830 --> 03:54:56,245
[SPEAKER_07]: The message coming out of Conservative headquarters was, Grant Shapps shouldn't have said this, he overspoke a bit, even though they have been sending out advertisements

3160
03:54:56,225 --> 03:54:57,667
[SPEAKER_07]: putting out the same message.

3161
03:54:58,208 --> 03:55:10,568
[SPEAKER_07]: But now you're seeing the Daily Mail absolutely go for it and simply repeat what he said, that, you know, you don't want to create what they're calling a one-party socialist state.

3162
03:55:10,668 --> 03:55:23,329
